{"title_page": "National Bureau of Investigation (Ukraine)", "text_new": "{{Notability|Organization|date=November 2019}}\nThe '''National Bureau of Investigation''' ([[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]: \u041d\u0411\u0420, \u041d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0411\u044e\u0440\u043e \u0420\u043e\u0437\u0441\u043b\u0456\u0434\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u044c \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438) was an organization in [[Ukraine]] dedicated to prejudicial investigation on especially dangerous crimes. Its most recent inception was formed in 2005 by President [[Viktor Yushchenko]]. Subordinated to the [[General Prosecutor of Ukraine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://old.kmu.gov.ua/kmu/control/en/publish/printable_article?art_id=14289947|title=National Bureau of Investigation will specialize in prejudicial investigation, Security Service Chairman believes|last=|first=|date=22 March 2005|website=Web-Portal of Ukrainian Government|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:National Bureau Of Investigation (Ukraine)}}\n[[Category:Ukrainian intelligence agencies]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement agencies of Ukraine]]\n\n\n{{Ukraine-poli-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Notability|Organization|date=November 2019}}\nThe '''National Bureau of Investigation''' ([[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]: \u041d\u0411\u0420, \u041d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0411\u044e\u0440\u043e \u0420\u043e\u0437\u0441\u043b\u0456\u0434\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u044c \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438) was an organization in [[Ukraine]] dedicated to prejudicial investigation on especially dangerous crimes. Its most recent inception was formed in 2005 by President [[Viktor Yushchenko]]. Subordinated to the [[General Prosecutor of Ukraine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://old.kmu.gov.ua/kmu/control/en/publish/printable_article?art_id=14289947|title=National Bureau of Investigation will specialize in prejudicial investigation, Security Service Chairman believes|last=|first=|date=22 March 2005|website=Web-Portal of Ukrainian Government|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:National Bureau Of Investigation (Ukraine)}}\n[[Category:Ukrainian intelligence agencies]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement agencies of Ukraine]]\n\n\n{{Ukraine-poli-stub}}\n\n== References ==\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Bureau_of_Investigation_(Ukraine)"}
{"title_page": "Coat of arms of Argentina", "text_new": "{{short description|Coat of arms}}\n{{Infobox coat of arms\n|name             = Coat of arms of Argentina\n|image            = Coat of arms of Argentina.svg\n|image_width      = 150\n|middle           = \n|middle_width     = \n|middle_caption   = \n|lesser           = \n|lesser_width     = \n|lesser_caption   = \n|armiger          = [[Argentine Republic]]\n|year_adopted     = 1944 (1813)\n|crest            = A [[Sun of May]] [[or (heraldry)|or]]\n|torse            = \n|shield           = Party per fess azure and argent, in base two arms throughout fessways, the hands shaking and holding a pike paleways proper ensigned on the top with a Phrygian cap gules.\n|supporters       = \n|compartment      = \n|motto            = \n|orders           = \n|other_elements   = Around the shield two sprigs of laurel vert tied together in base by a ribbon azure charged with a fess argent \n|earlier_versions = \n|use              = \n}}\n\nThe '''coat of arms of the Argentine Republic''' or  '''Argentine shield''' <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.national-symbol.com/national-country-symbols-of-argentina.html |title=National country symbols of Argentina |publisher=National-symbol.com |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929112654/http://www.national-symbol.com/national-country-symbols-of-argentina.html |archive-date=September 29, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ({{lang-es|Escudo de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina}}) was established in its current form in 1944, but has its origins in the seal of the General Constituent Assembly of 1813.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://infoleg.mecon.gov.ar/infolegInternet/anexos/55000-59999/59311/norma.htm |title=Que el Escudo, la Bandera, el Himno y su letra son los s\u00edmbolos de la soberan\u00eda de la Naci\u00f3n. |publisher=Ministry of Economy and Production |language=Spanish |trans-title=That the Coat of Arms, the Flag, the Anthem, and its lyrics are the symbols of the sovereignty of the Nation. |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |quote=En adelante se adoptar\u00e1 como representaci\u00f3n del escudo argentino, la reproducci\u00f3n fiel del Sello que us\u00f3 la Soberana Asamblea General Constituyente de la Provincias Unidas del R\u00edo de la Plata, el mismo que \u00e9sta orden\u00f3 en sesi\u00f3n de 12 de marzo de 1813, usase el Poder Ejecutivo. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201192240/http://infoleg.mecon.gov.ar/infolegInternet/anexos/55000-59999/59311/norma.htm |archivedate=February 1, 2014 }}</ref> It is supposed that it was chosen quickly because of the existence of a decree signed on February 22 sealed with the symbol.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.casarosada.gov.ar/nuestro-pais/simbolos-nacionales |title=S\u00edmbolos Nacionales |publisher=Presidency of the Argentine Nation |language=Spanish |trans-title=National Symbols |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |quote=Como testimonio de ello, se conservan dos cartas de ciudadan\u00eda expedidas por la Asamblea el 22 de Febrero de 1813, donde figura el Escudo estampado en lacre: una de ellas se conserva en el Museo Hist\u00f3rico Nacional, extendida a favor de Don Antonio Olavaria, y est\u00e1 firmada por el presidente del cuerpo, general Carlos Mar\u00eda de Alvear, y el secretario, Don Hip\u00f3lito Vieytes.}}</ref> The first mention of it in a public document dates to March 12 of that same year, in which it is stated that the seal had to be used by the executive power, that is, the second triumvirate.\nOn April 13 the National Assembly coined the new silver and gold coins, each with the seal of the assembly on the reverse, and on April 27 the coat of arms became a national emblem. Although the coat of arms is not currently shown on flags, the [[Buenos Aires]]-born military leader [[Manuel Belgrano]] ordered to paint it over the flag he gave to the city of [[San Salvador de Jujuy]], and during the [[Argentine War of Independence]] [[Flag of the Andes|most flags had the coat of arms]].\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Coat of arms of the United Provinces of the Rio de la Plata.svg|thumb|160px|left|Seal of the General Constituent Assembly of 1813.]]\n[[File:Proto-escudo-dibujado.JPG|thumb|160px|left|Seal of a French group in the National Assembly, around 1793.]]\nIt is unknown who designed the coat of arms. It is often mentioned that there were three men involved: Alvear, Monteagudo, and Vieytes, but it is known that a few years before, President [[Bernardino Rivadavia]] asked the Peruvian Antonio Isidoro Castro to create an Argentine coat of arms; however, the two schemes have never been found.\n\nThe coat of arms is a figure, in which at the top we find the gold-yellowed [[Sun of May]], also found on the [[flag of Argentina]]. The rising sun symbolizes the rising of Argentina, as described in the first version of the [[Argentine National Anthem]], ''{{lang|es|se levanta a la faz de la tierra una nueva y gloriosa naci\u00f3n}}'', meaning \"a new and glorious nation rises to the surface of the Earth\". It must be noticed how the verb \"rise\", in English and Spanish can be used to describe the motion of the Sun.\n\nIn the center ellipse there are two shaking hands, connoting the unity of the [[provinces of Argentina]]. The hands come together to hold a pike, which represents power and willingness to defend freedom, epitomized by the [[Phrygian cap]] on the top of the spear.\n\nThe blue and white colors are symbols of the Argentine people and the same colors of the Argentine flag. Those derive from those utilised in the cockade promoting liberation from Spain, in the May Revolution in 1810, which in turn came about from the colours of the Borbonic dynasty.\n{{Css Image Crop|Image = Argentina 1828 8 Escudos.jpg |bSize = 361|cWidth = 175|cHeight = 175|oTop = 5|oLeft = 182|Location = right|Description = Coat of Arms of the General Constituent Assembly of Argentina depicted on the eight escudo gold coin.}}\nThe hands stand for friendship, peace, unity, and brotherhood. The pike is brown (wooden), and the Phrygian cap is red, like the traditional French liberty cap. The proximity of the hands and the Phrygian cap, in addition to their individual meanings, represent the national motto of [[Argentina]], ''{{lang|es|en uni\u00f3n y libertad}}'' (\"in unity and freedom\"), and illustrate the idea that in unity (the hands) there is power (the pike), and in power there is freedom (the Phrygian cap).\n\nThe Phrygian cap was typically worn by the inhabitants of [[Phrygia]], in the Anatolian peninsula, and is commonly mistaken for being a [[Pileus (hat)|Pileus]]. The Pileus was a hat that in ancient Rome became a symbol of freed slaves, who were touched by their owners with a wooden pike before setting them free.\nLaurel is another classical symbol. At the end of the [[ancient Olympic Games]] (and also the [[2004 Summer Olympics]]), the winner was given a laurel crown, and since then it has symbolized triumph and glory.\n\n==Provincial shields==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|+<big>Argentina's provincial shields</big>\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Escudo de la Ciudad de Buenos Aires.svg|100px]]<br />[[Coat of arms of Buenos Aires|Autonomous City of Buenos Aires]]\n! [[File:Coat of arms of the Buenos Aires Province.png|100px]]<br />[[Buenos Aires Province]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Catamarca.png|100px]]<br />[[Catamarca Province|Catamarca]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de C\u00f3rdoba.svg|100px]]<br />[[C\u00f3rdoba Province, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Corrientes.svg|100px]]<br />[[Corrientes Province|Corrientes]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia del Chaco.svg|100px]]<br />[[Chaco Province|Chaco]]\n! [[File:Chubut COA.jpg|100px]]<br />[[Chubut Province|Chubut]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Entre R\u00edos.svg|100px]]<br />[[Entre R\u00edos Province|Entre R\u00edos]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Formosa.svg|100px]]<br />[[Formosa Province|Formosa]]\n! [[File:Escudo COA Jujuy province argentina.PNG|100px]]<br />[[Jujuy Province|Jujuy]]\n! [[File:Arpampa.PNG|100px]]<br />[[La Pampa Province|La Pampa]]\n! [[File:Coat of arms of La Rioja province.png|100px]]<br />[[La Rioja Province, Argentina|La Rioja]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Mendoza province COA.png|100px]]<br />[[Mendoza Province|Mendoza]]\n! [[File:Esc mis.jpg|100px]]<br />[[Misiones Province|Misiones]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Neuqu\u00e9n.svg|100px]]<br />[[Neuqu\u00e9n Province|Neuqu\u00e9n]]\n! [[File:Escudo de R\u00edo Negro nuevo.JPG|100px]]<br />[[R\u00edo Negro Province|R\u00edo Negro]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Salta.svg|100px]]<br />[[Salta Province|Salta]]\n! [[File:Arsjuan2.PNG|100px]]<br />[[San Juan Province, Argentina|San Juan]]\n! [[File:Escudo de San Luis ARG.png|100px]]<br />[[San Luis Province|San Luis]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Santa Cruz.svg|100px]]<br />[[Santa Cruz Province, Argentina|Santa Cruz]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Arstafe2.gif|100px]]<br />[[Santa Fe Province|Santa Fe]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Santiago del Estero.png|100px]]<br />[[Santiago del Estero Province|Santiago del Estero]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Tierra del Fuego.svg|100px]]<br />[[Tierra del Fuego Province|Province of Tierra del Fuego, Antartica and South Atlantic Islands]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Tucum\u00e1n.svg|100px]]<br />[[Tucum\u00e1n Province|Tucum\u00e1n]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==See also==\n*[[Coat of arms of Buenos Aires Province]]\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category|National coats of arms of Argentina}}\n*{{cite book | title = S\u00edmbolos Nacionales de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina | publisher = Comisi\u00f3n Administradora de la Biblioteca del Congreso de la Naci\u00f3n | year = 1997 | location = Buenos Aires | language = Spanish | isbn = 950-691-036-7 }}\n\n{{National emblems of Argentina}}\n{{Coats of arms of South America}}\n\n[[Category:National symbols of Argentina]]\n[[Category:National coats of arms|Argentina]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with suns|Argentina]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with sunrays|Argentina]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with the Phrygian cap|Argentina]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with hands|Argentina]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Coat of arms}}\n{{Infobox coat of arms\n|name             = Coat of arms of Argentina\n|image            = Coat of arms of Argentina.svg\n|image_width      = 150\n|middle           = \n|middle_width     = \n|middle_caption   = \n|lesser           = \n|lesser_width     = \n|lesser_caption   = \n|armiger          = [[Argentine Republic]]\n|year_adopted     = 1944 (1813)\n|crest            = A [[Sun of May]] [[or (heraldry)|or]]\n|torse            = \n|shield           = Party per fess azure and argent, in base two arms throughout fessways, the hands shaking and holding a pike paleways proper ensigned on the top with a Phrygian cap gules.\n|supporters       = \n|compartment      = \n|motto            = \n|orders           = \n|other_elements   = Around the shield two sprigs of laurel vert tied together in base by a ribbon azure charged with a fess argent \n|earlier_versions = \n|use              = \n}}\n\nThe '''coat of arms of the Argentine Republic''' or  '''Argentine shield''' <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.national-symbol.com/national-country-symbols-of-argentina.html |title=National country symbols of Argentina |publisher=National-symbol.com |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929112654/http://www.national-symbol.com/national-country-symbols-of-argentina.html |archive-date=September 29, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ({{lang-es|Escudo de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina}}) was established in its current form in 1944, but has its origins in the seal of the General Constituent Assembly of 1813.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://infoleg.mecon.gov.ar/infolegInternet/anexos/55000-59999/59311/norma.htm |title=Que el Escudo, la Bandera, el Himno y su letra son los s\u00edmbolos de la soberan\u00eda de la Naci\u00f3n. |publisher=Ministry of Economy and Production |language=Spanish |trans-title=That the Coat of Arms, the Flag, the Anthem, and its lyrics are the symbols of the sovereignty of the Nation. |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |quote=En adelante se adoptar\u00e1 como representaci\u00f3n del escudo argentino, la reproducci\u00f3n fiel del Sello que us\u00f3 la Soberana Asamblea General Constituyente de la Provincias Unidas del R\u00edo de la Plata, el mismo que \u00e9sta orden\u00f3 en sesi\u00f3n de 12 de marzo de 1813, usase el Poder Ejecutivo. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201192240/http://infoleg.mecon.gov.ar/infolegInternet/anexos/55000-59999/59311/norma.htm |archivedate=February 1, 2014 }}</ref> It is supposed that it was chosen quickly because of the existence of a decree signed on February 22 sealed with the symbol.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.casarosada.gov.ar/nuestro-pais/simbolos-nacionales |title=S\u00edmbolos Nacionales |publisher=Presidency of the Argentine Nation |language=Spanish |trans-title=National Symbols |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |quote=Como testimonio de ello, se conservan dos cartas de ciudadan\u00eda expedidas por la Asamblea el 22 de Febrero de 1813, donde figura el Escudo estampado en lacre: una de ellas se conserva en el Museo Hist\u00f3rico Nacional, extendida a favor de Don Antonio Olavaria, y est\u00e1 firmada por el presidente del cuerpo, general Carlos Mar\u00eda de Alvear, y el secretario, Don Hip\u00f3lito Vieytes.}}</ref> The first mention of it in a public document dates to March 12 of that same year, in which it is stated that the seal had to be used by the executive power, that is, the second triumvirate.\nOn April 13 the National Assembly coined the new silver and gold coins, each with the seal of the assembly on the reverse, and on April 27 the coat of arms became a national emblem. Although the coat of arms is not currently shown on flags, the [[Buenos Aires]]-born military leader [[Manuel Belgrano]] ordered to paint it over the flag he gave to the city of [[San Salvador de Jujuy]], and during the [[Argentine War of Independence]] [[Flag of the Andes|most flags had the coat of arms]].\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Coat of arms of the United Provinces of the Rio de la Plata.svg|thumb|160px|left|Seal of the General Constituent Assembly of 1813.]]\n[[File:Proto-escudo-dibujado.JPG|thumb|160px|left|Seal of a French group in the National Assembly, around 1793.]]\nIt is unknown who designed the coat of arms. It is often mentioned that there were three men involved: Alvear, Monteagudo, and Vieytes, but it is known that a few years before, President [[Bernardino Rivadavia]] asked the Peruvian Antonio Isidoro Castro to create an Argentine coat of arms; however, the two schemes have never been found.\n\nThe coat of arms is a figure, in which at the top we find the gold-yellowed [[Sun of May]], also found on the [[flag of Argentina]]. The rising sun symbolizes the rising of Argentina, as described in the first version of the [[Argentine National Anthem]], ''{{lang|es|se levanta a la faz de la tierra una nueva y gloriosa naci\u00f3n}}'', meaning \"a new and glorious nation rises to the surface of the Earth\". It must be noticed how the verb \"rise\", in English and Spanish can be used to describe the motion of the Sun.\n\nIn the center ellipse there are two shaking hands, connoting the unity of the [[provinces of Argentina]]. The hands come together to hold a pike, which represents power and willingness to defend freedom, epitomized by the [[Phrygian cap]] on the top of the spear.\n\nThe blue and white colors are symbols of the Argentine people and the same colors of the Argentine flag. Those derive from those utilised in the cockade promoting liberation from Spain, in the May Revolution in 1810, which in turn came about from the colours of the Borbonic dynasty.\n{{Css Image Crop|Image = Argentina 1828 8 Escudos.jpg |bSize = 361|cWidth = 175|cHeight = 175|oTop = 5|oLeft = 182|Location = right|Description = Coat of Arms of the General Constituent Assembly of Argentina depicted on the eight escudo gold coin.}}\nThe hands stand for friendship, peace, unity, and brotherhood. The pike is brown (wooden), and the Phrygian cap is red, like the traditional French liberty cap. The proximity of the hands and the Phrygian cap, in addition to their individual meanings, represent the national motto of [[Argentina]], ''{{lang|es|en uni\u00f3n y libertad}}'' (\"in unity and freedom\"), and illustrate the idea that in unity (the hands) there is power (the pike), and in power there is freedom (the Phrygian cap).\n\nThe Phrygian cap was typically worn by the inhabitants of [[Phrygia]], in the Anatolian peninsula, and is commonly mistaken for being a [[Pileus (hat)|Pileus]]. The Pileus was a hat that in ancient Rome became a symbol of freed slaves, who were touched by their owners with a wooden pike before setting them free.\nLaurel is another classical symbol. At the end of the [[ancient Olympic Games]] (and also the [[2004 Summer Olympics]]), the winner was given a laurel crown, and since then it has symbolized triumph and glory.\n\n==Provincial shields==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|+<big>Argentina's provincial shields</big>\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Escudo de la Ciudad de Buenos Aires.svg|100px]]<br />[[Coat of arms of Buenos Aires|Autonomous City of Buenos Aires]]\n! [[File:Coat of arms of the Buenos Aires Province.png|100px]]<br />[[Buenos Aires Province]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Catamarca.png|100px]]<br />[[Catamarca Province|Catamarca]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de C\u00f3rdoba.svg|100px]]<br />[[C\u00f3rdoba Province, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Corrientes.svg|100px]]<br />[[Corrientes Province|Corrientes]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia del Chaco.svg|100px]]<br />[[Chaco Province|Chaco]]\n! [[File:Chubut COA.jpg|100px]]<br />[[Chubut Province|Chubut]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Entre R\u00edos.svg|100px]]<br />[[Entre R\u00edos Province|Entre R\u00edos]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Formosa.svg|100px]]<br />[[Formosa Province|Formosa]]\n! [[File:Escudo COA Jujuy province argentina.PNG|100px]]<br />[[Jujuy Province|Jujuy]]\n! [[File:Arpampa.PNG|100px]]<br />[[La Pampa Province|La Pampa]]\n! [[File:Coat of arms of La Rioja province.png|100px]]<br />[[La Rioja Province, Argentina|La Rioja]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Mendoza province COA.png|100px]]<br />[[Mendoza Province|Mendoza]]\n! [[File:Esc mis.jpg|100px]]<br />[[Misiones Province|Misiones]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Neuqu\u00e9n.svg|100px]]<br />[[Neuqu\u00e9n Province|Neuqu\u00e9n]]\n! [[File:Escudo de R\u00edo Negro nuevo.JPG|100px]]<br />[[R\u00edo Negro Province|R\u00edo Negro]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Salta.svg|100px]]<br />[[Salta Province|Salta]]\n! [[File:Arsjuan2.PNG|100px]]<br />[[San Juan Province, Argentina|San Juan]]\n! [[File:Escudo de San Luis ARG.png|100px]]<br />[[San Luis Province|San Luis]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Santa Cruz.svg|100px]]<br />[[Santa Cruz Province, Argentina|Santa Cruz]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n! [[File:Arstafe2.gif|100px]]<br />[[Santa Fe Province|Santa Fe]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Santiago del Estero.png|100px]]<br />[[Santiago del Estero Province|Santiago del Estero]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Tierra del Fuego.svg|100px]]<br />[[Tierra del Fuego Province, Argentina Tierra del /Land of Fire , Antarctica and South Atlantic Islands\" , or  [[Argentine Antarctica|Antarctica]] and South Atlantic Islands]]\n! [[File:Escudo de la Provincia de Tucum\u00e1n.svg|100px]]<br />[[Tucum\u00e1n Province|Tucum\u00e1n]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==See also==\n*[[Coat of arms of Buenos Aires Province]]\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category|National coats of arms of Argentina}}\n*{{cite book | title = S\u00edmbolos Nacionales de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina | publisher = Comisi\u00f3n Administradora de la Biblioteca del Congreso de la Naci\u00f3n | year = 1997 | location = Buenos Aires | language = Spanish | isbn = 950-691-036-7 }}\n\n{{National emblems of Argentina}}\n{{Coats of arms of South America}}\n\n[[Category:National symbols of Argentina]]\n[[Category:National coats of arms|Argentina]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with suns|Argentina]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with sunrays|Argentina]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with the Phrygian cap|Argentina]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with hands|Argentina]]\n", "name_user": "Spiritual Sausage", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Argentina"}
{"title_page": "French brig Victorieuse (1794)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{| {{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = \n| Ship caption = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header= \n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag=[[Image:Civil and Naval Ensign of France.svg|40px|border|French Navy Ensign]]\n| Ship name = ''Victorieuse''\n| Ship namesake = \n| Ship owner =\n| Ship operator = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship builder = \n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched =1 April 1794 \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship commissioned = \n| Ship decommissioned = \n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n| Ship renamed = \n| Ship captured = 25 August 1795 \n| Ship fate = \n| Ship status = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=title\n|Ship country=Great Britain\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag| Kingdom of Great Britain|naval}}\n| Ship name = \n| Ship namesake = \n| Ship owner =\n| Ship operator = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship builder = \n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched = \n| Ship acquired = 25 August 1795 by capture\n| Ship commissioned = \n| Ship decommissioned = \n| Ship honours = [[Naval General Service Medal (1847)|Naval General Service Medal]] with clasp \"Egypt\"\n| Ship out of service = \n| Ship renamed = \n| Ship captured = \n| Ship fate = [[Ship breaking|Broken up]] July 1807\n| Ship status = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = {{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=284}}\n| Ship class = {{sclass-|Belliqueuse|brig}}\n| Ship tons burthen= ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]])\n| Ship length = \n| Ship beam = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = \n| Ship hold depth = \n| Ship propulsion = \n| Ship sail plan = [[Brig]]\n| Ship complement = 130\n| Ship armament = *At capture: 14 \u00d7 12-pounder guns\n*Royal Navy (1795): 12 \u00d7 12-pounder guns + 2 \u00d7 32-pounder [[carronades]]\n*Royal Navy (1800): 14 \u00d7 24-pounder carronades + 2 \u00d7 9-pounder guns\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Victorieuse''''' was a brig of the French Navy, launched at Honfleur in 1794. The British [[Royal Navy]] captured in August 1795 and took her into service as HMS ''Victorieuse''. She captured several privateers and two forts in the Caribbean and then served briefly in the Mediterranean before she was broken up in 1807.\n\n==French Navy==\nBetween 4 April 1794 and 27 December, ''Victorieuse'', ''lieutenant de vaisseau'' Sala\u00fcn, commanding, was at [[Honfleur]]. She escorted convoys between Dunkirk and points north, returning to [[Ostend]]. Next, she made a transit from Havre to Dunkirk. Lastly, she cruised in the North Sea, returning to Ostend.\n \nFrom 24 April 1795 to 20 June ''Victorieuse'' was still under Sala\u00fcn's command. She was at Dunkirk. Then she cruised in the North Sea. Next she transported personnel from Dunkirk to [[Kristiansand]] and returned from there. She assumed her station in Dunkirk [[roadstead|Roads]].   \n\n'''Capture:''' On 25 August 1795 Admiral [[Adam Duncan, 1st Viscount Duncan|Duncan's]] squadron captured two French Navy brigs off the Texel: {{ship|French brig|Suffisante|1793|2}} and ''Victorieuse''. ''Suffisante'' was armed with fourteen 8&6-pounder guns; ''Victorieuse'', still under Sala\u00fcn's command, was armed with fourteen 12-pounder guns. The two brigs had just set out to cruise the North Sea.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=5 August 1795|issue=13808|page=884}}</ref> The Royal Navy took both into service.\n\n==Royal Navy==\nCommander Robert Winthrop commissioned ''Victoreuse'' in October 1796. Commander Jemmet Mainwaring replaced Winthrop and sailed her on 22 February 1796 to the Leeward Islands.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=284}} \n\nNext, ''Victorieuse'' was at the attack on [[Morne Fortune|St. Lucia]] on 24 May 1796. She was one of the vessels covering the landing of troops at Choc Bay.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=21 June 1796|issue=3903|page=593}}</ref> She shared in the prize money paid in June 1800.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=7 June 1800|issue=15265|page=623}}</ref>\n\nIn November Commander Edward Dickson (or Dickinson) replaced Mainwaring.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=284}} ''Victorieuse'' captured three merchantmen in January\u2013February 1797 and sent them into Grenada.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=29 April 1797|issue=14005|page=388}}</ref>\n\n*17 January: brig ''Philipina'', Y. Da Deson de Gebe, master. She was sailing from St. Sebastian's to La Gueria, with a cargo of bale goods, flour, etc. when captured off Trinidad.\n*27 January: schooner ''Laerdolorey'', M. Herboy, master. She was sailing from the Main to Port au Spain, with a cargo of bullocks, when detained off the [[Gulf of Paria]].\n*2 February: brig ''La Bregen'', J. Delgade, master. she was sailing from Rio Plata to Havana with a cargo of beef, pork, and tallow, when captured off Trinidad.\n\nIn February 1797 ''Victorieuse'' helped blockade [[Port of Spain|Port d'Espagne]] during Admiral [[Henry Harvey]]'s [[Invasion of Trinidad (1797)|capture of Trinidad]].<ref>{{London Gazette|date=27 March 1797|issue=13995|page=286}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 September ''Victorieuse'' captured the French privateer ''Etoile du Matin''. ''Etoile du Matin'' was armed with two guns and had a crew of 30 men.{{sfnp|Norie|1827|p=489}}\n\n''Victorieuse'' was escorting a convoy from Trinidad to St Kitts and was to leeward of Guadeloupe when on 7 May 1798 she sighted two French privateers. They made for her, seeking to take her by boarding. One was a schooner of 12 guns and 80 men, and the other a sloop of 6 guns and 51 men. ''Victorieuse'' engaged them, forcing the sloop st [[striking the colours|strike]] as she was so damaged that she was in danger of sinking. The schooner then fled; Dickson believed that she too was damaged and had suffered heavy casualties. ''Victorieuse'' did not pursue as she was unwilling to leave the convoy. The captured sloop turned out to be ''Brutus'', of Guadeloupe. She was under the command of Citizen Roufel and was 10 days out of Guadeloupe but had not taken anything. She had had four men killed and four wounded before she struck. ''Victorieuse'' had no casualties.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=23 June 1798|issue=15035|page=572}}</ref>\n\n*20 June: ''Victorieuse'' captured ''Trois Couleurs'' off Trinidad. ''Trois Couleurs'' was  a privateer of four guns and 33 men.{{sfnp|Norie|1827|p=495}}\n*11 November: ''Victorieuse'' destroyed a schooner of 20 guns and 80 men that was sheltering under the guns of batteries at [[R\u00edo Caribe]].{{sfnp|Norie|1827|p=496}}\n\nIn December, having received intelligence that three French privateers were operating off the Spanish Main (what is now is now Venezuela's Caribbean coast), Dickson decided to ensure that the privateers, if the Royal Navy chased them, would not be able to shelter under the guns of the Spanish forts at Rio Caribe and [[Car\u00fapano|Gurupano]]. ''Victorieuse'' sailed in company with {{HMS|Zephyr|1795|2}}. They also had on board a detachment of 40 men from the Royal Rangers. On 2 December ''Victorieuse''  destroyed the Dutch privateer ''Proserpine'', from [[Cura\u00e7ao|Caracoa]], on Cape Three Points on the Spanish Main. ''Proserpine'' was armed with two guns and had a crew of 15 men. At 2am on 3 December Dickson landed the troops and some seamen to attack the fort at Rio Caribe from the rear, while ''Victorieuse'' and ''Zephyr'' attacked from the front. At daylight the fort's commander sent word that he would surrender the fort without resisting. The landing party took away the fort's guns and reembarked. The British then arrived off Gurupano at 4pm, where they found a French privateer in the harbour. The Spanish commander of the two forts refused to surrender and stated that he would protect the privateer. At 5pm the Rangers landed, together with 30 seamen from the brigs. The landing party attacked the forts from the rear while the brigs came up and fired on the front. The landing party took the lower fort within 10 minutes. The upper fort was taken in five minutes. The landing party of 70 men had overcome some 300 defenders. The brigs also took possession of the French privateer, which was armed with six guns and had a crew of 80 men. Dickson took the guns and ammunition out of the forts before destroying them, and sent the privateer to Trinidad.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=2 March 1799|issue=15112|pages=209\u2013210}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1799 ''Victorieuse'' captured a small Spanish schooner carrying salt from [[Margarita Island|Margaritta]] to the [[Oronoque River]].<ref>{{London Gazette|date=2 July 1799|issue=15154|page=669}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1800 Commander John Richards replaced Dickson.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=284}} ''Victorieuse'' then served in the Mediterranean.\n\n''Victorieuse'' served in the fleet under Admiral Lord [[George Elphinstone, 1st Viscount Keith|Keith]] in the Egyptian campaign between 8 March and 2 September 1801.  \n\n''Victorieuse'' was among the vessels that shared in the proceeds of the capture of ''Rosa'' on 26 February 1801.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15507|page=877|date=17 August 180}}</ref>\n\nThen on 18 April ''Victorieuse'', Captain J.  Richards, captured the French [[trabaccalo]] ''Madona de Lorette'', which was sailing from Ancona to Alexandria.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15428|page=1386|date=17 November 1801}}</ref> \n\n{{HMS|Peterel|1794|2}} and ''Victorieuse'' drove a Greek [[Ca\u00efque|caicque]] onshore on 11 March at Tower of Arabs. The vessel was on her way to Alexandria.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15428|page=1385|date=17 November 1801}}</ref> \n\nOn 9 June ''Victorieuse'' captured the [[polacca]] ''Vierge de Niegrs''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15551|page=993|date=14 September 1802}}</ref> \n\nHer service in the Egyptian campaign qualified ''Victorieuse'' for prize money for the campaign.{{refn|A first-class share of the prize money awarded in April 1823 was worth [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]34 2[[shilling|s]] 4[[pence|d]]; a fifth-class share, that of a seaman, was worth 3s 11\u00bdd. The amount was small as the total had to be shared between 79 vessels and the entire army contingent.<ref>{{London Gazette|page=633 |issue=17915|date=3 April 1823}}</ref>|group=Note}} In 1850 the Admiralty awarded the Naval General Service Medal with clasp \"Egypt\" to claimants from the crews of the vessels that had served in the navy's Egyptian campaign, including ''Victorieuse''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=21077|pages=791\u2013792|date=15 March 1850}}</ref>\n\n==Fate==\nThe Navy paid off ''Victorieuse'' in October 1803. She was broken up in July 1807.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=284}}\n\n==Notees, citations, and references==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n'''References'''\n* {{cite book|first=J.W.|last=Norie|title=The naval gazetteer, biographer and chronologist; containing a history of the late wars from ... 1793 to ... 1801; and from ... 1803 to 1815, and continued, as to the biographical part to the present time|location=London|publisher=C.Wilson|year=1827|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Rif|last=Winfield|title=British Warships in the Age of Sail 1793\u20131817: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates|publisher=Seaforth Publishing|year=2008|isbn=1-86176-246-1|ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book|last1=Winfield|first1=Rif|last2=Roberts|first2=Stephen S.|year=2015|title=French Warships in the Age of Sail 1786\u20131861: Design Construction, Careers and Fates|publisher=Seaforth Publishing|location=|isbn=978-1-84832-204-2|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:1794 ships]]\n[[Category:Brigs of the French Navy]]\n[[Category:Captured ships]]\n[[Category:Brigs of the Royal Navy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{| {{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = \n| Ship caption = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header= \n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag=[[Image:Civil and Naval Ensign of France.svg|40px|border|French Navy Ensign]]\n| Ship name = ''Victorieuse''\n| Ship namesake = \n| Ship owner =\n| Ship operator = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship builder = \n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched =1 April 1794 \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship commissioned = \n| Ship decommissioned = \n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n| Ship renamed = \n| Ship captured = 25 August 1795 \n| Ship fate = \n| Ship status = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=title\n|Ship country=Great Britain\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag| Kingdom of Great Britain|naval}}\n| Ship name = \n| Ship namesake = \n| Ship owner =\n| Ship operator = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship builder = \n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched = \n| Ship acquired = 25 August 1795 by capture\n| Ship commissioned = \n| Ship decommissioned = \n| Ship honours = [[Naval General Service Medal (1847)|Naval General Service Medal]] with clasp \"Egypt\"\n| Ship out of service = \n| Ship renamed = \n| Ship captured = \n| Ship fate = [[Ship breaking|Broken up]] July 1807\n| Ship status = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = {{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=284}}\n| Ship class = {{sclass-|Belliqueuse|brig}}\n| Ship tons burthen= ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]])\n| Ship length = \n| Ship beam = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = \n| Ship hold depth = \n| Ship propulsion = \n| Ship sail plan = [[Brig]]\n| Ship complement = 130\n| Ship armament = *At capture: 14 \u00d7 12-pounder guns\n*Royal Navy (1795): 12 \u00d7 12-pounder guns + 2 \u00d7 32-pounder [[carronades]]\n*Royal Navy (1800): 14 \u00d7 24-pounder carronades + 2 \u00d7 9-pounder guns\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Victorieuse''''' was a brig of the French Navy, launched at Honfleur in 1794. The British [[Royal Navy]] captured in August 1795 and took her into service as HMS ''Victorieuse''. She captured several privateers and two forts in the Caribbean and then served briefly in the Mediterranean before she was broken up in 1807.\n\n==French Navy==\nBetween 4 April 1794 and 27 December, ''Victorieuse'', ''lieutenant de vaisseau'' Sala\u00fcn, commanding, was at [[Honfleur]]. She escorted convoys between Dunkirk and points north, returning to [[Ostend]]. Next, she made a transit from Havre to Dunkirk. Lastly, she cruised in the North Sea, returning to Ostend.\n \nFrom 24 April 1795 to 20 June ''Victorieuse'' was still under Sala\u00fcn's command. She was at Dunkirk. Then she cruised in the North Sea. Next she transported personnel from Dunkirk to [[Kristiansand]] and returned from there. She assumed her station in Dunkirk [[roadstead|Roads]].   \n\n'''Capture:''' On 25 August 1795 Admiral [[Adam Duncan, 1st Viscount Duncan|Duncan's]] squadron captured two French Navy brigs off the Texel: {{ship|French brig|Suffisante|1793|2}} and ''Victorieuse''. ''Suffisante'' was armed with fourteen 8&6-pounder guns; ''Victorieuse'', still under Sala\u00fcn's command, was armed with fourteen 12-pounder guns. The two brigs had just set out to cruise the North Sea.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=5 August 1795|issue=13808|page=884}}</ref> The Royal Navy took both into service.\n\n==Royal Navy==\nCommander Robert Winthrop commissioned ''Victoreuse'' in October 1796. Commander Jemmet Mainwaring replaced Winthrop and sailed her on 22 February 1796 to the Leeward Islands.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=284}} \n\nNext, ''Victorieuse'' was at the attack on [[Morne Fortune|St. Lucia]] on 24 May 1796. She was one of the vessels covering the landing of troops at Choc Bay.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=21 June 1796|issue=3903|page=593}}</ref> She shared in the prize money paid in June 1800.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=7 June 1800|issue=15265|page=623}}</ref>\n\nIn November Commander Edward Dickson (or Dickinson) replaced Mainwaring.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=284}} ''Victorieuse'' captured three merchantmen in January\u2013February 1797 and sent them into Grenada.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=29 April 1797|issue=14005|page=388}}</ref>\n\n*17 January: brig ''Philipina'', Y. Da Deson de Gebe, master. She was sailing from St. Sebastian's to La Gueria, with a cargo of bale goods, flour, etc. when captured off Trinidad.\n*27 January: schooner ''Laerdolorey'', M. Herboy, master. She was sailing from the Main to Port au Spain, with a cargo of bullocks, when detained off the [[Gulf of Paria]].\n*2 February: brig ''La Bregen'', J. Delgade, master. she was sailing from Rio Plata to Havana with a cargo of beef, pork, and tallow, when captured off Trinidad.\n\nIn February 1797 ''Victorieuse'' helped blockade [[Port of Spain|Port d'Espagne]] during Admiral [[Henry Harvey]]'s [[Invasion of Trinidad (1797)|capture of Trinidad]].<ref>{{London Gazette|date=27 March 1797|issue=13995|page=286}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 September ''Victorieuse'' captured the French privateer ''Etoile du Matin''. ''Etoile du Matin'' was armed with two guns and had a crew of 30 men.{{sfnp|Norie|1827|p=489}}\n\n''Victorieuse'' was escorting a convoy from Trinidad to St Kitts and was to leeward of Guadeloupe when on 7 May 1798 she sighted two French privateers. They made for her, seeking to take her by boarding. One was a schooner of 12 guns and 80 men, and the other a sloop of 6 guns and 51 men. ''Victorieuse'' engaged them, forcing the sloop st [[striking the colours|strike]] as she was so damaged that she was in danger of sinking. The schooner then fled; Dickson believed that she too was damaged and had suffered heavy casualties. ''Victorieuse'' did not pursue as she was unwilling to leave the convoy. The captured sloop turned out to be ''Brutus'', of Guadeloupe. She was under the command of Citizen Roufel and was 10 days out of Guadeloupe but had not taken anything. She had had four men killed and four wounded before she struck. ''Victorieuse'' had no casualties.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=23 June 1798|issue=15035|page=572}}</ref>\n\n*20 June: ''Victorieuse'' captured ''Trois Couleurs'' off Trinidad. ''Trois Couleurs'' was  a privateer of four guns and 33 men.{{sfnp|Norie|1827|p=495}}\n*11 November: ''Victorieuse'' destroyed a schooner of 20 guns and 80 men that was sheltering under the guns of batteries at [[R\u00edo Caribe]].{{sfnp|Norie|1827|p=496}}\n\nIn December, having received intelligence that three French privateers were operating off the Spanish Main (what is now is now Venezuela's Caribbean coast), Dickson decided to ensure that the privateers, if the Royal Navy chased them, would not be able to shelter under the guns of the Spanish forts at Rio Caribe and [[Car\u00fapano|Gurupano]]. ''Victorieuse'' sailed in company with {{HMS|Zephyr|1795|2}}. They also had on board a detachment of 40 men from the Royal Rangers. On 2 December ''Victorieuse''  destroyed the Dutch privateer ''Proserpine'', from [[Cura\u00e7ao|Caracoa]], on Cape Three Points on the Spanish Main. ''Proserpine'' was armed with two guns and had a crew of 15 men. At 2am on 3 December Dickson landed the troops and some seamen to attack the fort at Rio Caribe from the rear, while ''Victorieuse'' and ''Zephyr'' attacked from the front. At daylight the fort's commander sent word that he would surrender the fort without resisting. The landing party took away the fort's guns and reembarked. The British then arrived off Gurupano at 4pm, where they found a French privateer in the harbour. The Spanish commander of the two forts refused to surrender and stated that he would protect the privateer. At 5pm the Rangers landed, together with 30 seamen from the brigs. The landing party attacked the forts from the rear while the brigs came up and fired on the front. The landing party took the lower fort within 10 minutes. The upper fort was taken in five minutes. The landing party of 70 men had overcome some 300 defenders. The brigs also took possession of the French privateer, which was armed with six guns and had a crew of 80 men. Dickson took the guns and ammunition out of the forts before destroying them, and sent the privateer to Trinidad.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=2 March 1799|issue=15112|pages=209\u2013210}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1799 ''Victorieuse'' captured a small Spanish schooner carrying salt from [[Margarita Island|Margaritta]] to the [[Oronoque River]].<ref>{{London Gazette|date=2 July 1799|issue=15154|page=669}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1800 Commander John Richards replaced Dickson.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=284}} ''Victorieuse'' then served in the Mediterranean.\n\n''Victorieuse'' served in the fleet under Admiral Lord [[George Elphinstone, 1st Viscount Keith|Keith]] in the Egyptian campaign between 8 March and 2 September 1801.  \n\n''Victorieuse'' was among the vessels that shared in the proceeds of the capture of ''Rosa'' on 26 February 1801.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15507|page=877|date=17 August 180}}</ref>\n\nThen on 18 April ''Victorieuse'', Captain J.  Richards, captured the French [[trabaccalo]] ''Madona de Lorette'', which was sailing from Ancona to Alexandria.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15428|page=1386|date=17 November 1801}}</ref> \n\n{{HMS|Peterel|1794|2}} and ''Victorieuse'' drove a a Greek [[Ca\u00efque|caicque]] onshore on 11 March at Tower of Arabs. The vessel was on her way to Alexandria.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15428|page=1385|date=17 November 1801}}</ref> \n\nOn 9 June ''Victorieuse'' captured the [[polacca]] ''Vierge de Niegrs''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15551|page=993|date=14 September 1802}}</ref> \n\nHer service in the Egyptian campaign qualified ''Victorieuse'' for prize money for the campaign.{{refn|A first-class share of the prize money awarded in April 1823 was worth [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]34 2[[shilling|s]] 4[[pence|d]]; a fifth-class share, that of a seaman, was worth 3s 11\u00bdd. The amount was small as the total had to be shared between 79 vessels and the entire army contingent.<ref>{{London Gazette|page=633 |issue=17915|date=3 April 1823}}</ref>|group=Note}} In 1850 the Admiralty awarded the Naval General Service Medal with clasp \"Egypt\" to claimants from the crews of the vessels that had served in the navy's Egyptian campaign, including ''Victorieuse''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=21077|pages=791\u2013792|date=15 March 1850}}</ref>\n\n==Fate==\nThe Navy paid off ''Victorieuse'' in October 1803. She was broken up in July 1807.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=284}}\n\n==Notees, citations, and references==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n'''References'''\n* {{cite book|first=J.W.|last=Norie|title=The naval gazetteer, biographer and chronologist; containing a history of the late wars from ... 1793 to ... 1801; and from ... 1803 to 1815, and continued, as to the biographical part to the present time|location=London|publisher=C.Wilson|year=1827|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Rif|last=Winfield|title=British Warships in the Age of Sail 1793\u20131817: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates|publisher=Seaforth Publishing|year=2008|isbn=1-86176-246-1|ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book|last1=Winfield|first1=Rif|last2=Roberts|first2=Stephen S.|year=2015|title=French Warships in the Age of Sail 1786\u20131861: Design Construction, Careers and Fates|publisher=Seaforth Publishing|location=|isbn=978-1-84832-204-2|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:1794 ships]]\n[[Category:Brigs of the French Navy]]\n[[Category:Captured ships]]\n[[Category:Brigs of the Royal Navy]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_brig_Victorieuse_(1794)"}
{"title_page": "Diego Trujillo", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Diego Trujillo\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1960|6|30|mf=yes}}\n| birth_name = Diego Trujillo Dangond\n| birth_place = [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]]\n| occupation = [[Actor]]\n| alias = \n| years_active = 1993\u2013present\n| spouse = \n| children = 3\n}}\n\n'''Diego Trujillo Dangond''' (born June 30, 1960) is a [[Colombia]]n film and television actor.\n\n==Life and career==\nTrujillo studied at the [[Gimnasio Moderno]] school in Bogot\u00e1, where he occasionally did theatre as a hobby. After graduating, he decided to study architecture at the [[Pilot University of Colombia]], and worked in that profession for twelve years.\n\nIn television he has had a long history and since 1993 has acted in many [[telenovela]]s.\n\nHis film career began in 2000 with his work in [[Taylor Hackford]]'s film ''[[Proof of Life]]'', starring [[Meg Ryan]] and [[Russell Crowe]], in which he was cast because of his excellent command of English.\n\nIn 2013, Trujillo was cast as [[Walter Blanco]] in the Spanish-language remake of ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' entitled ''[[Met\u00e1stasis]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brodzinsky|first=Sibylla|title=Breaking Bad lives on in Colombian remake Met\u00e1stasis|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/07/breaking-bad-colombia-remake-metastasis|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=12 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===TV===\n* [[De pies a cabeza (serie de TV)|De pies a cabeza]] \u2013 (1993)\n* [[La maldici\u00f3n del para\u00edso]] \u2013 (1993) \n* [[Tiempos dif\u00edciles]] \u2013 (1995) \n* [[Mascarada]] \u2013 (1995) \n* [[Perro amor (telenovela de 1998)|Perro amor]] \u2013 (1998) \n* [[El fiscal (TV series)]] \u2013 (1999) \n* [[Por qu\u00e9 diablos]] \u2013 (1999) \n* [[Brujeres]] \u2013 (2000) \n* [[Pobre Pablo]] \u2013 (2001) \n* [[La coste\u00f1a y el cachaco]] \u2013 (2003) Simon (El Italiano)\n* [[Todos quieren con Marilyn]] \u2013 (2004) \n* [[Protagonistas de Novela]] 3 \"El juicio final\" \u2013 (2004) \n* [[Los Reyes (telenovela)|Los Reyes]] \u2013 (2005) Emilio Iriarte De las Casas\n* [[Amas de casa desesperadas (Colombia)|Amas de casa desesperadas]] \u2013 (2006\u201308)\n* [[Tiempo final (Fox)|Tiempo final]] \u2013 (2007)\n* [[Infieles an\u00f3nimos]] \u2013 (2007) \n* [[El poder del diez]] \u2013 (2008) Presentador\n* [[El Capo (Colombia)]] (2009)\n* ''[[A coraz\u00f3n abierto (Colombian TV series)|A coraz\u00f3n abierto]]'' (2010)\n* [[La Pola (telenovela)]] (2010) Domingo Garc\u00eda\n* [[\u00bfD\u00f3nde Carajos esta Uma\u00f1a?]] (2012) Patricio Uma\u00f1a\n* ''[[Met\u00e1stasis]]'' (2014) Walter Blanco\n\n===Movies===\n* [[Prueba de vida]] \u2013 (2000)\n* [[Tres hombres tres mujeres]] \u2013 (2003)\n* [[Cuando rompen las olas]] \u2013 (2005)\n* [[El trato]] \u2013 (2005)\n* [[Martillo (pel\u00edcula)|Martillo]] \u2013 (2005) \n* [[Dios los junta y ellos se separan]] \u2013 (2006)\n* [[P\u00f3cima (pel\u00edcula)|P\u00f3cima]] \u2013 (2008) Tomas Herrera\n* [[Riverside (pel\u00edcula)|Riverside]] \u2013 (2009)\n\n===Theater===\n* En carne propia \u2013 (1996)\n* Muelle oeste \u2013 (2001)\n* La noche \u00e1rabe \u2013 (2006)\n* Cita a ciegas (2007)\n* \u00a1Qu\u00e9 desgracia tan infinita! \u2013 (2009) Stand up comedy\n* El cr\u00e9dito - (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0874197|Diego Trujillo}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trujillo, Diego}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Bogot\u00e1]]\n[[Category:Colombian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Colombian male telenovela actors]]\n[[Category:Colombian male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Colombian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Colombian male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Diego Trujillo\n| image = Diego Trujillo en 2017.jpg\n| caption = Trujillo in 2017\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1960|6|30|mf=yes}}\n| birth_name = Diego Trujillo Dangond\n| birth_place = [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]]\n| occupation = [[Actor]]\n| alias = \n| years_active = 1993\u2013present\n| spouse = \n| children = 3\n}}\n\n'''Diego Trujillo Dangond''' (born June 30, 1960) is a [[Colombia]]n film and television actor.\n\n==Life and career==\nTrujillo studied at the [[Gimnasio Moderno]] school in Bogot\u00e1, where he occasionally did theatre as a hobby. After graduating, he decided to study architecture at the [[Pilot University of Colombia]], and worked in that profession for twelve years.\n\nIn television he has had a long history and since 1993 has acted in many [[telenovela]]s.\n\nHis film career began in 2000 with his work in [[Taylor Hackford]]'s film ''[[Proof of Life]]'', starring [[Meg Ryan]] and [[Russell Crowe]], in which he was cast because of his excellent command of English.\n\nIn 2013, Trujillo was cast as [[Walter Blanco]] in the Spanish-language remake of ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' entitled ''[[Met\u00e1stasis]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brodzinsky|first=Sibylla|title=Breaking Bad lives on in Colombian remake Met\u00e1stasis|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/07/breaking-bad-colombia-remake-metastasis|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=12 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===TV===\n* [[De pies a cabeza (serie de TV)|De pies a cabeza]] \u2013 (1993)\n* [[La maldici\u00f3n del para\u00edso]] \u2013 (1993) \n* [[Tiempos dif\u00edciles]] \u2013 (1995) \n* [[Mascarada]] \u2013 (1995) \n* [[Perro amor (telenovela de 1998)|Perro amor]] \u2013 (1998) \n* [[El fiscal (TV series)]] \u2013 (1999) \n* [[Por qu\u00e9 diablos]] \u2013 (1999) \n* [[Brujeres]] \u2013 (2000) \n* [[Pobre Pablo]] \u2013 (2001) \n* [[La coste\u00f1a y el cachaco]] \u2013 (2003) Simon (El Italiano)\n* [[Todos quieren con Marilyn]] \u2013 (2004) \n* [[Protagonistas de Novela]] 3 \"El juicio final\" \u2013 (2004) \n* [[Los Reyes (telenovela)|Los Reyes]] \u2013 (2005) Emilio Iriarte De las Casas\n* [[Amas de casa desesperadas (Colombia)|Amas de casa desesperadas]] \u2013 (2006\u201308)\n* [[Tiempo final (Fox)|Tiempo final]] \u2013 (2007)\n* [[Infieles an\u00f3nimos]] \u2013 (2007) \n* [[El poder del diez]] \u2013 (2008) Presentador\n* [[El Capo (Colombia)]] (2009)\n* ''[[A coraz\u00f3n abierto (Colombian TV series)|A coraz\u00f3n abierto]]'' (2010)\n* [[La Pola (telenovela)]] (2010) Domingo Garc\u00eda\n* [[\u00bfD\u00f3nde Carajos esta Uma\u00f1a?]] (2012) Patricio Uma\u00f1a\n* ''[[Met\u00e1stasis]]'' (2014) Walter Blanco\n\n===Movies===\n* [[Prueba de vida]] \u2013 (2000)\n* [[Tres hombres tres mujeres]] \u2013 (2003)\n* [[Cuando rompen las olas]] \u2013 (2005)\n* [[El trato]] \u2013 (2005)\n* [[Martillo (pel\u00edcula)|Martillo]] \u2013 (2005) \n* [[Dios los junta y ellos se separan]] \u2013 (2006)\n* [[P\u00f3cima (pel\u00edcula)|P\u00f3cima]] \u2013 (2008) Tomas Herrera\n* [[Riverside (pel\u00edcula)|Riverside]] \u2013 (2009)\n\n===Theater===\n* En carne propia \u2013 (1996)\n* Muelle oeste \u2013 (2001)\n* La noche \u00e1rabe \u2013 (2006)\n* Cita a ciegas (2007)\n* \u00a1Qu\u00e9 desgracia tan infinita! \u2013 (2009) Stand up comedy\n* El cr\u00e9dito - (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0874197|Diego Trujillo}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trujillo, Diego}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Bogot\u00e1]]\n[[Category:Colombian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Colombian male telenovela actors]]\n[[Category:Colombian male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Colombian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Colombian male actors]]\n", "name_user": "EvergreenFir", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(vandalism)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diego_Trujillo"}
