{"title_page": "Bartley Crum", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Bartley Crum\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_upright      = \n| landscape          = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         = Bartley Cavanaugh Crum\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1900|11|28}}\n| birth_place        = [[Sacramento, California]], USA\n| baptised           = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1959|12|9|1900|11|28}}\n| death_place        = [[New York City]]\n| death_cause        = suicide by overdose\n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| burial_place       = <!-- may be used instead of resting_place and resting_place_coordinates (displays \"Burial place\" as label) -->\n| burial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments          = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| siglum             = \n| citizenship        = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of California at Berkeley]]\n| occupation         = attorney, activist\n| years_active       = 1933-1959\n| era                = [[New Deal]], [[McCarthyism]]\n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| known_for          = [[Hollywood Ten]] defense, [[Rita Hayworth]] divorce\n| notable_works      = ''Behind the Silken Curtain'' (1947)\n| style              = \n| home_town          = San Francisco\n| party              = Republican, Independent Republicans for Roosevelt\n| movement           = \n| opponents          = \n| boards             = [[National Lawyers Guild]], [[Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry]], Lawyers Committee for Justice in Palestine\n| spouse             = Anna Gertrude Bosworth\n| partner            = <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = [[Patricia Bosworth]], Bartley Crum Jr.\n| parents            = James Henry Crum,  Emma Cavanaugh\n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| awards             = \n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Bartley Crum''', AKA Bartley C. Crum (1900 \u2013 December 9, 1959), was a prominent mid-20th-century American lawyer, who became prominent as a member of the [[Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry]], his book on that experience, and for defending targets of the [[House Un-American Activities Committee|HUAC]], particularly the [[Hollywood Ten]] and [[Paul Robeson]].<ref name=LastParty>\n{{cite news\n  | title = The Last Party\n  | newspaper = New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/27/books/the-last-party.html\n  | date = 27 April 1997\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Anything>\n{{cite book \n | first=Patricia \n | last=Bosworth \n | authorlink=Patricia Bosworth \n | title=Anything Your Little Heart Desires: An American Family Story \n | publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]] \n | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G_mPAAAAMAAJ \n | pages = 69-83 (Wilkie 1940), 89 (SF address), 94 (NLG), 94-8 (Wilkie 1944), 100 (FPRC), 118-9 (Nike's), 124-136 (Wilkie 1944), 146-7 (FDR 1944), 158-161 (UN opens), 161 (2626 Green ST), 161-2 (Louise Bransten), 162 (FBI surveillance), 162-3 (JAFRC), 163-4 (Palm Court), 165 (1945 year-end snapshot), 167 (appointment AACIP), 167-201 (AACIP experience), 168 (Henderson), 171 (Henderson), 175 (Henderson), 177 (British surveillance), 183 (Vienna), 197 (Henderson), 200-201 (Henderson), 201 (American Christian Palestine Committee)\n | date=1997 \n | accessdate = 17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite news\n  | title = Bartley C. Crum, Lawyer, 59, Dies; Acted in Cases Involving Civil Rights -- Won Million in Rita Hayworth Divorce\n  | newspaper = New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1959/12/11/archives/bartley-c-crum-lawyer-59-dies-acted-in-cases-involving-civil-rights.html\n  | page = 33\n  | date = 11 December 1959\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nBartley Cavanaugh Crum was born on November 28, 1900, in [[Sacramento, California]], the son of James Henry Crum and  Emma Cavanaugh.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=Whos>\n{{cite book\n| title = Who's who in Commerce and Industry, Volume 11\n| publisher = Marquis Who's Who\n| url = https://books.google.ca/books?id=I-YdAQAAIAAJ&q=emma+cavanaugh+mary+crum&dq=emma+cavanaugh+mary+crum&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjnxv287c7oAhVJmuAKHc-IAaUQ6AEwAHoECAUQAQ\n| page = 278\n| date = 1959\n| accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref>  He was raised [[Roman Catholic]].<ref name=LastParty/>  In 1922, he received a BA and in 1924 a JD from the [[University of California at Berkeley]].<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Career==\n\nCrum started his career as a teach of English and International Law at UC/Berkeley.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n===Neylan and Hearst===\n[[File:HearstAbout1910.jpg|thumb|right|In the 1920s, Crum worked for XXX, whose major client was media magnate [[William Randolph Hearst]] (here {{circa|1910}})]]\nIn 1924, Crum joined the law offices of [[John Francis Neylan]], chief attorney for newspaper magnate [[William Randolph Hearst]].  As a Hearst lawyer, Crum helped defend [[Clarence Darrow]] in 1933.  \"Darrow taught me more law than I had known before,\" Crum said later.<ref name=NYTobit/>  \n\n===Kenny and NLG===\n[[File:Harry Bridges.png|thumb|right|Crum helped defend against the deportation of his friend [[Harry Bridges]] in 1939]]\nIn 1938, Crum left Neylan and set a law office with Philip Ehrich and David A. Silver.  In 1938 or 1939, he joined the [[National Lawyers Guild]] at the behest of friend and fellow liberal Republican [[Robert W. Kenny]].  In 1939, Crum helped defend [[Harry Bridges]] in one of his deportation hearings.<ref name=NYTobit/>  He also criticized the US policy during the [[Spanish Civil War]] and its aftermath.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n===Wendell Willkie===\n[[File:Wendell L. Willkie on the cover of TIME Magazine, July 31, 1939.jpg|thumb|right|For the 1940 and 1944 presidential elections, Crum supported [[Wendell Willkie]] (here, on the cover of [[TIME Magazine|''Time'' magazine]], July 31, 1939]]\nCrum worked in the 1940 and 1944 campaigns of U.S. Presidential candidate [[Wendell Willkie]].<ref name=Anything/><ref name=NYTobit/>  In 1941, he became chairman for the Western US of \"Fight for Freedom, Inc.,\" an group favoring intervention in World War II (in alignment with Wilkie).<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn 1943, Crum served as special counsel on [[FDR]]'s [[Fair Employment Practices Committee]].<ref name=Anything/><ref name=NYTobit/>  He also served as WilIke's liaison to FDR via [[David Niles]].  When Wilkie failed to get the nomination, Crum helped form \"Independent Republicans for Roosevelt\" and campaigned for FDR, occasionally with [[Harry S. Truman]].<ref name=Anything/><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nCrum was a Republican who opposed Communism but supported the civil liberties of Communists.  He joined the [[National Lawyers Guild]] shortly after it formed in 1939 as an organization of progressive and Communist lawyers to counter the conservative [[National Bar Association]] (NLG),<ref name=LastParty/> probably influenced by his friend and NLG co-founder [[Robert W. Kenny]]. In 1942, Crum was a vice president of NLG's local chapter.<ref name=Anything/>  \n\nIn September 1945, Crum chaired a rally of the [[Joint Anti-Fascist Refugee Committee]] (JAFRC), which featured an overseas call from [[Harold Laski]].<ref name=Anything/>  By year end, Crum's clients included Owl Drug, United Drug, and [[Borden (company)|Borden's]] Milk.  He was national vice president of the NLG, national co-chair of the [[CIO-PAC]], and California chair of [https://www.historyisaweapon.com/defcon1/leftchineseamerica.html United China War Relief].  Rumor had it that he would succeed [[Harold L. Ickes]] as [[United States Secretary of the Interior]].<ref name=Anything/>\n\n===Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry===\n[[File:Ben-Gurion at Anglo-American Committee.jpg|right|thumb|Crum served on the [[Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry]] (here, future president of [[Israel]], [[David Ben-Gurion]], testifies before the committee)]]\nOn January 1, 1946, Crum accepted an invitation to join the [[Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry|Anglo-American Commission of Inquiry on Palestine]] (AACIP) that advised President [[Harry Truman]] to support the opening of the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate of Palestine]] to unrestricted Jewish immigration and to ease restrictions on Jewish land purchases.<ref name=Anything/><ref name=NYTobit/>On February 17 1946, Crum announced in Vienna, Austria, that he expected to see \"mass suicides\" if European Jews did not receive permission to emigrate to Palestine.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Mass Suicides of Jews in Europe Feared by Palestine Investigator; SUICIDE WAVE SEEN FOR MIGRANT JEWS\n| first = Albion \n| last = Ross \n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1946/02/18/archives/mass-suicides-of-jews-in-europe-feared-by-palestine-investigator.html\n| date = 18 February 1946\n| accessdate = 16 April 2020}}</ref>  His book, ''Behind the Silken Curtain a Personal Account of Anglo-American Diplomacy in Palestine and the Middle East'' was published by [[Simon & Schuster]] in 1947.<ref name=NYTobit/>  When [[Clifford Clarke]] succeeded the issue of Israeli independence from [[David Niles]], he received \"advice and assistance\" from Crum, [[Eliahu Epstein]], and [[Max Lowenthal]].<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Israel \n| last = Goldstein\n| title = My World as a Jew: The Memoirs of Israel Goldstein, Volume 1\n| publisher = Herzl Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=IQUcAAAAMAAJ\n| page = 225\n| date = 1984\n| accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref>  Israeli State Archives show that on May 11, 1948, Crum visited President [[Harry S. Truman]]:  \"Crum [Bartley Crum] saw President yesterday, returned fairly optimistic.\"<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Irene L.  \n| last = Gendzier\n| title = Dying to Forget: Oil, Power, Palestine, and the Foundations of U.S. Policy in the Middle East\n| publisher = Columbia University Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=znrICgAAQBAJ\n| page = 359 (fn2)\n| date = 17 November 2015\n| accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Hollywood Ten===\n[[File:Robert W. Kenny.jpg|thumb|right|[[Robert W. Kenny]] (undated), 21st [[California Attorney General]], was a long-time friend and colleague of Crum]] \nAs vice president of the NLG's state chapter and with Kenny as president, Crum entered into increasing prominent issues involving civil rights of left-leaning people.\n\nIn 1946, Crum answered [[Paul Robeson]] in his \"crusade call\" and endorsed the [[American Crusade Against Lynching]] (ACAL) organization.<ref>{{cite book|last=Swindall|first=Lindsey R.|title=Paul Robeson: A Life of Activism and Art|publisher=Rowman and Littlefield Publishers, Inc.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/paulrobesonlifeo0000swin/page/113 113]\u2013114|url=https://archive.org/details/paulrobesonlifeo0000swin|url-access=registration|quote=American Crusade Against Lynching Paul Robeson.|isbn=9781442207950|date=2013-02-07}}</ref> The ACAL had been accused of socialist and communist motives; which led to the organization, including Crum, coming under close watch by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI). The FBI tapped Crum's phones, opened his mail, and shadowed him constantly.\n\nIn 1946, Crum was also a member of the national board of the [[Independent Citizens Committee of the Arts, Sciences and Professions]], which also had a large branch in California, the Hollywood Independent Citizens Committee of the Arts, Sciences and Professions.<ref>\n{{citation\n| title = Independent Citizens Committee of the Arts, Sciences and Professions\n| publisher = New York City April 1946\n| url = https://sites.google.com/site/newyorkcityapril1946/in-progress/the-left/the-popular-front-in-1946/independent-citizens-committee-of-the-arts-sciences-and-professions\n| date = 6 June 2013\n| accessdate = 19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947, Crum was the attorney for some of the so-called \"[[Hollywood Ten]]\" who were subpoenaed to appear before the House Un-American Activities Committee in 1949.  His daughter recalled:    <blockquote> <small> I first learned about the Hollywood blacklist on Nov. 24, 1947. I remember the exact moment. I was standing with my father, Bartley Crum, by a phone booth near Union Square in San Francisco, feeding him nickels and dimes while he made a series of intense phone calls to Dore Schary, who was the head of MGM. <br> If you're wondering why he had to make those calls from a pay phone, it's because our home phone was bugged by the F.B.I. At that point I was too young to quite grasp the significance of those bugged calls, but I did know that my father had been one of six lawyers who had just defended the ''Hollywood 10'' in front of the House Un-American Activities Committee (HUAC) in Washington.<ref name=Blacklist>\n{{cite news \n  | first =  Patricia \n  | last = Bosworth \n  | authorlink = Patricia Bosworth\n  | title = Hollywood Blacklist, per the Daughter of Bartley Crum\n  | newspaper=The New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/20/movies/giving-credit-where-credit-is-long-overdue.html\n  | date = 20 April 1997\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref> </small> </blockquote>   She also recorded differences between Communist and non-Communist lawyers (in which latter camp Crum was), contrary to other accounts of greater unity among lawyers.<ref name=Blacklist/>\n\n===''New York Star''===\n[[File:MarshallField3-c.1919.JPG|thumb|right|Crum bought ''[[PM (newspaper)|PM]]'' with [[Joseph Fels Barnes]] from [[Marshall Field III]] (here, 1919) and renamed it ''[[New York Star (1948\u20131949)|New York Star]]'']]\nIn 1948, due to blowback from the HUAC Hollywood hearings, Crum moved his family from the San Francisco Bay area to New York City.  In 1948, Crum bought a major interest in the dying ''[[PM (newspaper)|PM]]'' newspaper with [[Joseph Fels Barnes]] from [[Marshall Field III]], who maintained a minority interest.  On June 23, 1948, they renamed ''PM'' as the ''[[New York Star (1948\u20131949)|New York Star]]''.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=NYT1948>\n{{cite news\n  | title = The Star Becomes a Morning Paper: Successor to PM Stresses Abandonment of Editorial Comment With News\n  | newspaper = New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1948/06/23/archives/the-star-becomes-a-morning-paper-successor-to-pm-stresses.html\n  | date = 23 June 1948\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=NYS1948>\n{{cite web\n  | title = New York Star, Formerly Pm (New York, N.Y.) 1948-1948\n  | publisher = Library of Congress\n  | url = https://www.loc.gov/item/sn86071546/\n  | date = 20 April 1997\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=NYS1949>\n{{cite web\n  | title = New York Star, Formerly Pm (New York, N.Y.) 1948-1949\n  | publisher = Library of Congress\n  | url = https://www.loc.gov/item/sn83030878/\n  | date = \n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref>  Also in the [[1948 United States presidential election]], he supported Harry S. Truman (Democrat) over [[Thomas E. Dewey]] (Republican) or [[Henry A. Wallace]] (Progressive).<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn January 1949, the ''Star'' folded (and helped undermine Crum's personal finances).<ref name=LastParty/>  During that year, Crum joined Hays, Podell, Algase, Crum & Feuer with offices at 39 Broadway.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n===Continued politics===\n\nIn 1950, Crum's name came up in Congress during investigation into Truman crony [[Max Lowenthal]].  On September 15, 1950, Lowenthal appeared before the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] AKA \"HUAC\" (two of whose members were Mundt and Nixon\u2013of the Mundt-Nixon Bill). Already in August 1950, HUAC had re-subpoenaed four witness who had been part of [[Whittaker Chambers]]'s [[Ware group|Ware Group]]:  [[Lee Pressman]], [[Nathan Witt]], [[Charles Kramer (economist)|Charles Kramer]] and [[John Abt]].  The committee had asked both Pressman and Kramer whether they knew Lowenthal; both confirmed. Lowenthal brought former U.S. Senator [[Burton K. Wheeler]] as counsel.  After reviewing his curriculum vitae, the committee tried to link him with known Communist Party members and organizations, some of which he confirmed, others not, all without admitting any wrongdoing. Names mentioned included:  Crum, [[Alger Hiss]], [[Donald Hiss]], [[David Wahl]], [[Martin Popper]], [[Allan Rosenberg (spy)|Allan Rosenberg]], Lee Pressman, the [[Russian-American Industrial Corporation]], the [[Twentieth Century Fund]], and the [[International Juridical Association]].<ref name=1950hearing>\n{{cite book\n| title = Hearings regarding communism in the United States Government: Hearings before the Committee on Un-American Activities, House of Representatives, Eighty-first Congress, second session\n| publisher = US Government Printing Office\n| url =https://archive.org/details/hearingsregardin195002unit\n| page = \n| date = 15 September 1950\n| accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = FOIA document\n| publisher = FBI\n| url = https://archive.org/stream/foia_HUAC_HQ-58/HUAC_HQ-58#page/n97/mode/2up/search/lowenthal\n| page = 97\n| date = 1950\n| accessdate = 15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1952 United States presidential election]], Crum supported [[Adlai E. Stevenson]] (Democrat) over [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] (Republican).<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n===Teamsters involvement===\n[[File:James_R._Hoffa_NYWTS.jpg|thumb|right|Shortly before his suicide, Crum became embroiled in an issue with [[Jimmy Hoffa]] of the \"[[International Brotherhood of Teamsters|Teamsters]]\"]]\nIn 1958, Crum became involved in a controversy with [[Jimmy Hoffa]], head of the [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters]] (\"Teamsters\").  He had been trying to collect $210,000 in legal fees from the Teamsters for a client (lawyers represented by [[Godfrey P. Schmidt]]).  He testified in before the United States Select Committee on Improper Activities in the Labor or Management Field.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Death==\n\nLabeled a subversive,<ref name=Blacklist/> Crum lost most of his clients.  Unable to cope with stress from the harassment, he successfully committed suicide on December 9, 1959, by washing down an entire bottle of [[seconal]] with [[whisky]].  His wife discovered his body at their home at 165 East Eightieth Street, New York City.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nCrum married Anna Gertrude Bosworth, an author of novels and (later) a cookbook.<ref name=NYTobit/>  They had two children.  The younger, son Bartley Crum, Jr., committed suicide in 1953  by shooting himself with his grandfather's gun in his freshman year at [[Reed College]].<ref name=Without>\n{{cite news \n  | last = Fitzgerald\n  | first =  Brian\n  | title =  Life without father\n  | publisher =  Office of University Relations\n  | volume=IV\n  | issue=28 \n  | work= B.U. Bridge\n  | date = March 30, 2001\n  | url = http://www.bu.edu/bridge/archive/2001/03-30/bosworth.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-02-11}}</ref>  The older, daughter [[Patricia Bosworth]], became first a successful actress and then even more successful writer. In 1997, she wrote a family memoir, ''Anything Your Little Heart Desires'', reminiscing about her father.<ref name=\"Kakutani\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/13/books/finding-out-who-the-man-called-daddy-was.html|title=Finding Out Who the Man Called Daddy Was|last=Kakutani|first=Michiko|date=13 May 1997|work=The New York Times|page=16|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref>  In 2017, she wrote a second memoir about her father, brother, and husbands, called ''The Men in My Life: Love and Art in 1950s Manhattan''.  She died from complications of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"BosworthDies\">\n{{Cite journal\n| url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/patricia-bosworth-dead-hollywood-actress-turned-chronicler-dies-coronavirus-complications-at-86-1288456 \n| title=Patricia Bosworth, Hollywood Actress-Turned-Chronicler, Dies From Coronavirus Complications at 86 \n| journal=The Hollywood Reporter\n| date = 2 April 2020\n| accessdate= 3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1941, Crum moved his family from Berkeley to 763 Bay Street, San Francisco.  In 1945, they moved again to 2626 Green Street, San Francisco.  In 1948, they moved to New York City, where they lived at several addresses.<ref name=Anything/>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nIn their obituary of Crum in 1959, the ''New York Times'' quoted Crum's stance on outlawing the [[CPUSA]]:     <blockquote> <small>  It is unconstitutional and utterly stupid for government to attempt to prevent people from thinking or believing as they wish...  As a non-Comnunist, I think the most effective answer to the Marxists is to make our democracy work by providing equality and job opportunities for all, strengthening the trade unions, and raising the standard of living.<ref name=NYTobit/>  </small> </blockquote>    Assessing his daughter's 1997 memoir, the ''New York Times'' wrote that she remembered him as:  <blockquote> <small> a hero-daddy who championed just causes, the doughty fighter for civil rights who defended the Hollywood Ten; the politically connected lawyer, friend of Harry S. Truman and Wendell L. Willkie; the member of the Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry Into Palestine in 1946 who told the world about the plight of the Jewish death-camp survivors in displaced-persons camps and fought for their safe passage to Palestine against British and Arab double-dealing... [Yet his] addiction to political causes and big legal retainers exercised a centrifugal pull away from the family he certainly loved.<ref name=LastParty/> </small> </blockquote>  She also admitted, \"My father informed on two colleagues already known to be Communists.\"<ref name=LastParty/><ref name=Blacklist/>\n\n==Works==\n\n* ''Behind the Silken Curtain:  A Personal Account of Anglo-American Diplomacy in Palestine and the Middle East'' (1947)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TfAcAAAAMAAJ&dq=editions:1kSpqI7tBLkC\n| first = Bartley Cavanaugh\n| last = Crum\n| authorlink = Bartley Crum\n| title = Behind the Silken Curtain:  A Personal Account of Anglo-American Diplomacy in Palestine and the Middle East\n| publisher = Simon and Schuster\n| date = 1947\n| accessdate= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Patricia Bosworth]]\n* [[Harry Bridges]]\n* [[Robert W. Kenny]]\n\n* [[Paul Robeson]]\n* [[Hollywood Ten]]\n* ''[[New York Star (1948\u20131949)]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.criticalpast.com/video/65675026586_HUAC-hearing_attorneys-Robert-Kenny-and-Bartley-Crum-appeal Critical Past - Kenny and Crum ask HUAC to stop hearings (1947)]\n* [https://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/attend-truman-award-dinner-new-york-arriving-at-the-waldorf-news-photo/517237544 Getty Images]:  Crum with Rita Hayworth (1953)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crum, Bartley Cavanaugh}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:Drug-related suicides in the United States]]\n[[Category:Barbiturates-related deaths]]\n[[Category:Hollywood blacklist]]\n[[Category:Jurists who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n\n{{US-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Bartley Crum\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_upright      = \n| landscape          = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         = Bartley Cavanaugh Crum\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1900|11|28}}\n| birth_place        = [[Sacramento, California]], USA\n| baptised           = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1959|12|9|1900|11|28}}\n| death_place        = [[New York City]]\n| death_cause        = suicide by overdose\n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| burial_place       = <!-- may be used instead of resting_place and resting_place_coordinates (displays \"Burial place\" as label) -->\n| burial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments          = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| siglum             = \n| citizenship        = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of California at Berkeley]]\n| occupation         = attorney, activist\n| years_active       = 1933-1959\n| era                = [[New Deal]], [[McCarthyism]]\n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| known_for          = [[Hollywood Ten]] defense, [[Rita Hayworth]] divorce\n| notable_works      = ''Behind the Silken Curtain'' (1947)\n| style              = \n| home_town          = San Francisco\n| party              = Republican, Independent Republicans for Roosevelt\n| movement           = \n| opponents          = \n| boards             = [[National Lawyers Guild]], [[Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry]], Lawyers Committee for Justice in Palestine\n| spouse             = Anna Gertrude Bosworth\n| partner            = <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = [[Patricia Bosworth]], Bartley Crum Jr.\n| parents            = James Henry Crum,  Emma Cavanaugh\n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| awards             = \n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Bartley Crum''', AKA Bartley C. Crum (1900 \u2013 December 9, 1959), was a prominent mid-20th-century American lawyer, who became prominent as a member of the [[Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry]], his book on that experience, and for defending targets of the [[House Un-American Activities Committee|HUAC]], particularly the [[Hollywood Ten]] and [[Paul Robeson]].<ref name=LastParty>\n{{cite news\n  | title = The Last Party\n  | newspaper = New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/27/books/the-last-party.html\n  | date = 27 April 1997\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Anything>\n{{cite book \n | first=Patricia \n | last=Bosworth \n | authorlink=Patricia Bosworth \n | title=Anything Your Little Heart Desires: An American Family Story \n | publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]] \n | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G_mPAAAAMAAJ \n | pages = 69-83 (Wilkie 1940), 89 (SF address), 94 (NLG), 94-8 (Wilkie 1944), 100 (FPRC), 118-9 (Nike's), 124-136 (Wilkie 1944), 146-7 (FDR 1944), 158-161 (UN opens), 161 (2626 Green ST), 161-2 (Louise Bransten), 162 (FBI surveillance), 162-3 (JAFRC), 163-4 (Palm Court), 165 (1945 year-end snapshot), 167 (appointment AACIP), 167-201 (AACIP experience), 168 (Henderson), 171 (Henderson), 175 (Henderson), 177 (British surveillance), 183 (Vienna), 197 (Henderson), 200-201 (Henderson), 201 (American Christian Palestine Committee)\n | date=1997 \n | accessdate = 17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite news\n  | title = Bartley C. Crum, Lawyer, 59, Dies; Acted in Cases Involving Civil Rights -- Won Million in Rita Hayworth Divorce\n  | newspaper = New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1959/12/11/archives/bartley-c-crum-lawyer-59-dies-acted-in-cases-involving-civil-rights.html\n  | page = 33\n  | date = 11 December 1959\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nBartley Cavanaugh Crum was born on November 28, 1900, in [[Sacramento, California]], the son of James Henry Crum and  Emma Cavanaugh.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=Whos>\n{{cite book\n| title = Who's who in Commerce and Industry, Volume 11\n| publisher = Marquis Who's Who\n| url = https://books.google.ca/books?id=I-YdAQAAIAAJ&q=emma+cavanaugh+mary+crum&dq=emma+cavanaugh+mary+crum&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjnxv287c7oAhVJmuAKHc-IAaUQ6AEwAHoECAUQAQ\n| page = 278\n| date = 1959\n| accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref>  He was raised [[Roman Catholic]].<ref name=LastParty/>  In 1922, he received a BA and in 1924 a JD from the [[University of California at Berkeley]].<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Career==\n\nCrum started his career as a teach of English and International Law at UC/Berkeley.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n===Neylan and Hearst===\n[[File:HearstAbout1910.jpg|thumb|right|In the 1920s, Crum worked for XXX, whose major client was media magnate [[William Randolph Hearst]] (here {{circa|1910}})]]\nIn 1924, Crum joined the law offices of [[John Francis Neylan]], chief attorney for newspaper magnate [[William Randolph Hearst]].  As a Hearst lawyer, Crum helped defend [[Clarence Darrow]] in 1933.  \"Darrow taught me more law than I had known before,\" Crum said later.<ref name=NYTobit/>  \n\n===Kenny and NLG===\n[[File:Harry Bridges.png|thumb|right|Crum helped defend against the deportation of his friend [[Harry Bridges]] in 1939]]\nIn 1938, Crum left Neylan and set a law office with Philip Ehrich and David A. Silver.  In 1938 or 1939, he joined the [[National Lawyers Guild]] at the behest of friend and fellow liberal Republican [[Robert W. Kenny]].  In 1939, Crum helped defend [[Harry Bridges]] in one of his deportation hearings.<ref name=NYTobit/>  He also criticized the US policy during the [[Spanish Civil War]] and its aftermath.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n===Wendell Willkie===\n[[File:Wendell L. Willkie on the cover of TIME Magazine, July 31, 1939.jpg|thumb|right|For the 1940 and 1944 presidential elections, Crum supported [[Wendell Willkie]] (here, on the cover of [[TIME Magazine|''Time'' magazine]], July 31, 1939]]\nCrum worked in the 1940 and 1944 campaigns of U.S. Presidential candidate [[Wendell Willkie]].<ref name=Anything/><ref name=NYTobit/>  In 1941, he became chairman for the Western US of \"Fight for Freedom, Inc.,\" an group favoring intervention in World War II (in alignment with Wilkie).<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn 1943, Crum served as special counsel on [[FDR]]'s [[Fair Employment Practices Committee]].<ref name=Anything/><ref name=NYTobit/>  He also served as WilIke's liaison to FDR via [[David Niles]].  When Wilkie failed to get the nomination, Crum helped form \"Independent Republicans for Roosevelt\" and campaigned for FDR, occasionally with [[Harry S. Truman]].<ref name=Anything/><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nCrum was a Republican who opposed Communism but supported the civil liberties of Communists.  He joined the [[National Lawyers Guild]] shortly after it formed in 1939 as an organization of progressive and Communist lawyers to counter the conservative [[National Bar Association]] (NLG),<ref name=LastParty/> probably influenced by his friend and NLG co-founder [[Robert W. Kenny]]. In 1942, Crum was a vice president of NLG's local chapter.<ref name=Anything/>  \n\nIn September 1945, Crum chaired a rally of the [[Joint Anti-Fascist Refugee Committee]] (JAFRC), which featured an overseas call from [[Harold Laski]].<ref name=Anything/>  By year end, Crum's clients included Owl Drug, United Drug, and [[Borden (company)|Borden's]] Milk.  He was national vice president of the NLG, national co-chair of the [[CIO-PAC]], and California chair of [https://www.historyisaweapon.com/defcon1/leftchineseamerica.html United China War Relief].  Rumor had it that he would succeed [[Harold L. Ickes]] as [[United States Secretary of the Interior]].<ref name=Anything/>\n\n===Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry===\n[[File:Ben-Gurion at Anglo-American Committee.jpg|right|thumb|Crum served on the [[Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry]] (here, future president of [[Israel]], [[David Ben-Gurion]], testifies before the committee)]]\nOn January 1, 1946, Crum accepted an invitation to join the [[Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry|Anglo-American Commission of Inquiry on Palestine]] (AACIP) that advised President [[Harry Truman]] to support the opening of the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate of Palestine]] to unrestricted Jewish immigration and to ease restrictions on Jewish land purchases.<ref name=Anything/><ref name=NYTobit/>On February 17 1946, Crum announced in Vienna, Austria, that he expected to see \"mass suicides\" if European Jews did not receive permission to emigrate to Palestine.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Mass Suicides of Jews in Europe Feared by Palestine Investigator; SUICIDE WAVE SEEN FOR MIGRANT JEWS\n| first = Albion \n| last = Ross \n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1946/02/18/archives/mass-suicides-of-jews-in-europe-feared-by-palestine-investigator.html\n| date = 18 February 1946\n| accessdate = 16 April 2020}}</ref>  His book, ''Behind the Silken Curtain a Personal Account of Anglo-American Diplomacy in Palestine and the Middle East'' was published by [[Simon & Schuster]] in 1947.<ref name=NYTobit/>  When [[Clifford Clarke]] succeeded the issue of Israeli independence from [[David Niles]], he received \"advice and assistance\" from Crum, [[Eliahu Epstein]], and [[Max Lowenthal]].<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Israel \n| last = Goldstein\n| title = My World as a Jew: The Memoirs of Israel Goldstein, Volume 1\n| publisher = Herzl Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=IQUcAAAAMAAJ\n| page = 225\n| date = 1984\n| accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref>  Israeli State Archives show that on May 11, 1948, Crum visited President [[Harry S. Truman]]:  \"Crum [Bartley Crum] saw President yesterday, returned fairly optimistic.\"<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Irene L.  \n| last = Gendzier\n| title = Dying to Forget: Oil, Power, Palestine, and the Foundations of U.S. Policy in the Middle East\n| publisher = Columbia University Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=znrICgAAQBAJ\n| page = 359 (fn2)\n| date = 17 November 2015\n| accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Hollywood Ten===\n[[File:Robert W. Kenny.jpg|thumb|right|[[Robert W. Kenny]] (undated), 21st [[California Attorney General]], was a long-time friend and colleague of Crum]] \nAs vice president of the NLG's state chapter and with Kenny as president, Crum entered into increasing prominent issues involving civil rights of left-leaning people.\n\nIn 1946, Crum answered [[Paul Robeson]] in his \"crusade call\" and endorsed the [[American Crusade Against Lynching]] (ACAL) organization.<ref>{{cite book|last=Swindall|first=Lindsey R.|title=Paul Robeson: A Life of Activism and Art|publisher=Rowman and Littlefield Publishers, Inc.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/paulrobesonlifeo0000swin/page/113 113]\u2013114|url=https://archive.org/details/paulrobesonlifeo0000swin|url-access=registration|quote=American Crusade Against Lynching Paul Robeson.|isbn=9781442207950|date=2013-02-07}}</ref> The ACAL had been accused of socialist and communist motives; which led to the organization, including Crum, coming under close watch by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI). The FBI tapped Crum's phones, opened his mail, and shadowed him constantly.\n\nIn 1946, Crum was also a member of the national board of the [[Independent Citizens Committee of the Arts, Sciences and Professions]], which also had a a large branch in California, the Hollywood Independent Citizens Committee of the Arts, Sciences and Professions.<ref>\n{{citation\n| title = Independent Citizens Committee of the Arts, Sciences and Professions\n| publisher = New York City April 1946\n| url = https://sites.google.com/site/newyorkcityapril1946/in-progress/the-left/the-popular-front-in-1946/independent-citizens-committee-of-the-arts-sciences-and-professions\n| date = 6 June 2013\n| accessdate = 19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947, Crum was the attorney for some of the so-called \"[[Hollywood Ten]]\" who were subpoenaed to appear before the House Un-American Activities Committee in 1949.  His daughter recalled:    <blockquote> <small> I first learned about the Hollywood blacklist on Nov. 24, 1947. I remember the exact moment. I was standing with my father, Bartley Crum, by a phone booth near Union Square in San Francisco, feeding him nickels and dimes while he made a series of intense phone calls to Dore Schary, who was the head of MGM. <br> If you're wondering why he had to make those calls from a pay phone, it's because our home phone was bugged by the F.B.I. At that point I was too young to quite grasp the significance of those bugged calls, but I did know that my father had been one of six lawyers who had just defended the ''Hollywood 10'' in front of the House Un-American Activities Committee (HUAC) in Washington.<ref name=Blacklist>\n{{cite news \n  | first =  Patricia \n  | last = Bosworth \n  | authorlink = Patricia Bosworth\n  | title = Hollywood Blacklist, per the Daughter of Bartley Crum\n  | newspaper=The New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/20/movies/giving-credit-where-credit-is-long-overdue.html\n  | date = 20 April 1997\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref> </small> </blockquote>   She also recorded differences between Communist and non-Communist lawyers (in which latter camp Crum was), contrary to other accounts of greater unity among lawyers.<ref name=Blacklist/>\n\n===''New York Star''===\n[[File:MarshallField3-c.1919.JPG|thumb|right|Crum bought ''[[PM (newspaper)|PM]]'' with [[Joseph Fels Barnes]] from [[Marshall Field III]] (here, 1919) and renamed it ''[[New York Star (1948\u20131949)|New York Star]]'']]\nIn 1948, due to blowback from the HUAC Hollywood hearings, Crum moved his family from the San Francisco Bay area to New York City.  In 1948, Crum bought a major interest in the dying ''[[PM (newspaper)|PM]]'' newspaper with [[Joseph Fels Barnes]] from [[Marshall Field III]], who maintained a minority interest.  On June 23, 1948, they renamed ''PM'' as the ''[[New York Star (1948\u20131949)|New York Star]]''.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=NYT1948>\n{{cite news\n  | title = The Star Becomes a Morning Paper: Successor to PM Stresses Abandonment of Editorial Comment With News\n  | newspaper = New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1948/06/23/archives/the-star-becomes-a-morning-paper-successor-to-pm-stresses.html\n  | date = 23 June 1948\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=NYS1948>\n{{cite web\n  | title = New York Star, Formerly Pm (New York, N.Y.) 1948-1948\n  | publisher = Library of Congress\n  | url = https://www.loc.gov/item/sn86071546/\n  | date = 20 April 1997\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=NYS1949>\n{{cite web\n  | title = New York Star, Formerly Pm (New York, N.Y.) 1948-1949\n  | publisher = Library of Congress\n  | url = https://www.loc.gov/item/sn83030878/\n  | date = \n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref>  Also in the [[1948 United States presidential election]], he supported Harry S. Truman (Democrat) over [[Thomas E. Dewey]] (Republican) or [[Henry A. Wallace]] (Progressive).<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn January 1949, the ''Star'' folded (and helped undermine Crum's personal finances).<ref name=LastParty/>  During that year, Crum joined Hays, Podell, Algase, Crum & Feuer with offices at 39 Broadway.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n===Continued politics===\n\nIn 1950, Crum's name came up in Congress during investigation into Truman crony [[Max Lowenthal]].  On September 15, 1950, Lowenthal appeared before the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] AKA \"HUAC\" (two of whose members were Mundt and Nixon\u2013of the Mundt-Nixon Bill). Already in August 1950, HUAC had re-subpoenaed four witness who had been part of [[Whittaker Chambers]]'s [[Ware group|Ware Group]]:  [[Lee Pressman]], [[Nathan Witt]], [[Charles Kramer (economist)|Charles Kramer]] and [[John Abt]].  The committee had asked both Pressman and Kramer whether they knew Lowenthal; both confirmed. Lowenthal brought former U.S. Senator [[Burton K. Wheeler]] as counsel.  After reviewing his curriculum vitae, the committee tried to link him with known Communist Party members and organizations, some of which he confirmed, others not, all without admitting any wrongdoing. Names mentioned included:  Crum, [[Alger Hiss]], [[Donald Hiss]], [[David Wahl]], [[Martin Popper]], [[Allan Rosenberg (spy)|Allan Rosenberg]], Lee Pressman, the [[Russian-American Industrial Corporation]], the [[Twentieth Century Fund]], and the [[International Juridical Association]].<ref name=1950hearing>\n{{cite book\n| title = Hearings regarding communism in the United States Government: Hearings before the Committee on Un-American Activities, House of Representatives, Eighty-first Congress, second session\n| publisher = US Government Printing Office\n| url =https://archive.org/details/hearingsregardin195002unit\n| page = \n| date = 15 September 1950\n| accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = FOIA document\n| publisher = FBI\n| url = https://archive.org/stream/foia_HUAC_HQ-58/HUAC_HQ-58#page/n97/mode/2up/search/lowenthal\n| page = 97\n| date = 1950\n| accessdate = 15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1952 United States presidential election]], Crum supported [[Adlai E. Stevenson]] (Democrat) over [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] (Republican).<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n===Teamsters involvement===\n[[File:James_R._Hoffa_NYWTS.jpg|thumb|right|Shortly before his suicide, Crum became embroiled in an issue with [[Jimmy Hoffa]] of the \"[[International Brotherhood of Teamsters|Teamsters]]\"]]\nIn 1958, Crum became involved in a controversy with [[Jimmy Hoffa]], head of the [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters]] (\"Teamsters\").  He had been trying to collect $210,000 in legal fees from the Teamsters for a client (lawyers represented by [[Godfrey P. Schmidt]]).  He testified in before the United States Select Committee on Improper Activities in the Labor or Management Field.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Death==\n\nLabeled a subversive,<ref name=Blacklist/> Crum lost most of his clients.  Unable to cope with stress from the harassment, he successfully committed suicide on December 9, 1959, by washing down an entire bottle of [[seconal]] with [[whisky]].  His wife discovered his body at their home at 165 East Eightieth Street, New York City.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nCrum married Anna Gertrude Bosworth, an author of novels and (later) a cookbook.<ref name=NYTobit/>  They had two children.  The younger, son Bartley Crum, Jr., committed suicide in 1953  by shooting himself with his grandfather's gun in his freshman year at [[Reed College]].<ref name=Without>\n{{cite news \n  | last = Fitzgerald\n  | first =  Brian\n  | title =  Life without father\n  | publisher =  Office of University Relations\n  | volume=IV\n  | issue=28 \n  | work= B.U. Bridge\n  | date = March 30, 2001\n  | url = http://www.bu.edu/bridge/archive/2001/03-30/bosworth.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-02-11}}</ref>  The older, daughter [[Patricia Bosworth]], became first a successful actress and then even more successful writer. In 1997, she wrote a family memoir, ''Anything Your Little Heart Desires'', reminiscing about her father.<ref name=\"Kakutani\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/13/books/finding-out-who-the-man-called-daddy-was.html|title=Finding Out Who the Man Called Daddy Was|last=Kakutani|first=Michiko|date=13 May 1997|work=The New York Times|page=16|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref>  In 2017, she wrote a second memoir about her father, brother, and husbands, called ''The Men in My Life: Love and Art in 1950s Manhattan''.  She died from complications of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"BosworthDies\">\n{{Cite journal\n| url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/patricia-bosworth-dead-hollywood-actress-turned-chronicler-dies-coronavirus-complications-at-86-1288456 \n| title=Patricia Bosworth, Hollywood Actress-Turned-Chronicler, Dies From Coronavirus Complications at 86 \n| journal=The Hollywood Reporter\n| date = 2 April 2020\n| accessdate= 3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1941, Crum moved his family from Berkeley to 763 Bay Street, San Francisco.  In 1945, they moved again to 2626 Green Street, San Francisco.  In 1948, they moved to New York City, where they lived at several addresses.<ref name=Anything/>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nIn their obituary of Crum in 1959, the ''New York Times'' quoted Crum's stance on outlawing the [[CPUSA]]:     <blockquote> <small>  It is unconstitutional and utterly stupid for government to attempt to prevent people from thinking or believing as they wish...  As a non-Comnunist, I think the most effective answer to the Marxists is to make our democracy work by providing equality and job opportunities for all, strengthening the trade unions, and raising the standard of living.<ref name=NYTobit/>  </small> </blockquote>    Assessing his daughter's 1997 memoir, the ''New York Times'' wrote that she remembered him as:  <blockquote> <small> a hero-daddy who championed just causes, the doughty fighter for civil rights who defended the Hollywood Ten; the politically connected lawyer, friend of Harry S. Truman and Wendell L. Willkie; the member of the Anglo-American Committee of Inquiry Into Palestine in 1946 who told the world about the plight of the Jewish death-camp survivors in displaced-persons camps and fought for their safe passage to Palestine against British and Arab double-dealing... [Yet his] addiction to political causes and big legal retainers exercised a centrifugal pull away from the family he certainly loved.<ref name=LastParty/> </small> </blockquote>  She also admitted, \"My father informed on two colleagues already known to be Communists.\"<ref name=LastParty/><ref name=Blacklist/>\n\n==Works==\n\n* ''Behind the Silken Curtain:  A Personal Account of Anglo-American Diplomacy in Palestine and the Middle East'' (1947)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TfAcAAAAMAAJ&dq=editions:1kSpqI7tBLkC\n| first = Bartley Cavanaugh\n| last = Crum\n| authorlink = Bartley Crum\n| title = Behind the Silken Curtain:  A Personal Account of Anglo-American Diplomacy in Palestine and the Middle East\n| publisher = Simon and Schuster\n| date = 1947\n| accessdate= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Patricia Bosworth]]\n* [[Harry Bridges]]\n* [[Robert W. Kenny]]\n\n* [[Paul Robeson]]\n* [[Hollywood Ten]]\n* ''[[New York Star (1948\u20131949)]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.criticalpast.com/video/65675026586_HUAC-hearing_attorneys-Robert-Kenny-and-Bartley-Crum-appeal Critical Past - Kenny and Crum ask HUAC to stop hearings (1947)]\n* [https://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/attend-truman-award-dinner-new-york-arriving-at-the-waldorf-news-photo/517237544 Getty Images]:  Crum with Rita Hayworth (1953)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crum, Bartley Cavanaugh}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:Drug-related suicides in the United States]]\n[[Category:Barbiturates-related deaths]]\n[[Category:Hollywood blacklist]]\n[[Category:Jurists who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n\n{{US-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bartley_Crum"}
{"title_page": "The Powerpuff Girls", "text_new": "{{About|the original 1998 TV series|other uses|The Powerpuff Girls (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|American superhero animated television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n|image = The Powerpuff Girls logo.svg\n|image_alt = Pink letters reading \"The Powerpuff Girls\" against a black background.\n|caption = <!-- An image of the title card including the title logo, or the logo only, of the show does not need a caption -->\n|genre = [[Superhero fiction|Superhero]]<br />Action [[Adventure fiction|adventure]]<br />[[Comedy]]<br />[[Satire]]\n|creator = [[Craig McCracken]]\n|writer = {{unbulleted list|Craig McCracken|[[Jason Butler Rote]]|[[Amy Keating Rogers]]|[[Chris Savino]]}}\n|director = {{unbulleted list|Craig McCracken <small>(1998\u20132002)</small>|[[John McIntyre (cartoonist)|John McIntyre]] <small>(animation)</small>|[[Randy Myers (animator)|Randy Myers]] <small>(animation)</small>|[[Lauren Faust]] <small>(supervising)</small>|[[Genndy Tartakovsky]] <small>(recording)</small>|[[Robert Alvarez]] <small>(animation)</small>|[[Chris Savino]] <small>(2003\u201305)</small>|David Smith <small>(\"Dance Pantsed\")</small>}}\n|voices = {{unbulleted list|[[Cathy Cavadini]]|[[Tara Strong]]|[[E. G. Daily]]|[[Tom Kane]]|[[Tom Kenny]]|[[Roger L. Jackson]]|[[Jennifer Hale]]|[[Jeff Bennett]]|Jennifer Martin|[[Jim Cummings]]|[[Jill Talley]]}}\n|narrated = Tom Kenny\n|theme_music_composer = {{unbulleted list|Thomas Chase|[[Stephen Rucker|Steve Rucker]]|[[James L. Venable]]}}\n|opentheme = \"The Powerpuff Girls (Main Theme)\"\n|endtheme = \"The Powerpuff Girls (End Theme)\", <br />{{small|performed by [[Bis (Scottish band)|Bis]]}}\n|composer = {{unbulleted list|Thomas Chase|Steve Rucker|James L. Venable}}\n|country = United States\n|language = English\n|channel = [[Cartoon Network]]<!--Do not place foreign networks/channels here.-->\n|executive_producer = Craig McCracken\n|producer = {{unbulleted list|Chris Savino <small>(seasons 5\u20136)</small>|Genndy Tartakovsky <small><br />(supervising producer, seasons 1\u20134)</small>}}\n|company = {{unbulleted list|[[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Cartoons]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Powerpuff Girls Episode Guide -Hanna-Barbera|url=http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/P-R/The_Powerpuff_Girls/|work=[[The Big Cartoon DataBase]]|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20150501001713/http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/P-R/The_Powerpuff_Girls/|archivedate=May 1, 2015}}</ref> <!-- Do Not add Hanna-Barbera without a reliable source confirming this, otherwise it is considered questionable information--> <small><br />(1998\u20132002)</small>|[[Cartoon Network Studios]] <small><br />(2003\u201305)</small>}}\n|distributor = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n|num_seasons = 6\n|num_episodes = 80 (whole)<br />139 (segments)\n|list_episodes= List of The Powerpuff Girls episodes\n|runtime = 11 minutes (short-length episodes)<br>22 minutes (specials)<br>44 minutes (\"'Twas the Fight Before Christmas\")\n|audio_format = {{unbulleted list|[[Monoaural|Mono]] <small>(1998\u20132000)</small>|[[Dolby Surround]] <small>(2000\u201302)</small>|[[Dolby Digital]] 5.1 <small>(2003\u201305)</small>}}\n|picture_format = {{unbulleted list|[[4:3]] [[SDTV]]|[[16:9]] [[HDTV]] <small>(specials)</small>}}\n|first_aired = {{Start date|1998|11|18}}<ref name=\"CN Featured Episodes\"/>\n|last_aired = {{End date|2005|3|25}}<ref name=\"CN Featured Episodes\"/><ref name=\"Final airdate\"/><!--This article is about the ORIGINAL 1998\u2013 2005 series, the new series of the same name has its own separate article. Don't include post-2005 specials either.-->\n|related = ''[[Powerpuff Girls Z]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv-tokyo.co.jp/anime/ppgz/|title=Powerpuff Girls Z|work=tv-tokyo.co.jp|language=Japanese|accessdate=February 3, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20121204170224/http://www.tv-tokyo.co.jp/anime/ppgz/|archivedate=December 4, 2012}}</ref>''<br />''[[What a Cartoon!]]<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/>''<br />[[The Powerpuff Girls (2016 TV series)|''The Powerpuff Girls'']] (2016)\n|website =https://archive.today/20150125075015/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/games/ppg/index.html\n}}\n'''''The Powerpuff Girls''''' is an American comedy [[Superhero fiction|superhero]] [[List of animated television series|animated television series]] created by animator [[Craig McCracken]] for [[Cartoon Network]] and the fifth of the network's [[Cartoon Cartoons]] brand. The series was produced by [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]] in its first four seasons, and by [[Cartoon Network Studios]] in its final two seasons. It centers on Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup, three [[kindergarten]]-aged girls with [[Superpower (ability)|superpowers]]. The girls all live in the fictional city of Townsville with their father and creator, a scientist named Professor Utonium, and are frequently called upon by the city's mayor to help fight nearby criminals and other enemies using their powers.\n\nMcCracken originally developed the show in 1992 as a cartoon short entitled Whoopass Stew! while in his second year at [[California Institute of the Arts|CalArts]]. Following a name change, Cartoon Network featured the first Powerpuff Girls pilots in its animation showcase program [[What a Cartoon!]] in 1995 and 1996. The series premiered on November 18, 1998 and ended on March 25, 2005. Excluding the two pilot shorts, the series ran for a total of six seasons, totaling 78 episodes. In addition, a [[The Powerpuff Girls Movie|feature film]] was released in July 2002 and a Christmas special aired in December 2003. Two additional specials were made: a tenth-anniversary special , aired in 2008, and a [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] special, aired in 2014, the latter of which was made without McCracken's input.\n\nVarious spin-off media include an [[Powerpuff Girls Z|anime]], three CD soundtracks, a home video collection, comic books, a [[List of The Powerpuff Girls video games|series of video games]], a [[The Powerpuff Girls (2016 TV series)|2016 reboot series]], as well as various licensed merchandise. The series has been nominated for six [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Awards]], nine [[Annie Award]]s, and a [[Kids' Choice Award]] during its run.\n\nIt was the last cartoon produced in [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Studios]], which was closed in [[2001]] after [[William Hanna]]'s death.\n\n==Premise==\nThe show revolves around the adventures of three kindergarten aged girls with an array of various [[Superpower (ability)|superpowers]]: Blossom (pink), Bubbles (blue), and Buttercup (green). The plot of an episode is usually some humorous variation of standard [[superhero]] and [[tokusatsu]] shows, with the girls using their powers to defend their town from [[villain]]s and giant [[monster movie|monsters]]. In addition, the girls have to deal with the normal issues that young children face, such as sibling rivalries, loose teeth,<ref>{{cite episode|title=Moral Decay|series=The Powerpuff Girls|network=Cartoon Network|date=February 9, 2001|season=3|number=12A}}</ref> personal hygiene,<ref>{{cite episode|title=Down 'n' Dirty|series=The Powerpuff Girls|network=Cartoon Network|date=September 10, 1999|season=2|number=5B}}</ref> going to school, [[Nocturnal enuresis|bed wetting]],<ref>{{cite episode|title=Pee Pee G's|series=The Powerpuff Girls|network=Cartoon Network|date=November 13, 2003|season=5|number=6A}}</ref> or dependence on a [[security blanket]].<ref>{{cite episode|title=Cover Up|series=The Powerpuff Girls|network=Cartoon Network|date=May 26, 2000|season=2|number=11B}}</ref> Episodes often contain hidden references to older pop culture (especially noticeable in the episode \"Meet the Beat Alls\",<ref>{{cite episode|title=Meet the Beat-Alls|series=The Powerpuff Girls|network=Cartoon Network|date=February 9, 2001|season=3|number=12B}}</ref> which is a homage to [[the Beatles]]). The cartoon always tries to keep different ideas within each episode with some small tributes and [[Running gag|parodies thrown in.]]<ref name=\"autogenerated2001\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,98235,00.html|title='Power' Hungry|first=Mike|last=Flaherty|date=February 8, 2001|work=EW.com|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=May 28, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021144559/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,98235,00.html|archivedate=October 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe show is set mainly in the city of Townsville, USA. Townsville is depicted as a major American city, with a cityscape consisting of several major skyscrapers. In his review of ''[[The Powerpuff Girls Movie]]'', movie critic Bob Longino of ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' said, \"the intricate drawings emanate 1950s futuristic pizzazz like a [[David Hockney]] scenescape,\" and that the show is \"one of the few American creations that is both gleeful pop culture and exquisite high art.\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Powerpuff Girls Movie|first=Bob|last=Longino|url=http://mo.accessatlanta.com/movies/content/shared/movies/reviews/P/thepowerpuffgirlsmovie.html|journal=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|accessdate=May 27, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116094053/http://mo.accessatlanta.com/movies/content/shared/movies/reviews/P/thepowerpuffgirlsmovie.html|archivedate=January 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\n{{See also|List of The Powerpuff Girls characters}}\n<!-- Please stick to a simple description format and incorporate analyzes of character traits only if they appear in reliable third party publications, any unsourced original research will be removed. -->\n[[File:Powerpuff girls characters.jpg|thumb|left|270px|alt=The Powerpuff Girls&nbsp;\u2013 Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup|The Powerpuff Girls: Bubbles (left), Blossom (middle), and Buttercup (right)|alt=The Powerpuff Girls&nbsp;\u2013 Blossom, and Buttercup]]\nAs depicted in the opening sequence of each episode, the Powerpuff Girls [[Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup]] were created by Professor Utonium in an attempt to create the \"perfect little girl\" using a mixture of \"[[What Are Little Boys Made Of?|sugar, spice, and everything nice]]\". However, he accidentally spilled a mysterious substance called \"Chemical X\" into the mixture, creating three girls and granting all three superpowers including flight, [[Superhuman strength|super strength]], superhuman speed, near invulnerability, x-ray vision, superhuman senses, red heat vision, energy projection, invisibility, and control over lightning and fire. In the original pilot, the accidental substance was [[wikt:open a can of whoop ass|a can of \"Whoopass\"]], which was replaced by \"Chemical X\" in the aired version.<ref name=\"awn\"/>\n\nThe three girls all have oval-shaped heads, abnormally large eyes inspired by [[Margaret Keane]]'s art,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Craig McCracken on Stupid Dogs and Powerful Girls|first=Emru|last=Townsend|url=http://5x5media.com/eye/inte/cmccracken.php|date=Summer 1995|journal=Frames per Second Magazine|issue=6|accessdate=May 29, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810205143/http://5x5media.com/eye/inte/cmccracken.php|archivedate=August 10, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> flat feet and stubby arms and legs, and lack noses, ears, fingers, toes and necks. McCracken preferred them to look more animated rather than going for a \"realistic\" look, meaning fewer body parts were needed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Beyond Good and Evil: To the utterly adorable kicking superheroics of the Powerpuff Girls!|first=Robert|last=Lloyd|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2000-11-30/news/beyond-good-and-evil/4/|date=November 22, 2000|work=LA Weekly|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120906235656/http://www.laweekly.com/2000-11-30/news/beyond-good-and-evil/4/|archivedate=September 6, 2012}}</ref> Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup normally wear dresses that match the colors of their eyes with black stripes, as well as white tights and black [[Mary Jane (shoe)|Mary Janes]]. The closing theme to the cartoon offers a nutshell description of the three Powerpuff Girls' personalities: ''Blossom, commander and the leader. Bubbles, she is the joy and the laughter. Buttercup, she is the toughest fighter.''\n* Blossom (voiced by [[Cathy Cavadini]], [[Grey Delisle]]) is the self-proclaimed leader of the Powerpuff Girls. Her personality ingredient is \"everything nice\", her signature color is pink, and she has long strawberry blonde hair with a red bow.<ref name=\"CN\"/><!--CN source describes her hair as \"fiery red\" not orange--> She was named for having spoken freely and honestly to the Professor shortly after her creation as shown in ''The Powerpuff Girls Movie''. She is often seen as the most level-headed, and composed member of the group and also strong and determined. Her unique abilities include \"Ice Breath\" (develops in \"Ice Sore\"), microscopic vision, and advanced intelligence; she is also a master strategist and apt planner.\n* Bubbles (voiced by [[Tara Strong]], credited as [[Tara Strong|Tara Charendoff]], in the series and by [[Kath Soucie]] in the What a Cartoon! episodes) is the \"softest and sweetest\" of the three.<ref name=\"CN\"/> Her signature color is blue, her personality ingredient is \"sugar\", and she has blonde hair in pigtails. Bubbles is seen as kind and very sweet but she is also capable of extreme rage and can fight monsters just as well as her sisters can. Her best friend is a stuffed octopus doll she calls \"Octi\", and she also loves animals. She exhibits the ability to both understand multiple languages and communicate with various animals, and her unique power is emitting supersonic waves.\n* Buttercup (voiced by [[E. G. Daily]]) is described as a \"tough hotheaded tomboy\".<ref name=\"CN\"/> Her personality ingredient is \"spice\", her signature color is green, and she has black hair in a flip. She loves to get dirty, fights hard and plays rough; she does not plan and is all action.<ref name=\"CN\"/> Buttercup is the only Powerpuff Girl without any unique superpowers (aside from being able to curl her tongue as shown in the episode \"Nuthin' Special\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-powerpuff-girls-2005/episode-15-season-6/nuthin-special/194523|title=Nuthin' Special Episode|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=May 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130306081804/http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-powerpuff-girls-2005/episode-15-season-6/nuthin-special/194523|archive-date=March 6, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> McCracken originally wanted to name the character \"Bud\" until a friend suggested the name Buttercup.<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/>\n\nTheir main arch-enemies throughout the show are a villain by the name of Mojo Jojo (voiced by [[Roger L. Jackson]]), a chimpanzee who always plans to take over Townsville (the character was inspired by a character from a live-action Japanese series), and Him (voiced by [[Tom Kane]]), a mysterious, sinister, and effeminate demon who is able to manipulate events to either drive the Powerpuff Girls insane or drive wedges between them.\n\n                                                                                                                                        \n==Voice Cast==\n*[[Cathy Cavadini]]/[[Grey Delisle]] - Blossom\n*[[Tara Strong]] - Bubbles\n*[[Elizabeth Daily]] - Buttercup\n*[[Tom Kane]] - Professor Utonium, Him\n*[[Jennifer Hale]] - Miss Keane, Sedusa, Princess Morbucks (Season 1-3)\n*[[Tom Kenny]] - Mayor, Snake, Butch, Junior\n*[[Roger L. Jackson]] - Mojo Jojo, Brick\n*[[Rob Paulsen]] - Boomer\n*[[Chuck McCann]] - Bossman, \n*[[Jim Cummings]] - Fuzzy, Slim\n*[[Audrey Wasilewski]] - Sedusa\n*[[Dee Bradley Baker]] - Various characters\n*[[Frank Welker]] - Various characters\n*[[Jill Talley]] - Various characters\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      \n                                                                                                                                  \n===Additional voices===\n[[Mark Hamill]], [[Kath Soucie]], [[Vanessa Marshall]], [[Maurice LaMarche]], Aaron Spann, [[Keone Young]], [[Bob Joles]], [[Sandra Bernhard]], [[Maria Bamford]], [[Paget Brewster]], [[Susanne Blakeslee]], [[Daran Norris]], [[Lori Alan]], [[Candi Milo]], [[Kerri Kenney]], [[Christine Cavanaugh]], [[Tress MacNeille]], [[Jess Harnell]], [[Gail Matthius]], [[Pamela Adlon]], Rachael Macfarlane, [[April Stewart]], [[April Winchell]], [[Sarah Chalke]], [[Pamela Hayden]], [[Josh Peck]], [[Clancy Brown]], [[Nancy Cartwright]], [[Roger Rose]], [[John DiMaggio]], [[Phil LaMarr]], [[Debi Derryberry]], [[Nika Futterman]], [[Wendy Schaal]], [[Julie Nathanson]], [[Cristina Pucelli]], [[Karen Maruyama]], [[Melanie Chartoff]], [[Katey Sagal]], [[Bill Fagerbakke]], [[Jean Smart]], [[Kat Cressida]], Charlie Bean, [[Bob Joles]], [[Teresa Ganzel]], [[Laura Silverman]], [[Nicole Sullivan]], [[Jodi Carlisle]], [[Kathy Griffin]], [[Richard Steven Horvitz]], [[Lara Jill Miller]], [[Cristina Pucelli]], [[June Foray]], [[Phyllis Diller]], [[Sherri Stoner]], [[Peri Gilpin]], [[Kathryn Fiore]], [[Tisha Terrasini Banker]], [[Mindy Sterling]], [[Eliza Jane Schneider]], [[Jason Marsden]], [[Maile Flanagan]], [[Michael Bell]], Mike Bell, [[Carlos Alazraqui]], [[Catherine Taber]], [[Troy Baker]], [[Scott Menville]], [[Sarah Silverman]], [[Nicole Sullivan]], [[Bob Joles]], Lou Romano, [[Townsend Coleman]], Lauri Fraser, [[Kimberly Brooks]], [[Diane Michelle]], [[Janice Kawaye]], Brigitte Bako, [[Pamela Adlon]], [[Hynden Walch]], [[Diane Delano]], Julia Kato, [[Alex Borstein]], [[Kevin Michael Richardson]], [[Tony Pope]], [[Marcia Wallace]], [[Olivia Hack]], [[Gwendoline Yeo]], [[Sirena Irwin]], Pat Pinney, [[Steve Blum]], [[Wally Wingert]], [[Charlie Adler]], [[Karen Strassman]], [[Cheryl Chase]], Colleen Villard, [[David Kaufman]], Jeff Bergman, Veronica Taylor, Lisa Ortiz, Andrea Martin, Frankie Ingrassia, [[Lauren Tom]], [[Marley Shelton]], [[Missi Pyle]], [[Yeardley Smith]], [[Wendee Lee]].                                                                                                                                   \n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         \n===Episodes===\n{{main|List of The Powerpuff Girls episodes}}\n{{:List of The Powerpuff Girls episodes}}                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           \n                                                                                                                                 \n==Production==\n[[File:Whoopass Stew - 1992.png|thumb|left|The first early animated versions of the Powerpuff Girls, who were originally known as the \"Whoopass Girls\"]]\nDuring Craig McCracken's first year in the character animation program of [[CalArts]],<ref>{{cite news|title=SIGNOFF; Never Underestimate the Power of a Puff|first=Daniel|last=Wineman|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/15/tv/signoff-never-underestimate-the-power-of-a-puff.html|date=November 15, 1998|work=The New York Times|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120908114308/http://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/15/tv/signoff-never-underestimate-the-power-of-a-puff.html|archivedate=September 8, 2012}}</ref> he created a series of short cartoons based on a character called \"No Neck Joe\".<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\">{{cite AV media|year=2009|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Who, What, Where, How, Why... Who Cares?}}</ref> In June 1991, he created a drawing of three girls with large eyes, inspired visually by the 'waif' paintings of [[Margaret Keane]],<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=385584741803511808  |user=CrackMcCraigen |title=_LaurenH_ Yes The Powerpuff Girls were inspired by Keane paintings and yes Ms. Keane is named after Margaret. Good catch! |author=Craig McCracken |date=2013-10-03}}</ref> on a small sheet of orange construction paper as a [[birthday card]] design for his brother.<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deviantart.com/cmcc/art/1st-PPG-Drawing-75162491|title=1st PPG Drawing|first=Craig|last=McCracken|date=January 20, 2008|work=CMcC's DeviantArt Gallery|accessdate=May 31, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118094844/https://www.deviantart.com/cmcc/art/1st-PPG-Drawing-75162491|archivedate=November 18, 2018}}</ref> The following year he included the three girls as the main characters of his short film ''Whoopass Stew! The Whoopass Girls in: A Sticky Situation''.<ref name=\"lenburg\">{{cite book|title=Who's Who in Animated Cartoons: An International Guide to Film & Television's Award-winning and Legendary Animators|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|year=2006|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|isbn=978-1-55783-671-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/231 231]|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb|url-access=registration|quote=tartakovsky calarts.|accessdate=May 31, 2011}}</ref> Initially, McCracken wanted to animate four ''Whoopass Girls'' shorts, but only one came to be.<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/> McCracken's shorts were selected to be shown at [[Spike and Mike's Festival of Animation|Spike and Mike's Sick and Twisted Festival of Animation]] in 1994.<ref name=\"lenburg\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Spike and Mike's&nbsp;\u2013 A Brief History |url=http://spikeandmike.com/sitepages/press.php |work=SpikeandMike.com |date=July 3, 2011 |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703084323/http://spikeandmike.com/sitepages/press.php |archivedate=July 3, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Craig_and_Lauren_in_08.jpg|thumb|right|''The Powerpuff Girls'' was created by [[Craig McCracken]], and his wife [[Lauren Faust]] was a director and writer for the later seasons.]]\nWhile working on ''[[2 Stupid Dogs]]'' in 1992, McCracken's ''Whoopass Girls'' short was picked up for a series by Cartoon Network. However, the name ''Whoopass'' had to be dropped for the channel to include it as part of its new ''[[What a Cartoon!]]'' animated shorts showcase. McCracken explained it was because many executives at Cartoon Network didn't think that anyone would make toys for kids with the word \"ass\" in it. So the title was changed and became ''The Powerpuff Girls'', the name Whoopass was also changed to Powerpuff by Craig McCracken, and the \"can of whoop ass\" was renamed \"Chemical X\".<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/> McCracken's new short, entitled \"The Powerpuff Girls in: Meat Fuzzy Lumpkins\", aired as part the network's ''World Premiere Toon-In'' on February 20, 1995.<ref name=\"apcm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/ap/cmccracken.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310030357/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/ap/cmccracken.html|archivedate=March 10, 2007|title=Animator Profile: CRAIG McCRACKEN|work=CartoonNetwork.com|accessdate=March 26, 2007}}</ref> The short was not as popular as ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'', a project McCracken and former classmate [[Genndy Tartakovsky]] (who also directed many episodes of ''Powerpuff Girls'') worked on together; being the most popular of the shorts, ''Dexter's Laboratory'' was the first to be greenlit by the network.<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/><ref>{{cite news|title='Star Wars' goes animated tonight|first=Mike|last=Snider|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2003-11-06-animated-star-wars_x.htm|date=November 6, 2003|work=USA Today|accessdate=May 28, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130428103917/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2003-11-06-animated-star-wars_x.htm|archivedate=April 28, 2013}}</ref> Cartoon Network executive [[Mike Lazzo]] (who later serve as the executive producer for [[Williams Street]] in the [[Samurai Jack (season 5)|fifth season]] of ''[[Samurai Jack]]'') allowed McCracken to produce a new ''Powerpuff Girls'' short titled \"Crime 101\", which aired on ''What a Cartoon!'' in early 1996. Announcer [[Ernie Anderson]], the narrator of the pilot episodes, died of cancer in 1997, and he was replaced by [[Tom Kenny]] for the remainder of the series.<ref>{{cite news|title=TV's Ghoulardi was 'a wild man'|first=Christopher|last=Borrelli|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3mNPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gwMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1305,2621618&dq=ernie+anderson+death&hl=en|date=February 8, 1997|work=The Toledo Blade|accessdate=May 29, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312044938/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3mNPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gwMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1305,2621618&dq=ernie+anderson+death&hl=en|archive-date=March 12, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Powerpuff Girls'' series made its debut on November 18, 1998, and was the highest rated premiere in Cartoon Network's history at the time. During its run, the series consistently scored the highest rating for an original series each week for the network across a wide range of demographics\u2014from young children to adults.<ref name=\"awn\">{{cite journal|first=Rick|last=DeMott|date=October 2000|title=The Powerpuff Girls' Phenomenal Merchandising Mantra|journal=Animation World Magazine|volume=5|issue=7|publisher=Animation World Network|accessdate=May 26, 2011|url=http://www.awn.com/mag/issue5.07/5.07pages/demottppg.php3|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130102004513/http://www.awn.com/mag/issue5.07/5.07pages/demottppg.php3|archivedate=January 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,276431,00.html|title=Girl Power|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=June 16, 2000|accessdate=December 1, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20141117191107/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,276431,00.html|archivedate=November 17, 2014}}</ref> In October 2000, Cartoon Network credited the series for its Friday night prime time [[Ratings (broadcast)|ratings]] win among cable networks.<ref name=\"tw\">{{cite web|first=Laurie |last=Goldberg |url=http://www.timewarner.com/corp/newsroom/pr/0,20812,667918,00.html |date=October 11, 2001 |title=Cartoon Network Tops Weekly and Friday Prime Ratings for the Week of Oct. 2\u20138 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010539/http://www.timewarner.com/corp/newsroom/pr/0%2C20812%2C667918%2C00.html |archivedate=September 27, 2007 |publisher=Time Warner |accessdate=March 29, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> By the end of 2000, merchandising based on the series encompassed a whole variety of products, including T-shirts, toys, video games, lunchboxes, and dishware.<ref name=\"awn\"/> Concerning the show's success, Craig McCracken has stated, \"I thought it would get on Cartoon Network and college kids would watch it and there would be a few random T-shirts out there in the [[rave]] scene or in record shops. But I had no idea that it would take off to this extent.\"<ref name=\"awn\"/> <!-- Some mention needs to be made here about the movie and the change in animation style. ---> Following the series' fourth season, the closing of [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]] and the death of its executive [[William Hanna]] in 2001, McCracken left it to focus on his new animated series, ''[[Foster's Home for Imaginary Friends]]'', leaving [[Chris Savino]] to take his place while production of ''The Powerpuff Girls'' was moved to [[Cartoon Network Studios]].<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/> The show's last original run episode was on March 25, 2005; in all, six seasons were made.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altiusdirectory.com/Entertainment/cartoon-network-original-series.html|title=Cartoon Network Original Series|work=altiusdirectory.com|accessdate=May 21, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120718080334/http://www.altiusdirectory.com/Entertainment/cartoon-network-original-series.html|archivedate=July 18, 2012}}</ref> Cartoon Network had offered to give McCracken and Savino a seventh season of the series, but they believed six was enough, and that the series had run its course.<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/> Much of the people who worked on the new seasons also worked on seasons 3 and 4 of ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'', but included other new crew members, such as [[Thurop Van Orman]], who then created ''[[The Marvelous Misadventures of Flapjack]]'' in 2008. \n\nAll of the original episodes were hand-drawn and produced at [[Rough Draft Studios]] in South Korea,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roughdraftstudios.com/press/press_20040115.html |title=Special Report: Animation |first=Ray |last=Richmond |date=January 15, 2004 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=January 15, 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310222309/http://www.roughdraftstudios.com/press/press_20040115.html |archivedate=March 10, 2008 }}</ref> except the ''What a Cartoon!'' shorts, with the first one being animated at Animal House in Japan and Shanghai Morning Sun Animation in China and the second being animated at Fil Cartoons in the Philippines. [[James L. Venable]], Thomas Chase, & [[Stephen Rucker]] composed the opening theme of the series, and Scottish band [[Bis (Scottish band)|Bis]] performed the ending theme song,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1425853/bis-lends-hand-powerpuff-girls.jhtml|title=Bis Lends A Hand To \"The Powerpuff Girls\"|date=November 5, 1998|work=MTV.com|publisher=MTV Networks|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130129045540/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1425853/bis-lends-hand-powerpuff-girls.jhtml|archivedate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> as played during the credits. The opening theme uses a sped-up drum break sample of \"[[Funky Drummer]]\" performed by [[Clyde Stubblefield]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Rabb|first=Johnny|title=Jungle/Drum 'n' Bass for the Acoustic Drum Set: A Guide to Applying Today's Electronic Music to the Drum Set|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=o6AUnTjzj3UC&pg=PA16&lpg=PA16&dq=Clyde+Stubblefield+powerpuff#v=onepage&q=Clyde%20Stubblefield%20powerpuff&f=false|publisher=Alfred Music Publishing|isbn=978-0-7579-9025-0|page=16|chapter=Contributing to the Future: An Interview with Clyde Stubblefield|date=November 1, 2001}}</ref>\n\n===Tenth anniversary special===\nIn August 2008, McCracken revealed on his [[DeviantArt]] account, as had been announced in that year's Comic Con, that he was working with Cartoon Network on a new half-hour ''Powerpuff Girls'' special to celebrate the series' tenth anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cmcc.deviantart.com/journal/I-m-back-236070911|title=I'm back|first=Craig|last=McCracken|date=August 9, 2008|work=CMcC's DeviantArt Journal|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120715154409/http://cmcc.deviantart.com/journal/I-m-back-236070911|archivedate=July 15, 2012}}</ref> The special, titled \"The Powerpuff Girls Rule!!!\", aired on the Pan-Euro Cartoon Network on November 29, 2008, on the Powerpuff Girls Birthday Marathon, and in the United States on January 19, 2009, as part of its 10th anniversary marathon. Unlike previous episodes in the series, the anniversary special was animated using [[Adobe Flash]] at Cartoon Network Studios.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coldhardflash.com/2009/01/powerpuff-girls-10th-anniversary-interview-with-creator-craig-mccracken.html|title=Powerpuff Girls 10th Anniversary Interview With Creator Craig McCracken|first=Aaron|last=Simpson|date=January 16, 2009|work=ColdHardFlash.com|accessdate=January 16, 2009|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120707195019/http://coldhardflash.com/2009/01/powerpuff-girls-10th-anniversary-interview-with-creator-craig-mccracken.html|archivedate=July 7, 2012}}</ref> In March 2012, the series returned to Cartoon Network in reruns on the revived block, [[Cartoon Planet]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Walton |first=Zach |title=Cartoon Network Brings Back The Classics With Cartoon Planet |url=http://www.webpronews.com/cartoon-network-brings-back-the-classics-with-cartoon-planet-2012-03 |date=March 29, 2012 |work=WebProNews |publisher=iEntry Network |accessdate=March 31, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918192456/http://www.webpronews.com/cartoon-network-brings-back-the-classics-with-cartoon-planet-2012-03 |archivedate=September 18, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===2014 special===\n[[File:PowerpuffgirlsCGI.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Powerpuff Girls in the 2014 special.]]\n\nOn January 28, 2013, a new [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] special titled ''Powerpuff Girls: Dance Pantsed'' was announced to premiere that year, though it was later delayed to January 20, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-girls-are-back-in-townsville-the-powerpuff-girls-save-the-world-before-bedtime-again-in-all-new-special-236028091.html|title=The Girls Are Back in Townsville! The Powerpuff Girls Save the World Before Bedtime Again in All-New Special|work=PR Newswire|date=December 16, 2013|accessdate=January 14, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140115002624/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-girls-are-back-in-townsville-the-powerpuff-girls-save-the-world-before-bedtime-again-in-all-new-special-236028091.html|archivedate=January 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=VIDEO: \"The Powerpuff Girls: Dance Pantsed\" Sneak Peak|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2014/01/07/video-the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed-sneak-peak|publisher=Crunchyroll|date=January 7, 2014|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> Former [[The Beatles|Beatle]] [[Ringo Starr]] promoted the special on Cartoon Network singing a new original song \"I Wish I Was a Powerpuff Girl\" with previews leading up to the airdate. Ringo also voiced a new character named [[Fibonacci sequence|Fibonacci Sequins]] in the episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2012/11/14/ringo-starr-voicing-powerpuff-girls-character-starting-work.html|title=Ringo Starr Voicing \"Powerpuff Girls\" Character, Starting Work on New CD|work=abcnewsradioonline.com|accessdate=December 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121219192818/http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2012/11/14/ringo-starr-voicing-powerpuff-girls-character-starting-work.html|archivedate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> The special was directed by Dave Smith, who directed episodes for the series in the past, and featured the original cast members reprising their roles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/341049/scitech/geeksandgaming/the-powerpuff-girls-return-in-cgi-in-January|title=The Powerpuff Girls return in CGI in January|author=Mikael Angelo Francisco|work=gmanetwork.com|date=December 23, 2013|accessdate=January 14, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140115004436/http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/341049/scitech/geeksandgaming/the-powerpuff-girls-return-in-cgi-in-january|archivedate=January 15, 2014}}</ref> This ''Powerpuff Girls ''special marked the first time that series creator [[Craig McCracken]] had no input.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/news/powerpuff-girls-return-to-cartoon-network-with-january-special|title='Powerpuff Girls' return to Cartoon Network with January special|work=hitfix.com|date=December 18, 2013|accessdate=December 22, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131222211208/http://www.hitfix.com/news/powerpuff-girls-return-to-cartoon-network-with-january-special|archivedate=December 22, 2013}}</ref> The episode's plot has Mojo Jojo kidnap Fibonacci along with an opera singer and a badger. The girls rescue all of them, and the Powerpuff Girls defeat Mojo yet again. Not deterred, he then goes on to invent an evil video game called \"Dance Pants R-EVILution\" (a parody of the video game ''[[Dance Dance Revolution]]'') to take over Townsville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/ringo-starr-joins-powerpuff-girls-special-20131220|title=Ringo Starr Joins 'Powerpuff Girls' Special|work=rollingstone.com|date=December 20, 2013|accessdate=December 22, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131222234111/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/ringo-starr-joins-powerpuff-girls-special-20131220|archivedate=December 22, 2013}}</ref> [[Common Sense Media]] gave the special 3/5 stars citing the \"tasteful update of the original animation style\" however recommends it for older kids around the age of 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Dance Pantsed|work=commonsensemedia.org|accessdate=January 22, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140122145637/http://m.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed|archivedate=January 22, 2014}}</ref> GON (Geeked Out Nation) gave the show a B rank and described it as \"...a good special with the return of the characters that many of us grew up [with]\", while they said that the special has few flaws.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geekedoutnation.com/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed-review|title=The Powerpuff Girls: \"Dance Pantsed\" Review|work=geekedoutnation.com|date=January 25, 2014|accessdate=April 29, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140428042645/http://www.geekedoutnation.com/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed-review|archivedate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> Den of Geek gave the special a 2.5 out 5 said \"The Powerpuff reboot needs those paddles to jump-start it. I want more. But I want better.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/the-powerpuff-girls/232317/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed-review|title=The Powerpuff Girls, Dance Pantsed, review|work=denofgeek.us|date=January 20, 2014|accessdate=April 29, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140428020050/http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/the-powerpuff-girls/232317/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed-review|archivedate=April 28, 2014}}</ref>\n<!--Please do NOT add the new re-boot info here, it is unrelated to the original series or its production.-->\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Merchandise and media==\n===Anime and manga===\n{{Main|Powerpuff Girls Z}}\nIn April 2005, plans for a Japanese [[anime]] version, ''Demashita! Powerpuff Girls Z'', were announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://omelete.uol.com.br/series-e-tv/meninas-superpoderosas-em-versao-anime/|title=Meninas Superpoderosas em vers\u00e3o anim\u00ea|first=Alexandre|last=Nagado|date=April 7, 2005|work=Omlete.com.br|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120914024457/http://omelete.uol.com.br/series-e-tv/meninas-superpoderosas-em-versao-anime/|archivedate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> The series premiered in Japan the following year with 52 half-hour episodes, airing each Saturday from July 1 to December 23, 2006, and from January 6 to June 30, 2007. The series deviated from its American predecessor in terms of style, storyline, and characterization, but only minimally retained the essential themes that made the original a success.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/culture/2006/07/10/powerpuff-girls-re-anime-ted/|title='Powerpuff Girls' re-anime-ted|first=Jason|last=Lloren|date=July 10, 2006|work=SFGate.com|publisher=Hearst Communications|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120911070300/http://blog.sfgate.com/culture/2006/07/10/powerpuff-girls-re-anime-ted/|archivedate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> The characters feature three junior high school students Momoko Akatsutsumi (Hyper Blossom), Miyako Gotokuji (Rolling Bubbles), and Kaoru Matsubara (Powered Buttercup) as the three heroes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetworkasia.com/minisite/ppgz/characters.php|title=PowerPuff Girls Z Characters|work=cartoonnetworkasia.com|accessdate=January 14, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116101146/http://www.cartoonnetworkasia.com/minisite/ppgz/characters.php|archivedate=January 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A [[manga]] adaptation, illustrated by Shiho Komiyuno, was serialized in [[Shueisha]]'s [[Ribon|''Ribon'' magazine]] between June 2006 and July 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ribon.shueisha.co.jp/|title=Ribon Magazine (In Japanese)|work=ribon.shueisha.co.jp|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140313225732/http://ribon.shueisha.co.jp/|archivedate=March 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\n{{Main|The Powerpuff Girls Movie}}\n''The Powerpuff Girls Movie'' was released in the United States on July 3, 2002 by [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]] and Cartoon Network.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,266671,00.html|title=Movie Review: The Powerpuff Girls Movie (2002)|first=Lisa|last=Schwarzbaum|date=July 2, 2002|work=EW.com|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130122133537/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,266671,00.html|archivedate=January 22, 2013}}</ref> The movie, a prequel to the series, tells the story of how the Powerpuff Girls were created, and how Mojo Jojo (voiced by: [[Roger L. Jackson]]) became a supervillain. After Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup were created by [[Professor Utonium]] to help the city against crime, they end up only causing chaos in Townsville. Down about how everyone refers to them as freaks, they turn to Mojo Jojo, a monkey who says he is there to help make people like them again. Unknown to the girls, Mojo Jojo was Professor Utonium's lab chimp helper who was mutated when the Powerpuff Girls were made. The mishap made him super smart, and he has become jealous of the girls. Mojo Jojo ends up tricking the girls into helping him make a machine to mutate other chimps. Seeing what they have done, the kids run away in shame, but come back after seeing Professor Utonium in trouble. Blossom, Bubbles and Buttercup end up beating Mojo Jojo and his army of mutated smart chimps and save the day, thus becoming Townsville's new defenders.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/03/movies/film-review-they-have-a-tantrum-then-save-the-world.html|title=FILM REVIEW; They Have A Tantrum, Then Save The World|first=Stephen|last=Holden|date=July 3, 2002|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130130144331/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/03/movies/film-review-they-have-a-tantrum-then-save-the-world.html|archivedate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> The movie received a rating of 63% at Rotten Tomatoes, and received some criticism for the violence involved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/powerpuff_girls_movie/|title=The Powerpuff Girls&nbsp;\u2013 The Movie (2002)|work=RottenTomatoes.com|accessdate=July 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120913174512/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/powerpuff_girls_movie/|archivedate=September 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/movies/article/Violence-overpowers-Powerpuff-Girls-1090464.php|first=Paula|last=Nechak|title=Violence overpowers 'Powerpuff Girls'|date=July 2, 2002|work=Seattlepi.com|publisher=Hearst Communications|accessdate=May 21, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120910030214/http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/movies/article/Violence-overpowers-Powerpuff-Girls-1090464.php|archivedate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> In all, the movie grossed $16 million worldwide with an $11 million budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=powerpuffgirls.htm|title=The Powerpuff Girls Movie|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120721182808/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=powerpuffgirls.htm|archivedate=July 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|List of The Powerpuff Girls soundtracks}}\nThree CD soundtracks were officially released for the series. The first, entitled ''Heroes & Villains'', features original songs about the ''Powerpuff Girls'' characters by a number of artists, including the [[New wave music|new wave]] group [[Devo]], [[Bis (Scottish band)|Bis]], [[The Apples in Stereo]] and [[Black Francis|Frank Black]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Powerpuff Girls Heroes & Villains&nbsp;\u2013 Powerpuff Girls: Heroes & Villains Soundtrack CD|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/1119004/a/Powerpuff+Girls%3A+Heroes+%26+Villains.htm|work=CDUniverse.com|accessdate=June 2, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120722190024/http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/1119004/a/Powerpuff+Girls:+Heroes+%26+Villains.htm|archivedate=July 22, 2012}}</ref> The first album did well, topping the ''[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]''{{'}}s children's music chart for six weeks.<ref name=\"autogenerated2001\"/> Another album entitled ''The City of Soundsville'' features electronica-style character themes and also did well with critics.<ref>{{cite web|title=Powerpuff Girls: The City of Soundsville&nbsp;\u2014 The Powerpuff Girls|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/the-powerpuff-girls/powerpuff-girls-the-city-of-soundsville/494900|work=Billboard.com|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5oCpvZ3dV?url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/the-powerpuff-girls/powerpuff-girls-the-city-of-soundsville/494900|archive-date=March 13, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Heather|last=Phares|title=Review: ''Powerpuff Girls: The City of Soundsville&nbsp;\u2014 The Powerpuff Girls'' |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r550183/review|pure_url=yes}}|work=Allmusic.com|publisher=Rovi|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref> The third album, entitled ''Power Pop'', features a more teen-oriented variety of pop songs. This third and final album was considered a \"big disappointment\" and was not received as well as the previous albums.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-powerpuff-girls-power-pop-mw0000320918|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Power Pop Review|first=Heather|last=Phares|work=Allmusic.com|publisher=Rovi|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909210317/http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-powerpuff-girls-power-pop-mw0000320918|archive-date=September 9, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The British girl group [[Sugababes]] also released a song called \"[[Angels with Dirty Faces (Sugababes song)|Angels with Dirty Faces]]\" to promote ''[[The Powerpuff Girls Movie]].'' The song received generally positive reviews from critics, and peaked at number seven on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2002-11-23/|title=2002-11-23 Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive|work=[[UK Singles Chart]]|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=12 January 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130620195340/http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2002-11-23/|archivedate=June 20, 2013}}</ref>{{efn|\"Angels with Dirty Faces\" charted on the [[UK Singles Chart]] as part of its double A-side release with \"[[Stronger (Sugababes song)|Stronger]]\".<ref name=\"UK\"/>}} The music video hearkens to \"[[Nano of the North]]\", an episode from the fourth season of ''The Powerpuff Girls'',<ref name=\"Video\">{{cite video|people=[[Sugababes]]|year=2002|title=Angels with Dirty Faces|type = DVD|publisher=Island Records}}</ref> in which each Sugababes member portrays a Powerpuff Girl.<ref name=\"Video\"/>\n\n===Parodies and comics===\n\n<!--In 2003 a parody was done by [[MADtv]] in its [[MADtv (season 9)|ninth season]] called \"The Powerslut Girls\". The parody has [[Tara Reid]], [[Brittany Murphy]], and [[Paris Hilton]] as the superheroines.--> <!--Would love to add but I do not have reliable source for it-->\n\nA crossover parody of ''The Powerpuff Girls'' and ''[[2 Broke Girls]]'' was done in the second season of Cartoon Network's TV series ''[[Mad (TV series)|MAD]]'', known as \"2 Broke Powerpuff Girls\". The parody, which aired on January 30, 2012, is of Bubbles and Buttercup, who are broke and work for \"Him\" in a diner after the show got placed on permanent [[hiatus (television)|hiatus]]. [[Tara Strong]] (Bubbles) and [[Tom Kane]] (\"Him\") reprised their roles here.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Mad-Mash-Up-1042213.aspx|title=Mad Mash-up: 2 Broke Powerpuff Girls|work=Tvguide.com|accessdate=May 10, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130204220154/http://www.tvguide.com/News/Mad-Mash-Up-1042213.aspx|archivedate=February 4, 2013|date=January 26, 2012}}</ref> The ''MAD'' episode with the parody ranked #26/30 for the week with 1.903 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2012/02/01/mondays-cable-ratings-pawn-stars-leads-the-pack-once-again-568210/cable_20120130/#EY1Z6xL8rHr0bfr9.99|title=Monday's Cable Ratings: \"Pawn Stars\" Leads the Pack Once Again|author=The Futon Critic Staff|work=The Futon Critic|date=February 1, 2012|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130204003821/http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2012/02/01/mondays-cable-ratings-pawn-stars-leads-the-pack-once-again-568210/cable_20120130/%23EY1Z6xL8rHr0bfr9.99|archivedate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> In February 2013, [[IDW Publishing]] announced a partnership with Cartoon Network to produce comics based on its properties and this series was one of the titles announced to be published.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idwpublishing.com/news/article/2507/ |title=IDW Teams Up with Cartoon Network! |date=February 25, 2013 |publisher=IDW |accessdate=May 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140804051016/http://idwpublishing.com/news/article/2507 |archivedate=August 4, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nA fan-produced webcomic series called ''PowerPuff Girls [[Doujinshi]]'' was created in 2004 and released through [[Snafu Comics]]. The girls are shown to be a bit older, but with the same personalities as, their T.V. counterparts, and the comic includes many characters from other Cartoon Network shows. The story has the kids now going to school in a neighboring city of Townsville known as Megaville.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicbooked.com/webcomic-review-powerpuff-girls-doujinshi/|title=Webcomic Review: Powerpufff Girls Doujunshu|work=comicbooked.com|accessdate=May 12, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120910031221/http://www.comicbooked.com/webcomic-review-powerpuff-girls-doujinshi/|archivedate=September 10, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The comic was the \"Outstanding Superhero Comic\" and \"Outstanding Character Art\" winner on the [[Web Cartoonist's Choice Awards]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccawards.com/2005_ceremony.htm |title=2005 Web Cartoonists' Choice Award Celebration! |work=CCAwards.com |publisher=Web Cartoonist's Choice Awards Committee |accessdate=July 10, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708125905/http://www.ccawards.com/2005_ceremony.htm |archivedate=July 8, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nShortly after the 2014 CGI special's release, a comic which was published by [[IDW Publishing]] was withdrawn after retailers complained that they wanted to boycott the issue. The comic, which shows the Powerpuff Girls with [[breast]]s and dressed in [[Latex clothing|latex]], was designed by an artist who works for Cartoon Network. The artist was \"thinking of it more along the lines of 'female empowerment' than the kind of thing you guys are talking about\". Cartoon Network said in a statement: \"We recognise some fans' reaction to the cover and, as such, will no longer be releasing it at comic book shops.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jan/24/powerpuff-girls-sexualised-comic-withdrawn|title='Sexualised' Powerpuff Girls comic judged a boob by TV network|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=January 24, 2014|accessdate=February 15, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140216033429/http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jan/24/powerpuff-girls-sexualised-comic-withdrawn|archivedate=February 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Toys===\nFrom 1999\u20132002, [[Trendmasters]] made Powerpuff Girls dolls and action figures. From August 21 to October 1, 2000, [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway]] promoted the series with four toys in their [[kids' meal]]s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Subway Teams Up with Powerpuff Girls|url=http://www.qsrmagazine.com/news/subway-teams-powerpuff-girls|date=July 7, 2000|work=QSR Magazine|publisher=Journalistic|accessdate=August 8, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222202903/http://www.qsrmagazine.com/news/subway-teams-powerpuff-girls|archive-date=February 22, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> A set of six kids' meal toys was available as part of an April 2001 [[Dairy Queen]] promotion, which also included a sweepstakes offering the ''Powerpuff Girls'' VHS ''Boogie Frights''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dairy Queen|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Dairy+Queen.-a072467312|date=March 20, 2001|work=Ice Cream Reporter|accessdate=August 8, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130808232914/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Dairy+Queen.-a072467312|archivedate=August 8, 2013}}</ref> [[Jack in the Box]] released six ''Powerpuff Girls'' toys in July 2002 as a tie-in for ''The Powerpuff Girls Movie''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Powerpuff Girls Soar into Jack's|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Powerpuff+Girls+Soar+into+Jack%27s%3B+Crime-Fighting+Cuties+Team+Up+With...-a087912566|date=June 28, 2002|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|accessdate=August 8, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130809015238/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Powerpuff+Girls+Soar+into+Jack's;+Crime-Fighting+Cuties+Team+Up+With...-a087912566|archivedate=August 9, 2013}}</ref> On February 10, 2003, [[Burger King]] began a four-week promotion featuring ''The Powerpuff Girls'' and ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'' toys as well as special codes to redeem online for Cartoon Network's [[Cartoon Orbit]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Powerpuff Girls(TM) And Dragon Ball Z(R) Bring Three Exclusive Toys To Every Burger King(R) Big Kids Meal|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+Powerpuff+Girls%28TM%29+And+Dragon+Ball+Z%28R%29+Bring+Two+Exclusive+Toys...-a097428934|date=February 10, 2003|work=PR Newswire|publisher=United Business Media|accessdate=August 8, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130809015222/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+Powerpuff+Girls(TM)+And+Dragon+Ball+Z(R)+Bring+Two+Exclusive+Toys...-a097428934|archivedate=August 9, 2013}}</ref> In the United Kingdom the characters of Buttercup and Mojo Jojo were given away in [[Kelloggs]] cereal boxes as part of the Cartoon Network Wobble Heads in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|title=2003 - Frosties Cartoon Network Wobble Heads Free in Packets|url=http://cerealoffers.com/Kelloggs/Frosties/2000/Cartoon_Network_Wobble_Heads/cartoon_network_wobble_heads.html|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190622001621/http://cerealoffers.com/Kelloggs/Frosties/2000/Cartoon_Network_Wobble_Heads/cartoon_network_wobble_heads.html|archivedate=June 22, 2019}}</ref> In August 24, 2018, the 2 sets of LEGO had released in United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://brickset.com/article/36124/first-images-of-powerpuff-girls-sets |title=First images of Powerpuff Girls sets |publisher=Brickset |accessdate=2018-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://brickset.com/article/34355/powerpuff-girls-full-minifig-lineup-revealed |title=Powerpuff Girls: full minifig lineup revealed |publisher=Brickset |accessdate=2018-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://brickset.com/article/34316/powerpuff-girls-minifigs-revealed |title=Powerpuff Girls minifigs revealed |publisher=Brickset |accessdate=2018-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bricksfanz.com/first-look-at-lego-powerpuff-girls-sets/ |title=First Look At LEGO Powerpuff Girls Sets |publisher=Brickfanz |accessdate=2018-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bricksfanz.com/powerpuff-girls-lego-line-up-revealed/ |title=Powerpuff Girls LEGO Line-up Revealed |publisher=Brickfanz |accessdate=2018-02-16}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n{{Main|List of The Powerpuff Girls video games}}\nSeveral video games were made for this show all being action in genre. ''The Powerpuff Girls: Bad Mojo Jojo'', released on November 14, 2000, follows Blossom as she tries to beat Mojo Jojo.<ref>[[GameSpot]]. [http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo/techinfo/platform/gbc/ Tech Info for the Powerpuff Girls: Bad Mojo Jojo] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109061346/http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo/techinfo/platform/gbc/ |date=November 9, 2012 }}. [[GameSpot]]. Retrieved on February 1, 2008.</ref> The game was called \"simple and boring\" by [[GameSpot]] and was a failure critically.<ref name=GameSpot>Donald, Ryan Mac (December 4, 2000). [http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo/reviews/powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo-review-2660964/ The Powerpuff Girls: Bad Mojo Jojo Review] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109061420/http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo/reviews/powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo-review-2660964/ |date=November 9, 2012 }}. [[GameSpot]]. Retrieved on February 1, 2008.</ref><ref>Harris, Chris (December 1, 2000). [http://www.ign.com/articles/2000/12/02/powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo The Powerpuff Girls: Bad Mojo Jojo Review] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102115958/http://www.ign.com/articles/2000/12/02/powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo |date=November 2, 2012 }}. [[IGN]]. Retrieved on February 1, 2008.</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: Paint the Townsville Green'', another game released in November 2000, follows Buttercup as she fights crime.<ref>[http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-paint-the-townsville-green/gbc-16762 The Powerpuff Girls: Paint the Townsville Green] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102115944/http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-paint-the-townsville-green/gbc-16762 |date=November 2, 2012 }}. [[IGN]]. Retrieved on February 4, 2008.</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: Battle HIM'' follows Bubbles in her fight against HIM and was released in February 2001.<ref>[[GameSpot]]. [http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-battle-him/platform/gbc/ Tech Info for The Powerpuff Girls: Battle HIM] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109092537/http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-battle-him/platform/gbc/ |date=November 9, 2012 }}. [[GameSpot]]. Retrieved on June 26, 2011.</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: Chemical X-traction'' was released in October 2001, where the girls battle enemies in a variety of settings in order to reclaim Chemical X and track down Mojo Jojo, who fed the material to all the villains in Townsville. [[IGN]] gave the game a positive review while giving the [[PlayStation (console)|PSone]] version a 2.0/10 bad review.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-chemical-x-traction/n64-16829|title=The Powerpuff Girls-x-traction|website=IGN|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817015111/http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-chemical-x-traction/n64-16829|archive-date=August 17, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/11/30/power-puff-girls-chemical-x-traction IGN Reviews] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120115533/http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/11/30/power-puff-girls-chemical-x-traction |date=November 20, 2012 }} Powerpuff Girls: Chemical X-traction (PS1 version)</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: Relish Rampage'' was released in November 2002. All three girls are playable in a 3D world, and the game received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/ps2/561541-the-powerpuff-girls-relish-rampage/data|title=Release Information for PlayStation 2 on GameFAQs|work=[[GameFAQs]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=May 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102133803/http://www.gamefaqs.com/ps2/561541-the-powerpuff-girls-relish-rampage/data|archive-date=November 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: Mojo Jojo A-Go-Go'' released in 2001 centers around the name of the Powerpuff Girls' mission to stop Mojo Jojo and his minions. The game received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/01/25/powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go|title=Mojo-jojo-a-go-go review|website=IGN|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221125350/http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/01/25/powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go|archive-date=February 21, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go/reviews/powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go-review-2837304/|title=Mojo-jojo-a-go-go review (Gamestop)|work=www.gamespot.com|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926185651/http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go/reviews/powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go-review-2837304/|archive-date=September 26, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: HIM and Seek'' was released in 2002 where the girls battle their variety of enemies through Townsville while on a scavenger hunt. The game received mostly positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.ign.com/articles/2002/12/09/powerpuff-girls-him-and-seek|title=HIM and Seek review from IGN Dec. 09, 2002|access-date=March 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308173118/http://m.ign.com/articles/2002/12/09/powerpuff-girls-him-and-seek|archive-date=March 8, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[PC games]] were also made for the series. These include: ''The Powerpuff Girls: Mojo Jojo Clone Zone'', ''The Powerpuff Girls: Princess Snorebucks'', ''The Powerpuff Girls: Mojo Jojo's Pet Project'', and ''The Powerpuff Girls: Gamesville''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcworld.idg.com.au/review/software_and_services/the_learning_company/the_powerpuff_girls_mojo_jojo_s_clone_zone/218756|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Mojo Jojo Clone Zone|work=www.pcworld.idg.com.au|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028184026/http://www.pcworld.idg.com.au/review/software_and_services/the_learning_company/the_powerpuff_girls_mojo_jojo_s_clone_zone/218756|archive-date=October 28, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-learning-challenge-2-princess-snorebucks/pc-854911|title=The Powerpuff Girls Learning Challenge 2: Princess Snorebucks|website=IGN|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109050531/http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-learning-challenge-2-princess-snorebucks/pc-854911|archive-date=November 9, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=36826|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Mojo Jojo's Pet Project|work=www.allgame.com|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424110216/http://allgame.com/game.php?id=36826|archive-date=April 24, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-gamesville/pc-491680|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Gamesville|website=IGN|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816034729/http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-gamesville/pc-491680|archive-date=August 16, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\nIn a 2000 ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' review, Marc Bernadin complimented the show on its \"spot-on pop-culture acumen\" and \"unparalleled sense of fun\", giving it a warm welcome from earlier \"lame\" superhero cartoons that he grew up with.<ref>{{cite news|title=TV on DVD Review: The Powerpuff Girls|first=Marc|last=Bernadin|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20232855,00.html|date=June 3, 2000|work=EW.com|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130122194831/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20232855,00.html|archivedate=January 22, 2013}}</ref> Peter Marks of ''[[The New York Times]]'' noted the show's use of adult humor and pop culture references, declaring it \"the sort of playful satire that can appeal as much to a viewer of 37 as 7.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=TELEVISION/RADIO; Now Mom and Dad Are Going Cartoon-Crazy, Too|first=Peter|last=Marks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/16/arts/television-radio-now-mom-and-dad-are-going-cartoon-crazy-too.html|date=April 16, 2000|work=The New York Times|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130130122120/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/16/arts/television-radio-now-mom-and-dad-are-going-cartoon-crazy-too.html|archivedate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> Joly Herman of [[Common Sense Media]] describes the show as a \"cute, highly stylized series thrills the senses with its strange characters, funny situations, and lots of lowbrow humor\". She goes on to say, however, that the show does go from innocent to violent in no time and that there is not much protecting young viewers against the violent undertones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls|title=Tv reviews Powerpuff Girls|first=Joly|last=Herman|work=[[Common Sense Media]]|accessdate=May 15, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120723133202/http://www.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls|archivedate=July 23, 2012|date=May 25, 2007}}</ref> Robert Lloyd of the ''[[Los Angeles Times|LA Times]]'' said that the series might be \"[[transgressive art|transgressive]]\" based on little violence but \"also cute.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Review: 'Powerpuff Girls Rule!!!'|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/01/review-powerpuf.html|date=January 19, 2009|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=May 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429180731/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/01/review-powerpuf.html|archive-date=April 29, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[TV Guide]] chose the Powerpuff Girls as No. 13 in a list of the 50 Greatest cartoon characters of all time.<ref>{{cite news|title=TV Guide's 50 greatest cartoon characters of all time |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2002-07-30/entertainment/cartoon.characters.list_1_ren-and-stimpy-tv-guide-space-ghost?_s=PM:SHOWBIZ |date=July 30, 2002 |work=CNN |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008180927/http://articles.cnn.com/2002-07-30/entertainment/cartoon.characters.list_1_ren-and-stimpy-tv-guide-space-ghost?_s=PM%3ASHOWBIZ |archivedate=October 8, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[IGN]] ranked the series 18th in its Top 25 Primetime Animated Series of All Time list in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/29/top-25-primetime-animated-series-of-all-time?page=2|title=Top 25 Primetime Animated Series of All Time|date=September 28, 2006|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=January 27, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314072017/http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/29/top-25-primetime-animated-series-of-all-time?page=2|archive-date=March 14, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Delta Express]] promoted the series by having a [[Boeing 737-200]] jet painted with a special [[Aircraft livery|livery]] featuring the characters Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup on its exterior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airliners.net/photo/Delta-Express/Boeing-737-232-Adv/0224180&photo_nr=13&prev_id=0230336&next_id=0220519|title=Picture of the Boeing 737-232/Adv aircraft|first=Arnd|last=Wolf|date=March 16, 2002|work=[[Airliners.net]]|publisher=[[Demand Media]]|accessdate=December 29, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102221434/http://www.airliners.net/photo/Delta-Express/Boeing-737-232-Adv/0224180%26photo_nr%3D13%26prev_id%3D0230336%26next_id%3D0220519|archive-date=November 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The plane's inaugural flight was held at [[Logan International Airport]] in [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]], on July 17, 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Delta Express 737 Gets Animated Escort From Cartoon Network's THE POWERPUFF GIRLS|url=http://www.timewarner.com/newsroom/press-releases/2000/07/Delta_Express_737_Gets_Animated_Escort_From_Cartoon_07-17-2000.php|date=July 17, 2000|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|accessdate=December 29, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608035422/http://www.timewarner.com/newsroom/press-releases/2000/07/Delta_Express_737_Gets_Animated_Escort_From_Cartoon_07-17-2000.php|archive-date=June 8, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2002 the aircraft was repainted with a different ''Powerpuff Girls'' theme to promote ''[[The Powerpuff Girls Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Delta Express and Cartoon Network Celebrate 'The Powerpuff Girls Movie'|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/delta-express-and-cartoon-network-celebrate-the-powerpuff-girls-movie-77978017.html|date=June 25, 2002|work=[[PR Newswire]]|publisher=[[United Business Media]]|accessdate=December 29, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606093611/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/delta-express-and-cartoon-network-celebrate-the-powerpuff-girls-movie-77978017.html|archive-date=June 6, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Powerpuff Girls'' series has won two Primetime Emmys, two Annie Awards, and including those four wins, has been nominated a total of sixteen times for various awards.\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Nominee(s) !! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1999 || rowspan=\"3\"|[[Annie Awards]] || Outstanding Individual Achievement for Production Design in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a99\"/> || Craig Kellman {{small|(for \"Uh Oh Dynamo\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Individual Achievement for Directing in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a99\"/> || [[John McIntyre (cartoonist)|John McIntyre]] {{small|(for \"Mommie Fearest\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Individual Achievement for Voice Acting in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a99\"/> || [[Tara Charendoff|Tara Strong]] ({{small|as Bubbles)}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmys]] || Outstanding Achievement in Animation<ref>{{cite news|author=Variety Staff|title=Primetime Emmy noms&nbsp;\u2013 List 1|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|at=Section: ANIMATED PROGRAM (For programming one hour or less.)|publisher=Reed Business Information|date=July 22, 1999|url=https://variety.com/1999/tv/news/primetime-emmy-noms-list-1-1117744103/|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116145625/http://variety.com/1999/tv/news/primetime-emmy-noms-list-1-1117744103/|archive-date=January 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[Craig McCracken]], John McIntyre, [[Amy Keating Rogers]], [[Jason Butler Rote]], and [[Genndy Tartakovsky]] {{small|(for \"Bubblevicious/The Bare Facts\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2000 || Annie Awards || Outstanding Individual Achievement for Writing in an Animated Television Production<ref>{{cite web|title=28th Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (2000)|url=http://annieawards.org/28th-annie-awards|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=ASIFA-Hollywood|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425062300/http://annieawards.org/28th-annie-awards|archive-date=April 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[Chris Savino]] {{small|(for \"Dream Scheme\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Primetime Emmys || Outstanding Individual Achievement in Animation<ref name=\"emmys\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/powerpuff-girls|title=The Powerpuff Girls|work=[[Emmys.com]]|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013011916/http://www.emmys.com/shows/powerpuff-girls|archive-date=October 13, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> || Don Shank {{small|(for \"Twisted Sister/Cover Up\")}} || {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Animated Program (For Programming One Hour or Less)<ref name=\"emmys\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=52nd Annual Primetime Emmy Award Nominations|url=http://www.digitalhit.com/emmy/52/52noms.shtml|work=DigitalHit.com|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927021405/http://www.digitalhit.com/emmy/52/52noms.shtml|archive-date=September 27, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[Robert Alvarez]], Craig McCracken, John McIntyre, [[Randy Myers (animator)|Randy Myers]], Amy Keating Rogers, and Genndy Tartakovsky {{small|(for \"Beat Your Greens/Down 'N Dirty\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|2001 || rowspan=\"2\"|Annie Awards || Outstanding Individual Achievement for Music Score an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a01\">{{cite web|title=29th Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (2001)|url=http://annieawards.org/29th-annie-awards|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=ASIFA-Hollywood|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102052242/http://annieawards.org/29th-annie-awards|archive-date=January 2, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[James L. Venable]], Thomas Chase, and [[Stephen Rucker|Steve Rucker]] {{small|(for \"Meet the Beat Alls\")}} || {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Individual Achievement for Production Design in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a01\"/> || Don Shank || {{won}}\n|-\n| Primetime Emmys || Outstanding Animated Program (For Programming Less Than One Hour)<ref name=\"emmys\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Variety Staff |title=Emmy 2001 nomination list |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |page=Section: ANIMATED PROGRAM (For programming less than one hour) |publisher=Reed Business Information |date=July 12, 2001 |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117802665?refCatId=14 |accessdate=May 27, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111203305/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117802665?refCatId=14 |archivedate=November 11, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> || Robert Alvarez, [[Lauren Faust]], Craig McCracken, John McIntyre, Amy Rogers, and Genndy Tartakovsky {{small|(for \"Moral Decay/Meet the Beat Alls\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Kids' Choice Awards]] || Favorite Cartoon<ref>{{cite news|title=Nickelodeon Presents Kids Choice Awards|first=Donald|last=Liebenson|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2001-04-15/news/0104150411_1_billy-elliot-stephen-daldry-kids-choice-awards|date=April 15, 2001|work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930014634/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2001-04-15/news/0104150411_1_billy-elliot-stephen-daldry-kids-choice-awards|archive-date=September 30, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> || ''The Powerpuff Girls'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2002 || rowspan=\"2\"|Annie Awards || Outstanding Character Design in an Animated Television Production<ref>{{cite web|title=30th Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (2002)|url=http://annieawards.org/30th-annie-awards|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=ASIFA-Hollywood|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209203325/http://annieawards.org/30th-annie-awards|archive-date=February 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[Paul Rudish]] {{small|(for \"Members Only\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2003 || Outstanding Character Design in an Animated Television Production<ref>{{cite web|title=31st Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (2003)|url=http://annieawards.org/31st-annie-awards|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=ASIFA-Hollywood|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701220856/http://annieawards.org/31st-annie-awards|archive-date=July 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[Andy Bialk]] {{small|(for \"Save Mojo\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2004 || Annie Awards || Character Design in an Animated Television Production<ref>{{cite web|title=32nd Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (2004) |url=http://annieawards.org/32nd-annie-awards |work=AnnieAwards.org |publisher=ASIFA-Hollywood |accessdate=May 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214053223/http://annieawards.org/32nd-annie-awards |archivedate=February 14, 2014 }}</ref> || [[Chris Reccardi]] {{small|(for \"West in Pieces\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Primetime Emmys || Outstanding Animated Program (For Programming One Hour Or More)<ref>{{cite news|title=Complete list of primetime Emmy nominations|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/televisionawards/emmys/2004-07-15-nominees-complete-list_x.htm|date=July 15, 2004|work=USA Today|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023022540/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/televisionawards/emmys/2004-07-15-nominees-complete-list_x.htm|archive-date=October 23, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/powerpuff-girls-twas-fight-christm|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Twas The Fight Before Christm|work=Emmys.com|publisher=Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|accessdate=April 15, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013011902/http://www.emmys.com/shows/powerpuff-girls-twas-fight-christm|archive-date=October 13, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> || Robert Alvarez, Lauren Faust, et al. {{small|(for \"'Twas the Fight Before Christmas\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2005 || Outstanding Individual Achievement in Animation<ref name=\"emmys\"/> || Frank Gardner {{small|(for \"West in Pieces\")}} || {{won}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|1=Cartoon Network|3=Cartoon Cartoons}}\n* [[List of female action heroes]]\n{{Portal bar|United States|Cartoon|Comics|Anime and manga|Cartoon Network|Speculative fiction|Television|Video games|1990s}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"CN Featured Episodes\">{{cite web|url=http://cartoonnetwork.com/doc/ppg/fe.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001202235600/http://cartoonnetwork.com/doc/ppg/fe.html|archivedate=December 2, 2000|title=The Powerpuff Girls Featured Episodes|publisher=CartoonNetwork.com|accessdate=January 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CN\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140218034614/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/ppg/characters/index.html|archivedate=February 18, 2014|url=http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/ppg/characters/index.html|title=Powerpuff Girls Characters|work=Cartoon network.com|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Final airdate\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/73226-Octi_Gone.html|title=Octi-Gone (2005) The Powerpuff Girls Cartoon Episode Guide|work=The Big Cartoon DataBase|accessdate=April 11, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140412012212/http://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/73226-Octi_Gone.html|archivedate=April 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"a99\">{{cite web|title=27th Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (1999)|url=http://annieawards.org/27th-annie-awards|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=[[ASIFA-Hollywood]]|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140401040333/http://annieawards.org/27th-annie-awards|archive-date=April 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote-inline|The Powerpuff Girls}}\n* {{bcdb|Hanna-Barbera_Studios/P-R/The_Powerpuff_Girls/index.html}}\n* {{IMDb title|0175058}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{The Powerpuff Girls}}\n{{Craig McCracken}}\n{{Cartoon Network original programming}}\n{{Toonami-anime}}\n}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Powerpuff Girls, The}}\n[[Category:The Powerpuff Girls| ]]\n[[Category:1990s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American superhero comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1998 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American superhero comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2005 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated action television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated drama television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated superhero television series]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about families]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about sisters]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network Studios series and characters]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Cartoons]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Craig McCracken]]\n[[Category:Television series by Hanna-Barbera]]\n[[Category:Toonami]]\n[[Category:Annie Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the original 1998 TV series|other uses|The Powerpuff Girls (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|American superhero animated television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n|image = The Powerpuff Girls logo.svg\n|image_alt = Pink letters reading \"The Powerpuff Girls\" against a black background.\n|caption = <!-- An image of the title card including the title logo, or the logo only, of the show does not need a caption -->\n|genre = [[Superhero fiction|Superhero]]<br />Action [[Adventure fiction|adventure]]\n|creator = [[Craig McCracken]]\n|writer = {{unbulleted list|Craig McCracken|[[Jason Butler Rote]]|[[Amy Keating Rogers]]|[[Chris Savino]]}}\n|director = {{unbulleted list|Craig McCracken <small>(1998\u20132002)</small>|[[John McIntyre (cartoonist)|John McIntyre]] <small>(animation)</small>|[[Randy Myers (animator)|Randy Myers]] <small>(animation)</small>|[[Lauren Faust]] <small>(supervising)</small>|[[Genndy Tartakovsky]] <small>(recording)</small>|[[Robert Alvarez]] <small>(animation)</small>|[[Chris Savino]] <small>(2003\u201305)</small>|David Smith <small>(\"Dance Pantsed\")</small>}}\n|voices = {{unbulleted list|[[Cathy Cavadini]]|[[Tara Strong]]|[[E. G. Daily]]|[[Tom Kane]]|[[Tom Kenny]]|[[Roger L. Jackson]]|[[Jennifer Hale]]|[[Jeff Bennett]]|Jennifer Martin|[[Jim Cummings]]}}\n|narrated = Tom Kenny\n|theme_music_composer = {{unbulleted list|Thomas Chase|[[Stephen Rucker|Steve Rucker]]|[[James L. Venable]]}}\n|opentheme = \"The Powerpuff Girls (Main Theme)\"\n|endtheme = \"The Powerpuff Girls (End Theme)\", <br />{{small|performed by [[Bis (Scottish band)|Bis]]}}\n|composer = {{unbulleted list|Thomas Chase|Steve Rucker|James L. Venable}}\n|country = United States\n|language = English\n|channel = [[Cartoon Network]]<!--Do not place foreign networks/channels here.-->\n|executive_producer = Craig McCracken\n|producer = {{unbulleted list|Chris Savino <small>(seasons 5\u20136)</small>|Genndy Tartakovsky <small><br />(supervising producer, seasons 1\u20134)</small>}}\n|company = {{unbulleted list|[[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Cartoons]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Powerpuff Girls Episode Guide -Hanna-Barbera|url=http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/P-R/The_Powerpuff_Girls/|work=[[The Big Cartoon DataBase]]|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20150501001713/http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/P-R/The_Powerpuff_Girls/|archivedate=May 1, 2015}}</ref> <!-- Do Not add Hanna-Barbera without a reliable source confirming this, otherwise it is considered questionable information--> <small><br />(1998\u20132002)</small>|[[Cartoon Network Studios]] <small><br />(2003\u201305)</small>}}\n|distributor = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n|num_seasons = 6\n|num_episodes = 78 (whole)<br />136 (segments)\n|list_episodes= List of The Powerpuff Girls episodes\n|runtime = 11 minutes (short-length episodes)<br>22 minutes (specials)<br>44 minutes (\"'Twas the Fight Before Christmas\")\n|audio_format = {{unbulleted list|[[Monoaural|Mono]] <small>(1998\u20132000)</small>|[[Dolby Surround]] <small>(2000\u201302)</small>|[[Dolby Digital]] 5.1 <small>(2003\u201305)</small>}}\n|picture_format = {{unbulleted list|[[4:3]] [[SDTV]]|[[16:9]] [[HDTV]] <small>(specials)</small>}}\n|first_aired = {{Start date|1998|11|18}}<ref name=\"CN Featured Episodes\"/>\n|last_aired = {{End date|2005|3|25}}<ref name=\"CN Featured Episodes\"/><ref name=\"Final airdate\"/><!--This article is about the ORIGINAL 1998\u2013 2005 series, the new series of the same name has its own separate article. Don't include post-2005 specials either.-->\n|related = ''[[Powerpuff Girls Z]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv-tokyo.co.jp/anime/ppgz/|title=Powerpuff Girls Z|work=tv-tokyo.co.jp|language=Japanese|accessdate=February 3, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20121204170224/http://www.tv-tokyo.co.jp/anime/ppgz/|archivedate=December 4, 2012}}</ref>''<br />''[[What a Cartoon!]]<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/>''<br />[[The Powerpuff Girls (2016 TV series)|''The Powerpuff Girls'']] (2016)\n|website =https://archive.today/20150125075015/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/games/ppg/index.html\n}}\n'''''The Powerpuff Girls''''' is an American [[Superhero fiction|superhero]] [[List of animated television series|animated television series]] created by animator [[Craig McCracken]] for [[Cartoon Network]] and the fifth of the network's [[Cartoon Cartoons]] brand. The series was produced by [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]] in its first four seasons, and by [[Cartoon Network Studios]] in its final two seasons. It centers on Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup, three [[kindergarten]]-aged girls with [[Superpower (ability)|superpowers]]. The girls all live in the fictional city of Townsville with their father and creator, a scientist named Professor Utonium, and are frequently called upon by the city's mayor to help fight nearby criminals and other enemies using their powers.\n\nMcCracken originally developed the show in 1992 as a cartoon short entitled Whoopass Stew! while in his second year at [[California Institute of the Arts|CalArts]]. Following a name change, Cartoon Network featured the first Powerpuff Girls pilots in its animation showcase program [[What a Cartoon!]] in 1995 and 1996. The series premiered on November 18, 1998 and ended on March 25, 2005. Excluding the two pilot shorts, the series ran for a total of six seasons, totaling 78 episodes. In addition, a [[The Powerpuff Girls Movie|feature film]] was released in July 2002 and a Christmas special aired in December 2003. Two additional specials were made: a tenth-anniversary special , aired in 2008, and a [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] special, aired in 2014, the latter of which was made without McCracken's input.\n\nVarious spin-off media include an [[Powerpuff Girls Z|anime]], three CD soundtracks, a home video collection, comic books, a [[List of The Powerpuff Girls video games|series of video games]], a [[The Powerpuff Girls (2016 TV series)|2016 reboot series]], as well as various licensed merchandise. The series has been nominated for six [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Awards]], nine [[Annie Award]]s, and a [[Kids' Choice Award]] during its run.\n\nIt was the last cartoon produced in [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Studios]], which was closed in [[2001]] after [[William Hanna]]'s death.\n\n==Premise==\nThe show revolves around the adventures of three kindergarten aged girls with an array of various [[Superpower (ability)|superpowers]]: Blossom (pink), Bubbles (blue), and Buttercup (green). The plot of an episode is usually some humorous variation of standard [[superhero]] and [[tokusatsu]] shows, with the girls using their powers to defend their town from [[villain]]s and giant [[monster movie|monsters]]. In addition, the girls have to deal with the normal issues that young children face, such as sibling rivalries, loose teeth,<ref>{{cite episode|title=Moral Decay|series=The Powerpuff Girls|network=Cartoon Network|date=February 9, 2001|season=3|number=12A}}</ref> personal hygiene,<ref>{{cite episode|title=Down 'n' Dirty|series=The Powerpuff Girls|network=Cartoon Network|date=September 10, 1999|season=2|number=5B}}</ref> going to school, [[Nocturnal enuresis|bed wetting]],<ref>{{cite episode|title=Pee Pee G's|series=The Powerpuff Girls|network=Cartoon Network|date=November 13, 2003|season=5|number=6A}}</ref> or dependence on a [[security blanket]].<ref>{{cite episode|title=Cover Up|series=The Powerpuff Girls|network=Cartoon Network|date=May 26, 2000|season=2|number=11B}}</ref> Episodes often contain hidden references to older pop culture (especially noticeable in the episode \"Meet the Beat Alls\",<ref>{{cite episode|title=Meet the Beat-Alls|series=The Powerpuff Girls|network=Cartoon Network|date=February 9, 2001|season=3|number=12B}}</ref> which is a homage to [[the Beatles]]). The cartoon always tries to keep different ideas within each episode with some small tributes and [[Running gag|parodies thrown in.]]<ref name=\"autogenerated2001\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,98235,00.html|title='Power' Hungry|first=Mike|last=Flaherty|date=February 8, 2001|work=EW.com|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=May 28, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021144559/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,98235,00.html|archivedate=October 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe show is set mainly in the city of Townsville, USA. Townsville is depicted as a major American city, with a cityscape consisting of several major skyscrapers. In his review of ''[[The Powerpuff Girls Movie]]'', movie critic Bob Longino of ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' said, \"the intricate drawings emanate 1950s futuristic pizzazz like a [[David Hockney]] scenescape,\" and that the show is \"one of the few American creations that is both gleeful pop culture and exquisite high art.\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Powerpuff Girls Movie|first=Bob|last=Longino|url=http://mo.accessatlanta.com/movies/content/shared/movies/reviews/P/thepowerpuffgirlsmovie.html|journal=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|accessdate=May 27, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116094053/http://mo.accessatlanta.com/movies/content/shared/movies/reviews/P/thepowerpuffgirlsmovie.html|archivedate=January 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\n{{See also|List of The Powerpuff Girls characters}}\n<!-- Please stick to a simple description format and incorporate analyzes of character traits only if they appear in reliable third party publications, any unsourced original research will be removed. -->\n[[File:Powerpuff girls characters.jpg|thumb|left|270px|alt=The Powerpuff Girls&nbsp;\u2013 Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup|The Powerpuff Girls: Bubbles (left), Blossom (middle), and Buttercup (right)|alt=The Powerpuff Girls&nbsp;\u2013 Blossom, and Buttercup]]\nAs depicted in the opening sequence of each episode, the Powerpuff Girls [[Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup]] were created by Professor Utonium in an attempt to create the \"perfect little girl\" using a mixture of \"[[What Are Little Boys Made Of?|sugar, spice, and everything nice]]\". However, he accidentally spilled a mysterious substance called \"Chemical X\" into the mixture, creating three girls and granting all three superpowers including flight, [[Superhuman strength|super strength]], superhuman speed, near invulnerability, x-ray vision, superhuman senses, red heat vision, energy projection, invisibility, and control over lightning and fire. In the original pilot, the accidental substance was [[wikt:open a can of whoop ass|a can of \"Whoopass\"]], which was replaced by \"Chemical X\" in the aired version.<ref name=\"awn\"/>\n\nThe three girls all have oval-shaped heads, abnormally large eyes inspired by [[Margaret Keane]]'s art,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Craig McCracken on Stupid Dogs and Powerful Girls|first=Emru|last=Townsend|url=http://5x5media.com/eye/inte/cmccracken.php|date=Summer 1995|journal=Frames per Second Magazine|issue=6|accessdate=May 29, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810205143/http://5x5media.com/eye/inte/cmccracken.php|archivedate=August 10, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> flat feet and stubby arms and legs, and lack noses, ears, fingers, toes and necks. McCracken preferred them to look more animated rather than going for a \"realistic\" look, meaning fewer body parts were needed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Beyond Good and Evil: To the utterly adorable kicking superheroics of the Powerpuff Girls!|first=Robert|last=Lloyd|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2000-11-30/news/beyond-good-and-evil/4/|date=November 22, 2000|work=LA Weekly|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120906235656/http://www.laweekly.com/2000-11-30/news/beyond-good-and-evil/4/|archivedate=September 6, 2012}}</ref> Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup normally wear dresses that match the colors of their eyes with black stripes, as well as white tights and black [[Mary Jane (shoe)|Mary Janes]]. The closing theme to the cartoon offers a nutshell description of the three Powerpuff Girls' personalities: ''Blossom, commander and the leader. Bubbles, she is the joy and the laughter. Buttercup, she is the toughest fighter.''\n* Blossom (voiced by [[Cathy Cavadini]]) is the self-proclaimed leader of the Powerpuff Girls. Her personality ingredient is \"everything nice\", her signature color is pink, and she has long strawberry blonde hair with a red bow.<ref name=\"CN\"/><!--CN source describes her hair as \"fiery red\" not orange--> She was named for having spoken freely and honestly to the Professor shortly after her creation as shown in ''The Powerpuff Girls Movie''. She is often seen as the most level-headed, and composed member of the group and also strong and determined. Her unique abilities include \"Ice Breath\" (develops in \"Ice Sore\"), microscopic vision, and advanced intelligence; she is also a master strategist and apt planner.\n* Bubbles (voiced by [[Tara Strong]], credited as [[Tara Strong|Tara Charendoff]], in the series and by [[Kath Soucie]] in the What a Cartoon! episodes) is the \"softest and sweetest\" of the three.<ref name=\"CN\"/> Her signature color is blue, her personality ingredient is \"sugar\", and she has blonde hair in pigtails. Bubbles is seen as kind and very sweet but she is also capable of extreme rage and can fight monsters just as well as her sisters can. Her best friend is a stuffed octopus doll she calls \"Octi\", and she also loves animals. She exhibits the ability to both understand multiple languages and communicate with various animals, and her unique power is emitting supersonic waves.\n* Buttercup (voiced by [[E. G. Daily]]) is described as a \"tough hotheaded tomboy\".<ref name=\"CN\"/> Her personality ingredient is \"spice\", her signature color is green, and she has black hair in a flip. She loves to get dirty, fights hard and plays rough; she does not plan and is all action.<ref name=\"CN\"/> Buttercup is the only Powerpuff Girl without any unique superpowers (aside from being able to curl her tongue as shown in the episode \"Nuthin' Special\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-powerpuff-girls-2005/episode-15-season-6/nuthin-special/194523|title=Nuthin' Special Episode|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=May 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130306081804/http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-powerpuff-girls-2005/episode-15-season-6/nuthin-special/194523|archive-date=March 6, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> McCracken originally wanted to name the character \"Bud\" until a friend suggested the name Buttercup.<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/>\n\nTheir main arch-enemies throughout the show are a villain by the name of Mojo Jojo (voiced by [[Roger L. Jackson]]), a chimpanzee who always plans to take over Townsville (the character was inspired by a character from a live-action Japanese series), and Him (voiced by [[Tom Kane]]), a mysterious, sinister, and effeminate demon who is able to manipulate events to either drive the Powerpuff Girls insane or drive wedges between them.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of The Powerpuff Girls episodes}}\n{{:List of The Powerpuff Girls episodes}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Whoopass Stew - 1992.png|thumb|left|The first early animated versions of the Powerpuff Girls, who were originally known as the \"Whoopass Girls\"]]\nDuring Craig McCracken's first year in the character animation program of [[CalArts]],<ref>{{cite news|title=SIGNOFF; Never Underestimate the Power of a Puff|first=Daniel|last=Wineman|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/15/tv/signoff-never-underestimate-the-power-of-a-puff.html|date=November 15, 1998|work=The New York Times|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120908114308/http://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/15/tv/signoff-never-underestimate-the-power-of-a-puff.html|archivedate=September 8, 2012}}</ref> he created a series of short cartoons based on a character called \"No Neck Joe\".<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\">{{cite AV media|year=2009|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Who, What, Where, How, Why... Who Cares?}}</ref> In June 1991, he created a drawing of three girls with large eyes, inspired visually by the 'waif' paintings of [[Margaret Keane]],<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=385584741803511808  |user=CrackMcCraigen |title=_LaurenH_ Yes The Powerpuff Girls were inspired by Keane paintings and yes Ms. Keane is named after Margaret. Good catch! |author=Craig McCracken |date=2013-10-03}}</ref> on a small sheet of orange construction paper as a [[birthday card]] design for his brother.<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deviantart.com/cmcc/art/1st-PPG-Drawing-75162491|title=1st PPG Drawing|first=Craig|last=McCracken|date=January 20, 2008|work=CMcC's DeviantArt Gallery|accessdate=May 31, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118094844/https://www.deviantart.com/cmcc/art/1st-PPG-Drawing-75162491|archivedate=November 18, 2018}}</ref> The following year he included the three girls as the main characters of his short film ''Whoopass Stew! The Whoopass Girls in: A Sticky Situation''.<ref name=\"lenburg\">{{cite book|title=Who's Who in Animated Cartoons: An International Guide to Film & Television's Award-winning and Legendary Animators|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|year=2006|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|isbn=978-1-55783-671-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/231 231]|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb|url-access=registration|quote=tartakovsky calarts.|accessdate=May 31, 2011}}</ref> Initially, McCracken wanted to animate four ''Whoopass Girls'' shorts, but only one came to be.<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/> McCracken's shorts were selected to be shown at [[Spike and Mike's Festival of Animation|Spike and Mike's Sick and Twisted Festival of Animation]] in 1994.<ref name=\"lenburg\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Spike and Mike's&nbsp;\u2013 A Brief History |url=http://spikeandmike.com/sitepages/press.php |work=SpikeandMike.com |date=July 3, 2011 |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703084323/http://spikeandmike.com/sitepages/press.php |archivedate=July 3, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Craig_and_Lauren_in_08.jpg|thumb|right|''The Powerpuff Girls'' was created by [[Craig McCracken]], and his wife [[Lauren Faust]] was a director and writer for the later seasons.]]\nWhile working on ''[[2 Stupid Dogs]]'' in 1992, McCracken's ''Whoopass Girls'' short was picked up for a series by Cartoon Network. However, the name ''Whoopass'' had to be dropped for the channel to include it as part of its new ''[[What a Cartoon!]]'' animated shorts showcase. McCracken explained it was because many executives at Cartoon Network didn't think that anyone would make toys for kids with the word \"ass\" in it. So the title was changed and became ''The Powerpuff Girls'', the name Whoopass was also changed to Powerpuff by Craig McCracken, and the \"can of whoop ass\" was renamed \"Chemical X\".<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/> McCracken's new short, entitled \"The Powerpuff Girls in: Meat Fuzzy Lumpkins\", aired as part the network's ''World Premiere Toon-In'' on February 20, 1995.<ref name=\"apcm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/ap/cmccracken.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310030357/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/ap/cmccracken.html|archivedate=March 10, 2007|title=Animator Profile: CRAIG McCRACKEN|work=CartoonNetwork.com|accessdate=March 26, 2007}}</ref> The short was not as popular as ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'', a project McCracken and former classmate [[Genndy Tartakovsky]] (who also directed many episodes of ''Powerpuff Girls'') worked on together; being the most popular of the shorts, ''Dexter's Laboratory'' was the first to be greenlit by the network.<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/><ref>{{cite news|title='Star Wars' goes animated tonight|first=Mike|last=Snider|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2003-11-06-animated-star-wars_x.htm|date=November 6, 2003|work=USA Today|accessdate=May 28, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130428103917/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2003-11-06-animated-star-wars_x.htm|archivedate=April 28, 2013}}</ref> Cartoon Network executive [[Mike Lazzo]] (who later serve as the executive producer for [[Williams Street]] in the [[Samurai Jack (season 5)|fifth season]] of ''[[Samurai Jack]]'') allowed McCracken to produce a new ''Powerpuff Girls'' short titled \"Crime 101\", which aired on ''What a Cartoon!'' in early 1996. Announcer [[Ernie Anderson]], the narrator of the pilot episodes, died of cancer in 1997, and he was replaced by [[Tom Kenny]] for the remainder of the series.<ref>{{cite news|title=TV's Ghoulardi was 'a wild man'|first=Christopher|last=Borrelli|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3mNPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gwMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1305,2621618&dq=ernie+anderson+death&hl=en|date=February 8, 1997|work=The Toledo Blade|accessdate=May 29, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312044938/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3mNPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gwMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1305,2621618&dq=ernie+anderson+death&hl=en|archive-date=March 12, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Powerpuff Girls'' series made its debut on November 18, 1998, and was the highest rated premiere in Cartoon Network's history at the time. During its run, the series consistently scored the highest rating for an original series each week for the network across a wide range of demographics\u2014from young children to adults.<ref name=\"awn\">{{cite journal|first=Rick|last=DeMott|date=October 2000|title=The Powerpuff Girls' Phenomenal Merchandising Mantra|journal=Animation World Magazine|volume=5|issue=7|publisher=Animation World Network|accessdate=May 26, 2011|url=http://www.awn.com/mag/issue5.07/5.07pages/demottppg.php3|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130102004513/http://www.awn.com/mag/issue5.07/5.07pages/demottppg.php3|archivedate=January 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,276431,00.html|title=Girl Power|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=June 16, 2000|accessdate=December 1, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20141117191107/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,276431,00.html|archivedate=November 17, 2014}}</ref> In October 2000, Cartoon Network credited the series for its Friday night prime time [[Ratings (broadcast)|ratings]] win among cable networks.<ref name=\"tw\">{{cite web|first=Laurie |last=Goldberg |url=http://www.timewarner.com/corp/newsroom/pr/0,20812,667918,00.html |date=October 11, 2001 |title=Cartoon Network Tops Weekly and Friday Prime Ratings for the Week of Oct. 2\u20138 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010539/http://www.timewarner.com/corp/newsroom/pr/0%2C20812%2C667918%2C00.html |archivedate=September 27, 2007 |publisher=Time Warner |accessdate=March 29, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> By the end of 2000, merchandising based on the series encompassed a whole variety of products, including T-shirts, toys, video games, lunchboxes, and dishware.<ref name=\"awn\"/> Concerning the show's success, Craig McCracken has stated, \"I thought it would get on Cartoon Network and college kids would watch it and there would be a few random T-shirts out there in the [[rave]] scene or in record shops. But I had no idea that it would take off to this extent.\"<ref name=\"awn\"/> <!-- Some mention needs to be made here about the movie and the change in animation style. ---> Following the series' fourth season, the closing of [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]] and the death of its executive [[William Hanna]] in 2001, McCracken left it to focus on his new animated series, ''[[Foster's Home for Imaginary Friends]]'', leaving [[Chris Savino]] to take his place while production of ''The Powerpuff Girls'' was moved to [[Cartoon Network Studios]].<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/> The show's last original run episode was on March 25, 2005; in all, six seasons were made.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altiusdirectory.com/Entertainment/cartoon-network-original-series.html|title=Cartoon Network Original Series|work=altiusdirectory.com|accessdate=May 21, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120718080334/http://www.altiusdirectory.com/Entertainment/cartoon-network-original-series.html|archivedate=July 18, 2012}}</ref> Cartoon Network had offered to give McCracken and Savino a seventh season of the series, but they believed six was enough, and that the series had run its course.<ref name=\"ppgdocumentary\"/> Much of the people who worked on the new seasons also worked on seasons 3 and 4 of ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'', but included other new crew members, such as [[Thurop Van Orman]], who then created ''[[The Marvelous Misadventures of Flapjack]]'' in 2008. \n\nAll of the original episodes were hand-drawn and produced at [[Rough Draft Studios]] in South Korea,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roughdraftstudios.com/press/press_20040115.html |title=Special Report: Animation |first=Ray |last=Richmond |date=January 15, 2004 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=January 15, 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310222309/http://www.roughdraftstudios.com/press/press_20040115.html |archivedate=March 10, 2008 }}</ref> except the ''What a Cartoon!'' shorts, with the first one being animated at Animal House in Japan and Shanghai Morning Sun Animation in China and the second being animated at Fil Cartoons in the Philippines. [[James L. Venable]], Thomas Chase, & [[Stephen Rucker]] composed the opening theme of the series, and Scottish band [[Bis (Scottish band)|Bis]] performed the ending theme song,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1425853/bis-lends-hand-powerpuff-girls.jhtml|title=Bis Lends A Hand To \"The Powerpuff Girls\"|date=November 5, 1998|work=MTV.com|publisher=MTV Networks|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130129045540/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1425853/bis-lends-hand-powerpuff-girls.jhtml|archivedate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> as played during the credits. The opening theme uses a sped-up drum break sample of \"[[Funky Drummer]]\" performed by [[Clyde Stubblefield]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Rabb|first=Johnny|title=Jungle/Drum 'n' Bass for the Acoustic Drum Set: A Guide to Applying Today's Electronic Music to the Drum Set|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=o6AUnTjzj3UC&pg=PA16&lpg=PA16&dq=Clyde+Stubblefield+powerpuff#v=onepage&q=Clyde%20Stubblefield%20powerpuff&f=false|publisher=Alfred Music Publishing|isbn=978-0-7579-9025-0|page=16|chapter=Contributing to the Future: An Interview with Clyde Stubblefield|date=November 1, 2001}}</ref>\n\n===Tenth anniversary special===\nIn August 2008, McCracken revealed on his [[DeviantArt]] account, as had been announced in that year's Comic Con, that he was working with Cartoon Network on a new half-hour ''Powerpuff Girls'' special to celebrate the series' tenth anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cmcc.deviantart.com/journal/I-m-back-236070911|title=I'm back|first=Craig|last=McCracken|date=August 9, 2008|work=CMcC's DeviantArt Journal|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120715154409/http://cmcc.deviantart.com/journal/I-m-back-236070911|archivedate=July 15, 2012}}</ref> The special, titled \"The Powerpuff Girls Rule!!!\", aired on the Pan-Euro Cartoon Network on November 29, 2008, on the Powerpuff Girls Birthday Marathon, and in the United States on January 19, 2009, as part of its 10th anniversary marathon. Unlike previous episodes in the series, the anniversary special was animated using [[Adobe Flash]] at Cartoon Network Studios.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coldhardflash.com/2009/01/powerpuff-girls-10th-anniversary-interview-with-creator-craig-mccracken.html|title=Powerpuff Girls 10th Anniversary Interview With Creator Craig McCracken|first=Aaron|last=Simpson|date=January 16, 2009|work=ColdHardFlash.com|accessdate=January 16, 2009|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120707195019/http://coldhardflash.com/2009/01/powerpuff-girls-10th-anniversary-interview-with-creator-craig-mccracken.html|archivedate=July 7, 2012}}</ref> In March 2012, the series returned to Cartoon Network in reruns on the revived block, [[Cartoon Planet]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Walton |first=Zach |title=Cartoon Network Brings Back The Classics With Cartoon Planet |url=http://www.webpronews.com/cartoon-network-brings-back-the-classics-with-cartoon-planet-2012-03 |date=March 29, 2012 |work=WebProNews |publisher=iEntry Network |accessdate=March 31, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918192456/http://www.webpronews.com/cartoon-network-brings-back-the-classics-with-cartoon-planet-2012-03 |archivedate=September 18, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===2014 special===\n[[File:PowerpuffgirlsCGI.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Powerpuff Girls in the 2014 special.]]\n\nOn January 28, 2013, a new [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] special titled ''Powerpuff Girls: Dance Pantsed'' was announced to premiere that year, though it was later delayed to January 20, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-girls-are-back-in-townsville-the-powerpuff-girls-save-the-world-before-bedtime-again-in-all-new-special-236028091.html|title=The Girls Are Back in Townsville! The Powerpuff Girls Save the World Before Bedtime Again in All-New Special|work=PR Newswire|date=December 16, 2013|accessdate=January 14, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140115002624/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-girls-are-back-in-townsville-the-powerpuff-girls-save-the-world-before-bedtime-again-in-all-new-special-236028091.html|archivedate=January 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=VIDEO: \"The Powerpuff Girls: Dance Pantsed\" Sneak Peak|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2014/01/07/video-the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed-sneak-peak|publisher=Crunchyroll|date=January 7, 2014|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> Former [[The Beatles|Beatle]] [[Ringo Starr]] promoted the special on Cartoon Network singing a new original song \"I Wish I Was a Powerpuff Girl\" with previews leading up to the airdate. Ringo also voiced a new character named [[Fibonacci sequence|Fibonacci Sequins]] in the episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2012/11/14/ringo-starr-voicing-powerpuff-girls-character-starting-work.html|title=Ringo Starr Voicing \"Powerpuff Girls\" Character, Starting Work on New CD|work=abcnewsradioonline.com|accessdate=December 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121219192818/http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2012/11/14/ringo-starr-voicing-powerpuff-girls-character-starting-work.html|archivedate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> The special was directed by Dave Smith, who directed episodes for the series in the past, and featured the original cast members reprising their roles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/341049/scitech/geeksandgaming/the-powerpuff-girls-return-in-cgi-in-January|title=The Powerpuff Girls return in CGI in January|author=Mikael Angelo Francisco|work=gmanetwork.com|date=December 23, 2013|accessdate=January 14, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140115004436/http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/341049/scitech/geeksandgaming/the-powerpuff-girls-return-in-cgi-in-january|archivedate=January 15, 2014}}</ref> This ''Powerpuff Girls ''special marked the first time that series creator [[Craig McCracken]] had no input.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/news/powerpuff-girls-return-to-cartoon-network-with-january-special|title='Powerpuff Girls' return to Cartoon Network with January special|work=hitfix.com|date=December 18, 2013|accessdate=December 22, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131222211208/http://www.hitfix.com/news/powerpuff-girls-return-to-cartoon-network-with-january-special|archivedate=December 22, 2013}}</ref> The episode's plot has Mojo Jojo kidnap Fibonacci along with an opera singer and a badger. The girls rescue all of them, and the Powerpuff Girls defeat Mojo yet again. Not deterred, he then goes on to invent an evil video game called \"Dance Pants R-EVILution\" (a parody of the video game ''[[Dance Dance Revolution]]'') to take over Townsville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/ringo-starr-joins-powerpuff-girls-special-20131220|title=Ringo Starr Joins 'Powerpuff Girls' Special|work=rollingstone.com|date=December 20, 2013|accessdate=December 22, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131222234111/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/ringo-starr-joins-powerpuff-girls-special-20131220|archivedate=December 22, 2013}}</ref> [[Common Sense Media]] gave the special 3/5 stars citing the \"tasteful update of the original animation style\" however recommends it for older kids around the age of 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Dance Pantsed|work=commonsensemedia.org|accessdate=January 22, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140122145637/http://m.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed|archivedate=January 22, 2014}}</ref> GON (Geeked Out Nation) gave the show a B rank and described it as \"...a good special with the return of the characters that many of us grew up [with]\", while they said that the special has few flaws.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geekedoutnation.com/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed-review|title=The Powerpuff Girls: \"Dance Pantsed\" Review|work=geekedoutnation.com|date=January 25, 2014|accessdate=April 29, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140428042645/http://www.geekedoutnation.com/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed-review|archivedate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> Den of Geek gave the special a 2.5 out 5 said \"The Powerpuff reboot needs those paddles to jump-start it. I want more. But I want better.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/the-powerpuff-girls/232317/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed-review|title=The Powerpuff Girls, Dance Pantsed, review|work=denofgeek.us|date=January 20, 2014|accessdate=April 29, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140428020050/http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/the-powerpuff-girls/232317/the-powerpuff-girls-dance-pantsed-review|archivedate=April 28, 2014}}</ref>\n<!--Please do NOT add the new re-boot info here, it is unrelated to the original series or its production.-->\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Merchandise and media==\n===Anime and manga===\n{{Main|Powerpuff Girls Z}}\nIn April 2005, plans for a Japanese [[anime]] version, ''Demashita! Powerpuff Girls Z'', were announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://omelete.uol.com.br/series-e-tv/meninas-superpoderosas-em-versao-anime/|title=Meninas Superpoderosas em vers\u00e3o anim\u00ea|first=Alexandre|last=Nagado|date=April 7, 2005|work=Omlete.com.br|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120914024457/http://omelete.uol.com.br/series-e-tv/meninas-superpoderosas-em-versao-anime/|archivedate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> The series premiered in Japan the following year with 52 half-hour episodes, airing each Saturday from July 1 to December 23, 2006, and from January 6 to June 30, 2007. The series deviated from its American predecessor in terms of style, storyline, and characterization, but only minimally retained the essential themes that made the original a success.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/culture/2006/07/10/powerpuff-girls-re-anime-ted/|title='Powerpuff Girls' re-anime-ted|first=Jason|last=Lloren|date=July 10, 2006|work=SFGate.com|publisher=Hearst Communications|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120911070300/http://blog.sfgate.com/culture/2006/07/10/powerpuff-girls-re-anime-ted/|archivedate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> The characters feature three junior high school students Momoko Akatsutsumi (Hyper Blossom), Miyako Gotokuji (Rolling Bubbles), and Kaoru Matsubara (Powered Buttercup) as the three heroes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetworkasia.com/minisite/ppgz/characters.php|title=PowerPuff Girls Z Characters|work=cartoonnetworkasia.com|accessdate=January 14, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116101146/http://www.cartoonnetworkasia.com/minisite/ppgz/characters.php|archivedate=January 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A [[manga]] adaptation, illustrated by Shiho Komiyuno, was serialized in [[Shueisha]]'s [[Ribon|''Ribon'' magazine]] between June 2006 and July 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ribon.shueisha.co.jp/|title=Ribon Magazine (In Japanese)|work=ribon.shueisha.co.jp|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140313225732/http://ribon.shueisha.co.jp/|archivedate=March 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\n{{Main|The Powerpuff Girls Movie}}\n''The Powerpuff Girls Movie'' was released in the United States on July 3, 2002 by [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]] and Cartoon Network.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,266671,00.html|title=Movie Review: The Powerpuff Girls Movie (2002)|first=Lisa|last=Schwarzbaum|date=July 2, 2002|work=EW.com|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130122133537/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,266671,00.html|archivedate=January 22, 2013}}</ref> The movie, a prequel to the series, tells the story of how the Powerpuff Girls were created, and how Mojo Jojo (voiced by: [[Roger L. Jackson]]) became a supervillain. After Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup were created by [[Professor Utonium]] to help the city against crime, they end up only causing chaos in Townsville. Down about how everyone refers to them as freaks, they turn to Mojo Jojo, a monkey who says he is there to help make people like them again. Unknown to the girls, Mojo Jojo was Professor Utonium's lab chimp helper who was mutated when the Powerpuff Girls were made. The mishap made him super smart, and he has become jealous of the girls. Mojo Jojo ends up tricking the girls into helping him make a machine to mutate other chimps. Seeing what they have done, the kids run away in shame, but come back after seeing Professor Utonium in trouble. Blossom, Bubbles and Buttercup end up beating Mojo Jojo and his army of mutated smart chimps and save the day, thus becoming Townsville's new defenders.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/03/movies/film-review-they-have-a-tantrum-then-save-the-world.html|title=FILM REVIEW; They Have A Tantrum, Then Save The World|first=Stephen|last=Holden|date=July 3, 2002|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130130144331/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/03/movies/film-review-they-have-a-tantrum-then-save-the-world.html|archivedate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> The movie received a rating of 63% at Rotten Tomatoes, and received some criticism for the violence involved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/powerpuff_girls_movie/|title=The Powerpuff Girls&nbsp;\u2013 The Movie (2002)|work=RottenTomatoes.com|accessdate=July 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120913174512/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/powerpuff_girls_movie/|archivedate=September 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/movies/article/Violence-overpowers-Powerpuff-Girls-1090464.php|first=Paula|last=Nechak|title=Violence overpowers 'Powerpuff Girls'|date=July 2, 2002|work=Seattlepi.com|publisher=Hearst Communications|accessdate=May 21, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120910030214/http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/movies/article/Violence-overpowers-Powerpuff-Girls-1090464.php|archivedate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> In all, the movie grossed $16 million worldwide with an $11 million budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=powerpuffgirls.htm|title=The Powerpuff Girls Movie|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120721182808/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=powerpuffgirls.htm|archivedate=July 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|List of The Powerpuff Girls soundtracks}}\nThree CD soundtracks were officially released for the series. The first, entitled ''Heroes & Villains'', features original songs about the ''Powerpuff Girls'' characters by a number of artists, including the [[New wave music|new wave]] group [[Devo]], [[Bis (Scottish band)|Bis]], [[The Apples in Stereo]] and [[Black Francis|Frank Black]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Powerpuff Girls Heroes & Villains&nbsp;\u2013 Powerpuff Girls: Heroes & Villains Soundtrack CD|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/1119004/a/Powerpuff+Girls%3A+Heroes+%26+Villains.htm|work=CDUniverse.com|accessdate=June 2, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120722190024/http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/1119004/a/Powerpuff+Girls:+Heroes+%26+Villains.htm|archivedate=July 22, 2012}}</ref> The first album did well, topping the ''[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]''{{'}}s children's music chart for six weeks.<ref name=\"autogenerated2001\"/> Another album entitled ''The City of Soundsville'' features electronica-style character themes and also did well with critics.<ref>{{cite web|title=Powerpuff Girls: The City of Soundsville&nbsp;\u2014 The Powerpuff Girls|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/the-powerpuff-girls/powerpuff-girls-the-city-of-soundsville/494900|work=Billboard.com|accessdate=May 27, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5oCpvZ3dV?url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/the-powerpuff-girls/powerpuff-girls-the-city-of-soundsville/494900|archive-date=March 13, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Heather|last=Phares|title=Review: ''Powerpuff Girls: The City of Soundsville&nbsp;\u2014 The Powerpuff Girls'' |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r550183/review|pure_url=yes}}|work=Allmusic.com|publisher=Rovi|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref> The third album, entitled ''Power Pop'', features a more teen-oriented variety of pop songs. This third and final album was considered a \"big disappointment\" and was not received as well as the previous albums.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-powerpuff-girls-power-pop-mw0000320918|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Power Pop Review|first=Heather|last=Phares|work=Allmusic.com|publisher=Rovi|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909210317/http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-powerpuff-girls-power-pop-mw0000320918|archive-date=September 9, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The British girl group [[Sugababes]] also released a song called \"[[Angels with Dirty Faces (Sugababes song)|Angels with Dirty Faces]]\" to promote ''[[The Powerpuff Girls Movie]].'' The song received generally positive reviews from critics, and peaked at number seven on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2002-11-23/|title=2002-11-23 Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive|work=[[UK Singles Chart]]|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=12 January 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130620195340/http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2002-11-23/|archivedate=June 20, 2013}}</ref>{{efn|\"Angels with Dirty Faces\" charted on the [[UK Singles Chart]] as part of its double A-side release with \"[[Stronger (Sugababes song)|Stronger]]\".<ref name=\"UK\"/>}} The music video hearkens to \"[[Nano of the North]]\", an episode from the fourth season of ''The Powerpuff Girls'',<ref name=\"Video\">{{cite video|people=[[Sugababes]]|year=2002|title=Angels with Dirty Faces|type = DVD|publisher=Island Records}}</ref> in which each Sugababes member portrays a Powerpuff Girl.<ref name=\"Video\"/>\n\n===Parodies and comics===\n\n<!--In 2003 a parody was done by [[MADtv]] in its [[MADtv (season 9)|ninth season]] called \"The Powerslut Girls\". The parody has [[Tara Reid]], [[Brittany Murphy]], and [[Paris Hilton]] as the superheroines.--> <!--Would love to add but I do not have reliable source for it-->\n\nA crossover parody of ''The Powerpuff Girls'' and ''[[2 Broke Girls]]'' was done in the second season of Cartoon Network's TV series ''[[Mad (TV series)|MAD]]'', known as \"2 Broke Powerpuff Girls\". The parody, which aired on January 30, 2012, is of Bubbles and Buttercup, who are broke and work for \"Him\" in a diner after the show got placed on permanent [[hiatus (television)|hiatus]]. [[Tara Strong]] (Bubbles) and [[Tom Kane]] (\"Him\") reprised their roles here.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Mad-Mash-Up-1042213.aspx|title=Mad Mash-up: 2 Broke Powerpuff Girls|work=Tvguide.com|accessdate=May 10, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130204220154/http://www.tvguide.com/News/Mad-Mash-Up-1042213.aspx|archivedate=February 4, 2013|date=January 26, 2012}}</ref> The ''MAD'' episode with the parody ranked #26/30 for the week with 1.903 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2012/02/01/mondays-cable-ratings-pawn-stars-leads-the-pack-once-again-568210/cable_20120130/#EY1Z6xL8rHr0bfr9.99|title=Monday's Cable Ratings: \"Pawn Stars\" Leads the Pack Once Again|author=The Futon Critic Staff|work=The Futon Critic|date=February 1, 2012|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130204003821/http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2012/02/01/mondays-cable-ratings-pawn-stars-leads-the-pack-once-again-568210/cable_20120130/%23EY1Z6xL8rHr0bfr9.99|archivedate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> In February 2013, [[IDW Publishing]] announced a partnership with Cartoon Network to produce comics based on its properties and this series was one of the titles announced to be published.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idwpublishing.com/news/article/2507/ |title=IDW Teams Up with Cartoon Network! |date=February 25, 2013 |publisher=IDW |accessdate=May 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140804051016/http://idwpublishing.com/news/article/2507 |archivedate=August 4, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nA fan-produced webcomic series called ''PowerPuff Girls [[Doujinshi]]'' was created in 2004 and released through [[Snafu Comics]]. The girls are shown to be a bit older, but with the same personalities as, their T.V. counterparts, and the comic includes many characters from other Cartoon Network shows. The story has the kids now going to school in a neighboring city of Townsville known as Megaville.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicbooked.com/webcomic-review-powerpuff-girls-doujinshi/|title=Webcomic Review: Powerpufff Girls Doujunshu|work=comicbooked.com|accessdate=May 12, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120910031221/http://www.comicbooked.com/webcomic-review-powerpuff-girls-doujinshi/|archivedate=September 10, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The comic was the \"Outstanding Superhero Comic\" and \"Outstanding Character Art\" winner on the [[Web Cartoonist's Choice Awards]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccawards.com/2005_ceremony.htm |title=2005 Web Cartoonists' Choice Award Celebration! |work=CCAwards.com |publisher=Web Cartoonist's Choice Awards Committee |accessdate=July 10, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708125905/http://www.ccawards.com/2005_ceremony.htm |archivedate=July 8, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nShortly after the 2014 CGI special's release, a comic which was published by [[IDW Publishing]] was withdrawn after retailers complained that they wanted to boycott the issue. The comic, which shows the Powerpuff Girls with [[breast]]s and dressed in [[Latex clothing|latex]], was designed by an artist who works for Cartoon Network. The artist was \"thinking of it more along the lines of 'female empowerment' than the kind of thing you guys are talking about\". Cartoon Network said in a statement: \"We recognise some fans' reaction to the cover and, as such, will no longer be releasing it at comic book shops.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jan/24/powerpuff-girls-sexualised-comic-withdrawn|title='Sexualised' Powerpuff Girls comic judged a boob by TV network|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=January 24, 2014|accessdate=February 15, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140216033429/http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jan/24/powerpuff-girls-sexualised-comic-withdrawn|archivedate=February 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Toys===\nFrom 1999\u20132002, [[Trendmasters]] made Powerpuff Girls dolls and action figures. From August 21 to October 1, 2000, [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway]] promoted the series with four toys in their [[kids' meal]]s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Subway Teams Up with Powerpuff Girls|url=http://www.qsrmagazine.com/news/subway-teams-powerpuff-girls|date=July 7, 2000|work=QSR Magazine|publisher=Journalistic|accessdate=August 8, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222202903/http://www.qsrmagazine.com/news/subway-teams-powerpuff-girls|archive-date=February 22, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> A set of six kids' meal toys was available as part of an April 2001 [[Dairy Queen]] promotion, which also included a sweepstakes offering the ''Powerpuff Girls'' VHS ''Boogie Frights''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dairy Queen|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Dairy+Queen.-a072467312|date=March 20, 2001|work=Ice Cream Reporter|accessdate=August 8, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130808232914/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Dairy+Queen.-a072467312|archivedate=August 8, 2013}}</ref> [[Jack in the Box]] released six ''Powerpuff Girls'' toys in July 2002 as a tie-in for ''The Powerpuff Girls Movie''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Powerpuff Girls Soar into Jack's|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Powerpuff+Girls+Soar+into+Jack%27s%3B+Crime-Fighting+Cuties+Team+Up+With...-a087912566|date=June 28, 2002|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|accessdate=August 8, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130809015238/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Powerpuff+Girls+Soar+into+Jack's;+Crime-Fighting+Cuties+Team+Up+With...-a087912566|archivedate=August 9, 2013}}</ref> On February 10, 2003, [[Burger King]] began a four-week promotion featuring ''The Powerpuff Girls'' and ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'' toys as well as special codes to redeem online for Cartoon Network's [[Cartoon Orbit]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Powerpuff Girls(TM) And Dragon Ball Z(R) Bring Three Exclusive Toys To Every Burger King(R) Big Kids Meal|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+Powerpuff+Girls%28TM%29+And+Dragon+Ball+Z%28R%29+Bring+Two+Exclusive+Toys...-a097428934|date=February 10, 2003|work=PR Newswire|publisher=United Business Media|accessdate=August 8, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130809015222/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+Powerpuff+Girls(TM)+And+Dragon+Ball+Z(R)+Bring+Two+Exclusive+Toys...-a097428934|archivedate=August 9, 2013}}</ref> In the United Kingdom the characters of Buttercup and Mojo Jojo were given away in [[Kelloggs]] cereal boxes as part of the Cartoon Network Wobble Heads in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|title=2003 - Frosties Cartoon Network Wobble Heads Free in Packets|url=http://cerealoffers.com/Kelloggs/Frosties/2000/Cartoon_Network_Wobble_Heads/cartoon_network_wobble_heads.html|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190622001621/http://cerealoffers.com/Kelloggs/Frosties/2000/Cartoon_Network_Wobble_Heads/cartoon_network_wobble_heads.html|archivedate=June 22, 2019}}</ref> In August 24, 2018, the 2 sets of LEGO had released in United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://brickset.com/article/36124/first-images-of-powerpuff-girls-sets |title=First images of Powerpuff Girls sets |publisher=Brickset |accessdate=2018-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://brickset.com/article/34355/powerpuff-girls-full-minifig-lineup-revealed |title=Powerpuff Girls: full minifig lineup revealed |publisher=Brickset |accessdate=2018-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://brickset.com/article/34316/powerpuff-girls-minifigs-revealed |title=Powerpuff Girls minifigs revealed |publisher=Brickset |accessdate=2018-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bricksfanz.com/first-look-at-lego-powerpuff-girls-sets/ |title=First Look At LEGO Powerpuff Girls Sets |publisher=Brickfanz |accessdate=2018-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bricksfanz.com/powerpuff-girls-lego-line-up-revealed/ |title=Powerpuff Girls LEGO Line-up Revealed |publisher=Brickfanz |accessdate=2018-02-16}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n{{Main|List of The Powerpuff Girls video games}}\nSeveral video games were made for this show all being action in genre. ''The Powerpuff Girls: Bad Mojo Jojo'', released on November 14, 2000, follows Blossom as she tries to beat Mojo Jojo.<ref>[[GameSpot]]. [http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo/techinfo/platform/gbc/ Tech Info for the Powerpuff Girls: Bad Mojo Jojo] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109061346/http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo/techinfo/platform/gbc/ |date=November 9, 2012 }}. [[GameSpot]]. Retrieved on February 1, 2008.</ref> The game was called \"simple and boring\" by [[GameSpot]] and was a failure critically.<ref name=GameSpot>Donald, Ryan Mac (December 4, 2000). [http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo/reviews/powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo-review-2660964/ The Powerpuff Girls: Bad Mojo Jojo Review] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109061420/http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo/reviews/powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo-review-2660964/ |date=November 9, 2012 }}. [[GameSpot]]. Retrieved on February 1, 2008.</ref><ref>Harris, Chris (December 1, 2000). [http://www.ign.com/articles/2000/12/02/powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo The Powerpuff Girls: Bad Mojo Jojo Review] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102115958/http://www.ign.com/articles/2000/12/02/powerpuff-girls-bad-mojo-jojo |date=November 2, 2012 }}. [[IGN]]. Retrieved on February 1, 2008.</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: Paint the Townsville Green'', another game released in November 2000, follows Buttercup as she fights crime.<ref>[http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-paint-the-townsville-green/gbc-16762 The Powerpuff Girls: Paint the Townsville Green] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102115944/http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-paint-the-townsville-green/gbc-16762 |date=November 2, 2012 }}. [[IGN]]. Retrieved on February 4, 2008.</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: Battle HIM'' follows Bubbles in her fight against HIM and was released in February 2001.<ref>[[GameSpot]]. [http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-battle-him/platform/gbc/ Tech Info for The Powerpuff Girls: Battle HIM] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109092537/http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-battle-him/platform/gbc/ |date=November 9, 2012 }}. [[GameSpot]]. Retrieved on June 26, 2011.</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: Chemical X-traction'' was released in October 2001, where the girls battle enemies in a variety of settings in order to reclaim Chemical X and track down Mojo Jojo, who fed the material to all the villains in Townsville. [[IGN]] gave the game a positive review while giving the [[PlayStation (console)|PSone]] version a 2.0/10 bad review.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-chemical-x-traction/n64-16829|title=The Powerpuff Girls-x-traction|website=IGN|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817015111/http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-chemical-x-traction/n64-16829|archive-date=August 17, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/11/30/power-puff-girls-chemical-x-traction IGN Reviews] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120115533/http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/11/30/power-puff-girls-chemical-x-traction |date=November 20, 2012 }} Powerpuff Girls: Chemical X-traction (PS1 version)</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: Relish Rampage'' was released in November 2002. All three girls are playable in a 3D world, and the game received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/ps2/561541-the-powerpuff-girls-relish-rampage/data|title=Release Information for PlayStation 2 on GameFAQs|work=[[GameFAQs]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=May 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102133803/http://www.gamefaqs.com/ps2/561541-the-powerpuff-girls-relish-rampage/data|archive-date=November 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: Mojo Jojo A-Go-Go'' released in 2001 centers around the name of the Powerpuff Girls' mission to stop Mojo Jojo and his minions. The game received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/01/25/powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go|title=Mojo-jojo-a-go-go review|website=IGN|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221125350/http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/01/25/powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go|archive-date=February 21, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go/reviews/powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go-review-2837304/|title=Mojo-jojo-a-go-go review (Gamestop)|work=www.gamespot.com|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926185651/http://www.gamespot.com/the-powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go/reviews/powerpuff-girls-mojo-jojo-a-go-go-review-2837304/|archive-date=September 26, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Powerpuff Girls: HIM and Seek'' was released in 2002 where the girls battle their variety of enemies through Townsville while on a scavenger hunt. The game received mostly positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.ign.com/articles/2002/12/09/powerpuff-girls-him-and-seek|title=HIM and Seek review from IGN Dec. 09, 2002|access-date=March 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308173118/http://m.ign.com/articles/2002/12/09/powerpuff-girls-him-and-seek|archive-date=March 8, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[PC games]] were also made for the series. These include: ''The Powerpuff Girls: Mojo Jojo Clone Zone'', ''The Powerpuff Girls: Princess Snorebucks'', ''The Powerpuff Girls: Mojo Jojo's Pet Project'', and ''The Powerpuff Girls: Gamesville''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcworld.idg.com.au/review/software_and_services/the_learning_company/the_powerpuff_girls_mojo_jojo_s_clone_zone/218756|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Mojo Jojo Clone Zone|work=www.pcworld.idg.com.au|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028184026/http://www.pcworld.idg.com.au/review/software_and_services/the_learning_company/the_powerpuff_girls_mojo_jojo_s_clone_zone/218756|archive-date=October 28, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-learning-challenge-2-princess-snorebucks/pc-854911|title=The Powerpuff Girls Learning Challenge 2: Princess Snorebucks|website=IGN|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109050531/http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-learning-challenge-2-princess-snorebucks/pc-854911|archive-date=November 9, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=36826|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Mojo Jojo's Pet Project|work=www.allgame.com|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424110216/http://allgame.com/game.php?id=36826|archive-date=April 24, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-gamesville/pc-491680|title=The Powerpuff Girls: Gamesville|website=IGN|accessdate=May 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816034729/http://www.ign.com/games/the-powerpuff-girls-gamesville/pc-491680|archive-date=August 16, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\nIn a 2000 ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' review, Marc Bernadin complimented the show on its \"spot-on pop-culture acumen\" and \"unparalleled sense of fun\", giving it a warm welcome from earlier \"lame\" superhero cartoons that he grew up with.<ref>{{cite news|title=TV on DVD Review: The Powerpuff Girls|first=Marc|last=Bernadin|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20232855,00.html|date=June 3, 2000|work=EW.com|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130122194831/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20232855,00.html|archivedate=January 22, 2013}}</ref> Peter Marks of ''[[The New York Times]]'' noted the show's use of adult humor and pop culture references, declaring it \"the sort of playful satire that can appeal as much to a viewer of 37 as 7.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=TELEVISION/RADIO; Now Mom and Dad Are Going Cartoon-Crazy, Too|first=Peter|last=Marks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/16/arts/television-radio-now-mom-and-dad-are-going-cartoon-crazy-too.html|date=April 16, 2000|work=The New York Times|accessdate=June 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130130122120/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/16/arts/television-radio-now-mom-and-dad-are-going-cartoon-crazy-too.html|archivedate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> Joly Herman of [[Common Sense Media]] describes the show as a \"cute, highly stylized series thrills the senses with its strange characters, funny situations, and lots of lowbrow humor\". She goes on to say, however, that the show does go from innocent to violent in no time and that there is not much protecting young viewers against the violent undertones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls|title=Tv reviews Powerpuff Girls|first=Joly|last=Herman|work=[[Common Sense Media]]|accessdate=May 15, 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120723133202/http://www.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/the-powerpuff-girls|archivedate=July 23, 2012|date=May 25, 2007}}</ref> Robert Lloyd of the ''[[Los Angeles Times|LA Times]]'' said that the series might be \"[[transgressive art|transgressive]]\" based on little violence but \"also cute.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Review: 'Powerpuff Girls Rule!!!'|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/01/review-powerpuf.html|date=January 19, 2009|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=May 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429180731/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/01/review-powerpuf.html|archive-date=April 29, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[TV Guide]] chose the Powerpuff Girls as No. 13 in a list of the 50 Greatest cartoon characters of all time.<ref>{{cite news|title=TV Guide's 50 greatest cartoon characters of all time |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2002-07-30/entertainment/cartoon.characters.list_1_ren-and-stimpy-tv-guide-space-ghost?_s=PM:SHOWBIZ |date=July 30, 2002 |work=CNN |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008180927/http://articles.cnn.com/2002-07-30/entertainment/cartoon.characters.list_1_ren-and-stimpy-tv-guide-space-ghost?_s=PM%3ASHOWBIZ |archivedate=October 8, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[IGN]] ranked the series 18th in its Top 25 Primetime Animated Series of All Time list in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/29/top-25-primetime-animated-series-of-all-time?page=2|title=Top 25 Primetime Animated Series of All Time|date=September 28, 2006|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=January 27, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314072017/http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/29/top-25-primetime-animated-series-of-all-time?page=2|archive-date=March 14, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Delta Express]] promoted the series by having a [[Boeing 737-200]] jet painted with a special [[Aircraft livery|livery]] featuring the characters Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup on its exterior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airliners.net/photo/Delta-Express/Boeing-737-232-Adv/0224180&photo_nr=13&prev_id=0230336&next_id=0220519|title=Picture of the Boeing 737-232/Adv aircraft|first=Arnd|last=Wolf|date=March 16, 2002|work=[[Airliners.net]]|publisher=[[Demand Media]]|accessdate=December 29, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102221434/http://www.airliners.net/photo/Delta-Express/Boeing-737-232-Adv/0224180%26photo_nr%3D13%26prev_id%3D0230336%26next_id%3D0220519|archive-date=November 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The plane's inaugural flight was held at [[Logan International Airport]] in [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]], on July 17, 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Delta Express 737 Gets Animated Escort From Cartoon Network's THE POWERPUFF GIRLS|url=http://www.timewarner.com/newsroom/press-releases/2000/07/Delta_Express_737_Gets_Animated_Escort_From_Cartoon_07-17-2000.php|date=July 17, 2000|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|accessdate=December 29, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608035422/http://www.timewarner.com/newsroom/press-releases/2000/07/Delta_Express_737_Gets_Animated_Escort_From_Cartoon_07-17-2000.php|archive-date=June 8, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2002 the aircraft was repainted with a different ''Powerpuff Girls'' theme to promote ''[[The Powerpuff Girls Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Delta Express and Cartoon Network Celebrate 'The Powerpuff Girls Movie'|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/delta-express-and-cartoon-network-celebrate-the-powerpuff-girls-movie-77978017.html|date=June 25, 2002|work=[[PR Newswire]]|publisher=[[United Business Media]]|accessdate=December 29, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606093611/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/delta-express-and-cartoon-network-celebrate-the-powerpuff-girls-movie-77978017.html|archive-date=June 6, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Powerpuff Girls'' series has won two Primetime Emmys, two Annie Awards, and including those four wins, has been nominated a total of sixteen times for various awards.\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Nominee(s) !! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1999 || rowspan=\"3\"|[[Annie Awards]] || Outstanding Individual Achievement for Production Design in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a99\"/> || Craig Kellman {{small|(for \"Uh Oh Dynamo\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Individual Achievement for Directing in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a99\"/> || [[John McIntyre (cartoonist)|John McIntyre]] {{small|(for \"Mommie Fearest\")}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Individual Achievement for Voice Acting in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a99\"/> || [[Tara Charendoff|Tara Strong]] ({{small|as Bubbles)}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmys]] || Outstanding Achievement in Animation<ref>{{cite news|author=Variety Staff|title=Primetime Emmy noms&nbsp;\u2013 List 1|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|at=Section: ANIMATED PROGRAM (For programming one hour or less.)|publisher=Reed Business Information|date=July 22, 1999|url=https://variety.com/1999/tv/news/primetime-emmy-noms-list-1-1117744103/|accessdate=May 27, 2011|a